ef>{{cite web|title=Registered Foreigners in Japan by Nationality|url=http://www.stat.go.jp/data/nenkan/pdf/y0213014.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050824195238/http://www.stat.go.jp/data/nenkan/pdf/y0213014.pdf|archivedate=24 August 2005|publisher=Statistics Bureau|accessdate=7 November 2011}}</ref>\n|region5    = {{flagcountry|United Kingdom}}\n|pop5       = ''[[Latin American migration to the United Kingdom|186,500]]''<ref name=\"TfL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.trustforlondon.org.uk/No%20Longer%20Invisible%20report.pdf|title=No Longer Invisible: The Latin American community in London|publisher=Trust for London|accessdate=19 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321090718/http://www.trustforlondon.org.uk/No%20Longer%20Invisible%20report.pdf|archivedate=21 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|region6    = {{flagcountry|Portugal}}\n|pop6       = ''[[Immigration to Portugal|~100,000]]''<ref>[http://www.sef.pt/documentos/56/DADOS_2007.pdf POPULA\u00c7\u00c3O ESTRANGEIRA EM TERRIT\u00d3RIO NACIONAL, SERVI\u00c7O DE ESTRANGEIROS E FRONTEIRAS] 2008;</ref>\n|region7    = {{flagcountry|Australia}}\n|pop7       = ''[[Latin American Australians|93,795]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusdata.abs.gov.au/ABSNavigation/prenav/ViewData?breadcrumb=POLTD&method=Place%20of%20Usual%20Residence&subaction=-1&issue=2006&producttype=Census%20Tables&documentproductno=0&textversion=false&documenttype=Details&collection=Census&javascript=true&topic=Ancestry&action=404&productlabel=Ancestry%20(full%20classification%20list)%20by%20Sex&order=1&period=2006&tabname=Details&areacode=0&navmapdisplayed=true&|title=Redirect to Census data page|work=abs.gov.au|accessdate=22 September 2015}}</ref>\n|region9    = {{flagcountry|The Netherlands}}\n|pop9       = ''113.282''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://opendata.cbs.nl/statline/#/CBS/nl/dataset/37325/table?dl=2779A|work=[[Centraal Bureau voor de Statistiek]]|title=Bevolking; geslacht, leeftijd, generatie en migratieachtergrond |date=1 January 2019|language=nl|year=2019}}</ref>\n|region10   = {{flagcountry|Germany}}\n|pop10      = ''170.300''<ref>Eurostat Database (Data -> Population Consensus) https://ec.europa.eu/CensusHub2/query.do?step=selectHyperCube&qhc=false </ref>\n|region11   = {{flagcountry|France}}\n|pop11      = ''165.093''<ref>Eurostat Database (Data -> Population Consensus) https://ec.europa.eu/CensusHub2/query.do?step=selectHyperCube&qhc=false </ref>\n|region12   = {{flagcountry|Sweden}}\n|pop12     = ''75.491''<ref>Eurostat Database (Data -> Population Consensus) https://ec.europa.eu/CensusHub2/query.do?step=selectHyperCube&qhc=false </ref>\n|region13   = {{flagcountry|Italy}}\n|pop13     = ''512.857''<ref>Eurostat Database (Data -> Population Consensus) https://ec.europa.eu/CensusHub2/query.do?step=selectHyperCube&qhc=false </ref>\n|region14   = {{flagcountry|Switzerland}}\n|pop14     = ''89.868''<ref>Eurostat Database (Data -> Population Consensus) https://ec.europa.eu/CensusHub2/query.do?step=selectHyperCube&qhc=false </ref>\n|\n}}\n\n{{Latinos|History}}\nThe '''Latin American [[diaspora]]''' refers to the dispersion of [[Latin Americans]] out of their homelands in [[Latin America]] and the communities subsequently established by them across the world.\n\n== Latin American diaspora in Africa ==\nHistorically, Latin Americans have migrated to African countries over the course of colonization by Spain and in the aftermath of wars. [[Equatorial Guinea]], whose official language is Spanish, experienced an influx of Spanish migrants as it was once a Spanish colony. Some Cuban soldiers who served in the [[Angolan Civil War]] stayed in Angola afterwards. Brazilians have moved to Angola and Mozambique, former Portuguese colonies, and modern officially Portuguese-speaking nations. [[Nigeria]], the home of the [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] and [[Igbo people|Igbo]] cultures, experienced an influx of ex-slaves from Cuba and Brazil  brought there as indentured servants during the 17th century, and again during the 19th century; Equatorial Guinea received Afro-Cuban slaves. In Equatorial Guinea, they became part of the ''[[Emancipados]]''; in Nigeria, they were called ''[[Saro (Nigeria)#Amaros|Amaros]]''.  Despite being free to return to [[Cuba]] and [[Brazil]] when their tenure was over, they remained in these countries marrying into the local native population.\n\n== Latin American diaspora in Northern America ==\nCanada and the United States are popular destinations for Latin American immigrants. The United States is home to 55 million [[Hispanic and Latino Americans]], representing 16% of the US population. Meanwhile, Canada is home to over 300,000 Latino and Hispanic residents. (These numbers are majority descendants and minority immigrants)\n\n=== Latin American diaspora in Canada ===\n{{Main|Latin American Canadians}}\n{{See also|Immigration to Canada}}\n\n=== Latin American diaspora in the United States ===\n{{Main|Hispanic and Latino Americans}}\n\nOver 55 million Hispanic and Latino Americans are residents of the United States, representing 16% of the US population. Hispanic Americans and Latino Americans ({{lang-es|hispanos}} {{IPA-es|is\u02c8panos|}}, {{lang|es|latinos}}) are American citizens who are descendants of immigrants from the Spanish-speaking countries of [[Latin America]] and the [[Iberian peninsula]].<ref name=\"FragaGarcia2010\">{{cite book|author1=Luis Fraga|authorlink1=Luis Fraga|author2=John A. Garcia|title=Latino Lives in America: Making It Home|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XaNluPNVEQcC&pg=PA145|year=2010|publisher=Temple University Press| isbn=978-1-4399-0050-5|page=145}}</ref><ref name=\"Fisher1996\">{{cite book|author=Nancy L. Fisher|title=Cultural and Ethnic Diversity: A Guide for Genetics Professionals|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mqXlA7e4VN8C&pg=PA19| year=1996|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|isbn=978-0-8018-5346-3|page=19}}</ref><ref name=\"HoldenVillars2012\">{{cite book|author1=Robert H. Holden|author2=Rina Villars|title=Contemporary Latin America: 1970 to the Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2oShLUAPTYQC&pg=PA18| year=2012| publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-27487-3|page=18}}</ref> More generally, it includes all persons in the United States who self-identify as [[Hispanic]] or [[Latino (demonym)|Latino]], whether of full or partial ancestry.<ref name=\"fhwa.dot.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/hep/guidance/superseded/49cfr26.cfm|title=49 CFR Part 26|accessdate=2012-10-22|quote=\"'Hispanic Americans,' which includes persons of [[Mexican American|Mexican]]-, [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]]-, [[Cuban American|Cuban]], [[Dominican American|Dominican]]-, Central or South American, or other Spanish, culture or origin, regardless of race;\"}}</ref><ref name=\"SBA 8005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov/sops/8005/sop8005-3.pdf |title=US Small Business Administration 8(a) Program Standard Operating Procedure |accessdate=2012-10-22 |quote=\"SBA has defined 'Hispanic American' as an individual whose ancestry and culture are rooted in South America, Central America, Mexico, Cuba, the Dominican Republic, Puerto Rico, or the Iberian Peninsula, including Spain and Portugal.\" |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060925005103/http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov/sops/8005/sop8005-3.pdf |archivedate=2006-09-25 }}</ref><ref name=c2010def>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/cen2010/briefs/c2010br-02.pdf |title=Overview of Race and Hispanic Origin: 2010 |accessdate=2011-03-28 |first1=Karen R. |last1=Humes |first2=Nicholas A. |last2=Jones |first3=Roberto R. |last3=Ramirez |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau |quote=\"Hispanic or Latino\" refers to a person of Cuban, Mexican, Puerto Rican, South or Central American, or other Spanish or Portuguese culture or origin regardless of race. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429214029/http://www.census.gov/prod/cen2010/briefs/c2010br-02.pdf |archivedate=2011-04-29 }}</ref><ref name=hlorigin>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/help/en/hispanic_or_latino_origin.htm|title=American FactFinder Help: Hispanic or Latino origin|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-10-05|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213004743/http://factfinder.census.gov/help/en/hispanic_or_latino_origin.htm|archive-date=13 February 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> For the 2010 US census, the [[American Community Survey]], \"Hispanic\" or \"Latino\" were those who identified as one of the specific Hispanic or Latino categories listed on the census or ACS questionnaire (\"Mexican,\" \"Puerto Rican,\" or \"Cuban\") as well as those who indicated that they were \"other Spanish, Hispanic, or Latino.\" The peoples of countries considered as Hispanic or Latino American groups by the Census Bureau were the following: [[Spain]], [[Argentina]], [[Mexico]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Cuba]], [[Dominican Republic]], [[Costa Rica]], [[Guatemala]], [[Honduras]], [[Nicaragua]], [[Panama]], [[El Salvador]], [[Bolivia]], [[Chile]], [[Colombia]], [[Ecuador]], [[Paraguay]], [[Peru]], [[Uruguay]], and [[Venezuela]]. The Census Bureau uses the terms Hispanic and Latino interchangeably.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_11_1YR_B04006&prodType=table|title=PEOPLE REPORTING ANCESTRY Universe: Total population, 2014 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=14 October 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212212734/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_11_1YR_B04006&prodType=table|archive-date=12 February 2020|url-status=dead}} This page of the US Census bureau is about the reported ethnicities of United States in 2014. The page indicates the number of American people (or residents in United States) identifying as of different national origins.</ref> The Census office of the United States excluded [[Brazilian Americans]] from the Hispanic and Latino American population ([[Brazil]] is part of [[Latin America]], but [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] is the official language rather than [[Spanish language|Spanish]]).<ref name=\"Hispanic American ethnics Survey\">[http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_13_1YR_B03001&prodType=table US Census Bureau 2014 American Community Survey B03001 1-Year Estimates HISPANIC OR LATINO ORIGIN BY SPECIFIC ORIGIN] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20200212214432/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_13_1YR_B03001&prodType=table |date=12 February 2020 }} retrieved October 18, 2015. Number of people of Hispanic and Latino Origin by specific origin(except people of Brazilian origin).</ref><ref name=AmericanCommunitySurvey>{{cite web|title=PEOPLE REPORTING ANCESTRY Universe: Total population, 2014 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_11_1YR_B04006&prodType=table|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=14 October 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212212734/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_11_1YR_B04006&prodType=table|archive-date=12 February 2020|url-status=dead}} This page of the US Census bureau is about the reported ethnicities of United States in 2014. The page indicates the number of American people (or residents in United States) identifying as of different national origins. The page included the people from Brazil but excluded the people who indicated origins classified by the Census Bureau as \"Hispanic or Latino\".</ref> Other US government agencies have slightly different definitions of the term, including [[Brazilian Americans|Brazilians]] and other Portuguese-speaking groups.\n\n== Latin American diaspora in Europe ==\n{{Main|Migration from Latin America to Europe}}\n{{See also|Latin American migration to the United Kingdom}}\n\nLatin American migration to Europe is the diaspora of Latin Americans to the continent of [[Europe]], dates back to their independence from Spain. Latin Americans in Europe are a rapidly growing group consisting of immigrants from [[Argentina]], [[Bolivia]], [[Brazil]], [[Chile]], [[Colombia]], [[Costa Rica]], [[Cuba]], [[Dominican Republic]], [[Ecuador]], [[El Salvador]], [[Guatemala]], [[Honduras]], [[Mexico]], [[Nicaragua]], [[Panama]], [[Paraguay]], [[Peru]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Uruguay]] and [[Venezuela]].\n\nAs of 2019, around 3 million Latin Americans lived in Europe, mostly in Spain, which has around 2.8 million people residents and/or citizens born in the Americas as of 2019. They represent over 6% of the population of Spain, yet less than 1% of the total population of the [[European Union]]. Portugal also has a sizable Brazilian population.\n\nLatin Americans migrate to the European Union for the following reasons:\n\n*Common language and cultural proximity to Spain and Portugal.\n*Family ties both in Spain and other European countries which grant right to citizenship at origin.\n*Favorable naturalization laws for all Hispanics Americans in Spain, regardless of ancestry.\n* European countries commonly have multicultural societies and there is no feeling of [[Hispanophobia]] as observed in other countries.<ref>[http://cat.inist.fr/?aModele=afficheN&cpsidt=2457295 \"The Hispanophobia of the Official English movement in the US.\" A.C. Zentella. ''International journal of the sociology of language'' 1997, no 127 (1 p.1/4), pp. 71-86]</ref><ref>[http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/mcb/031/1998/00000018/00000005/art00002 \" Biological categories and border controls: the revival of eugenics in anti-immigration rhetoric.\" ''International Journal of Sociology and Social Policy'' Volume 18, Number 56, 1998 , pp. 35-63(29)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001162737/http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/mcb/031/1998/00000018/00000005/art00002 |date=October 1, 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://kvoa.com/Global/story.asp?S=4744652 \"Officials: Radio host's call to kill border crossers dangerous.\" Associated Press \u00a92006.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927221617/http://kvoa.com/Global/story.asp?S=4744652 |date=September 27, 2007 }}</ref> Europeans welcome Hispanics/Latinos as a source of workers, scientists, tourist, buyers of goods, houses and lands, as part of their society.\n* Universities are tuition-free or significantly cheaper than other countries (like the United States). \n* Study loans are widely available.\n\n== Latin American diaspora in Asia ==\n{{Main|Latin American Asian}}\n\nMexicans<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/16086/16086-h/16086-h.htm Letter from Fajardo to Felipe III From Manila, August 15 1620.(From the Spanish Archives of the Indies)]\n\n(\"The infantry does not amount to two hundred men, in three companies. If these men were that number, and Spaniards, it would not be so bad; but, although I have not seen them, because they have not yet arrived here, I am told that they are, as at other times, for the most part '''boys, mestizos, and mulattoes, with some Indians (Native Americans).''' There is no little cause for regret in the great sums that re\u00ebnforcements of such men waste for, and cost, your Majesty. I cannot see what betterment there will be until your Majesty shall provide it, since I do not think, that more can be done in Nueva Spa\u00f1a, although the viceroy must be endeavoring to do so, as he is ordered.\")</ref> and Peruvians<ref>[http://www.zamboanga.com/html/history_1634_moro_attacks.htm \"Second Book of the Second Part of the Conquests of the Filipinas Islands, and Chronicle of the Religious of Our Father, St. Augustine\"] (Zamboanga City History)\n\"He (Governor Don Sebast\u00edan Hurtado de Corcuera) brought a great re\u00ebnforcements of soldiers, many of them from Per\u00fa, as he made his voyage to Acapulco from that kingdom.\"</ref> have immigrated to the [[Philippines]] since Spanish colonial rule. One in three inhabitants of the Filipino island of [[Luzon]] have partial Latino descent.<ref>Jagor, F\u00ebdor, et al. (1870). [http://www.authorama.com/former-philippines-b-8.html ''The Former Philippines thru Foreign Eyes'']</ref> Furthermore, about 1.2 million citizens of [[Zamboanga City]], [[Mindanao]], speak [[Chavacano]], a creole language based on Mexican-Spanish.<ref>Spanish creole: {{Citation | first = Antonio | last = Quilis | title = La lengua espa\u00f1ola en Filipinas | year = 1996 | page = 54 and 55 | url = http://www.cervantesvirtual.com/servlet/SirveObras/01350553135573500088680/209438_0013.pdf | publisher = Cervantes virtual }}</ref>\n\nThe most significant Latino diaspora in Japan is Peruvian, followed by the Bolivian and Brazilian diaspora. Migration of South Americans to Japan was significant after the Second World War. Peruvian, Brazilian, and Bolivian settlers in Japan are largely, but not exclusively of Japanese blood; migration of Brazilian settlers to Japan represented the largest number of [[Portuguese language in Asia|Portuguese speakers in Asia]], greater than those of formerly Portuguese [[East Timor]], [[Macau]] and [[Goa]] combined. Because of common language and cultural proximity, a number of Brazilians settled Macau, others in East Timor and Goa.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Latin countries !! Immigrants to Japan\n|-\n| Peru || 57,464\n|-\n|Colombia\n|37,500\n|-\n| Bolivia || 6,094\n|-\n|-\n| Paraguay || 2,240\n|-\n| Mexico || 1,995\n|}\n\n== Latin American diaspora in Oceania ==\n{{See also|Latin American Australians}}\n\nChile, Colombia and El Salvador have significant diasporas in Australia.<ref>http://www.ausstats.abs.gov.au/ausstats/subscriber.nsf/0/E0A79B147EA8E0B5CA2572AC001813E8/$File/34120_2005-06.pdf</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country !! Immigrants in Australia\n|-\n|-\n| Chile || 26 204\n|-\n|Colombia\n|21 000\n|-\n| El Salvador || 10 563\n|-\n|}\n\nThe most significant Latin American diasporas in New Zealand are Brazilian, Chileans, Argentinians, Colombians, Mexicans, Uruguayans, Venezuelans, and Bolivians.<ref>[https://teara.govt.nz/en/latin-americans Latin Americans \u2013 Te Ara Encyclopedia]</ref><ref>[https://teara.govt.nz/en/latin-americans/page-1 1. \u2013 Latin Americans \u2013 Te Ara Encyclopedia]</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Latino Country !! Immigrants in New Zealand\n|-\n|-\n|Brazil \n| 3,588\n|-\n| Chile\n| 2,409\n|-\n|Argentina\n|1,701\n|-\n|Colombia\n| 1,155 \n|-\n|Mexico\n|741\n|-\n|Uruguay\n|447\n|-\n|Venezuela\n|150\n|-\n|Bolivia\n| 153\n|-\n|}\n\nThe Latin American diaspora in Easter Island is Chilean, 39% of Easter Islander population were mainland Chileans (or their Easter Island-born descendants) or mestizos (primarily indigenous Chilean blood with little European mixtures, or their Easter Island-born descendants) and Easter Island-born mestizos of Chilean and Rapa Nui and/or native Chilean descent, and the remaining 1% were indigenous mainland native Chileans (or their Easter Island-born descendants).\n\n== Emigrant Policies ==\n\nThe countries of Latin America seek to strengthen links between migrants and their states of origin, while promoting their integration in the receiving state. These Emigrant Policies focus on the rights, obligations and opportunities for participation of emigrated citizens who already live outside the borders of their country of origin. Citizens' rights are the most important policy area, followed by social policies that expand welfare functions beyond state borders. Research on Latin America shows that the extension of policies towards migrants is linked to a focus on civil rights and state benefits that can positively influence integration in recipient countries. Some states actively help their emigrated citizens to integrate into local society. Such policies can reduce the cost of integration for emigrants - and provide untapped potential for cooperation between countries of origin and destination.\nIn addition, the tolerance of dual citizenship has spread more in Latin America than in any other region of the world.<ref>Pedroza, L., Palop, P. & Hoffmann, B. (2016). Emigrant Policies in Latin America and the Caribbean. Santiago de Chile: FLACSO-Chile. https://www.giga-hamburg.de/sites/default/files/md_pdf/emigrant-policies-LatinAmerica-and-theCaribbean.pdf</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Latino]]\n* [[Latin American culture]]\n* [[Migration from Latin America to Europe]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Latin American diaspora}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Latino Diaspora}}\n[[Category:Latin American diasporas| ]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino| ]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLatino(link changed toLatin Americans) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_American_diaspora"}
{"title_page": "Exide lead contamination", "text_new": "{{Tone|date=July 2019}}\n[[File:Pallet of scrap lead-acid automotive batteries (right side).jpg|thumb|Pallet of scrap lead-acid automotive batteries ready to be recycled]]\n[[Exide]] is one of the world's largest producers, distributors and [[Battery recycling|recyclers]] of [[lead-acid batteries]]. Lead-acid batteries are used in automobiles, golf carts, fork-lifts, and motorcycles.  They are recycled by grinding them open, neutralizing the sulfuric acid, and separating the [[polymers]] from the [[lead]] and [[copper]]. In the US, 97 percent of the lead from car batteries is recycled - which is the highest recycling rate for any commodity. Most states require stores to take back old batteries.<ref name=\"NYT 2011-12-09\"/>\n\nSince 2010, operations at seven Exide lead-acid battery plants have been linked to ambient heavy metal levels that posed a health risk to the environment and thousands of residents in neighborhoods surrounding the Exide plants.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/29/local/la-me-exide-pollute-20130530|title=Battery recycler Exide's problems aren't just local|first1=Kim|last1=Christensen|first2=Jessica|last2=Garrison|date=29 May 2013|newspaper=LA Times|access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref> Exide has been found to be a significant source of lead emissions and/or contamination in [[Los Angeles County]]; [[Frisco, Texas]]; [[Muncie, Indiana]]; [[Salina, Kansas]]; [[Bristol, Tennessee]]; [[Reading, Pennsylvania]]; and [[Forest City, Missouri]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Los Angeles County, California (Vernon)==\n[[File:Recycling lead in a lead-acid battery recovery facility.jpg|thumb|right|Recycling lead in a lead-acid battery recovery facility]]\n\nA [[battery recycling]] plant in southeast Los Angeles County, California, United States, emitted toxic metal dust over decades that contaminated as many as 10,000 homes in half a dozen [[working-class]], [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]] communities near the plant.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\"/>  Lead is a neurotoxin that causes harm to most organs, but it most commonly causes cognitive deficits, neurodevelopmental delays, and psychological impairments.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Johnston|first=Jill E.|last2=Hricko|first2=Andrea|date=2017-10-01|title=Industrial Lead Poisoning in Los Angeles: Anatomy of a Public Health Failure|journal=Environmental Justice |volume=10|issue=5|pages=162\u2013167|doi=10.1089/env.2017.0019|issn=1939-4071|pmc=5783279|pmid=30687453}}</ref> [[Exide Technologies]], owner of the [[lead-acid battery]] [[Lead smelter|smelter]] located in [[Vernon, California|Vernon]], agreed in 2015 to close the facility during the massive cleanup of the [[contaminated soil]], which will take years and cost hundreds of millions of dollars.<ref name=\"LAT 2015-12-21\"/>\n\n===Background===\nThe 15-acre battery recycling plant (6.1 ha) is located in Vernon, CA \u2013 a heavily industrialized city in Southeast Los Angeles county<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cityofvernon.org/about-vernon|title=City of Vernon - About Vernon|website=www.cityofvernon.org|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>. The smelter was issued an \u201cinterim status document\u201d by the California Department of Health Services in 1981 and operated under a provisional permit while documented violations were occurring. Exide took ownership of the smelter when they purchased the Gould-National Battery and its assets in 2000.<ref name=\"KPPC \"/><ref name=\"LAT 2015-03-12\"/> In 2013, Exide was under federal criminal investigation for emitting high levels of harmful pollutants from its battery recycling plant in Vernon, CA.<ref name=\"LAT 2014-08-16\"/> Hundreds of residents had complained for years about Exide's toxic emissions before state and federal agencies acted.<ref name=\"LAT Video\"/> In March 2015, the company signed an agreement with the U.S. attorney's office to close permanently.<ref name=\"graphics_exide\">{{Cite web |url=http://graphics.latimes.com/exide-battery-plant/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-06-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404234600/http://graphics.latimes.com/exide-battery-plant/ |archive-date=2018-04-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The deal allowed Exide and its employees to avoid prosecution for years of environmental crimes, including illegal storage, disposal and shipment of hazardous waste, while agreeing to pay $50 million to demolish and clean the plant and surrounding communities, including $9 million set aside for removing lead from homes.<ref name=\"graphics_exide\"/>\n\n===Environmental impact===\n\nThe soil beneath the facility tests high for [[toxic metals]]. The groundwater was also polluted from the operation of the plant and corrosive and irritating sulfates drained onto public streets.<ref name=\"LAT 2015-03-12\"/>\n\nStudies have indicated that as many as 10,000 homes in half a dozen working-class, Latino communities near the plant have had their homes and yards contaminated by the lead emissions. The decades of [[air pollution]] from the Exide Technologies facility has potentially contaminated the nearby communities of  [[Boyle Heights]], [[Maywood, California|Maywood]] [[East Los Angeles, California|East Los Angeles]], [[Commerce, California|Commerce]], [[Bell, California|Bell]], and [[Huntington Park, California|Huntington Park]].<ref name=\"LAT 2015-03-12\"/>\n\nResidents had long been concerned about the air pollution from the plant that was found to have emitted lead, arsenic and other dangerous pollutants over decades. Lead is a potent [[neurotoxin]] that puts children at-risk for [[learning disabilities]], lower [[IQ]]s and other [[Developmental disability|developmental problems]] who may have acquired [[lead poisoning]] from playing outdoors.<ref name=\"LAT 2015-12-21\"/>\n\n=== Public Health Impacts in East Los Angeles ===\nThroughout history, lead exposure has led to public health problems, specifically for workers in factories or other industrial entities.<ref name=\":0\" /> While past measures that prevent lead exposure in the first place have been successful, \u201csecondary prevention\u201d is emphasized by public health agencies now, leaving the people who have already been exposed or who will continually be exposed at risk because lead is still used in the manufacture of batteries, buses, trucks, tractors, and motorcycles.<ref name=\":0\" /> As a result, Low income communities and communities of color face a major gap in the public health system for lead exposure prevention.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAccording to \u201cIndustrial Lead Poisoning in Los Angeles: Anatomy of a Public Health Failure\u201d in the Journal of Environmental Justice, Southeastern Los Angeles has similar gaps and failures of lead prevention as in the [[Flint water crisis|Flint Michigan Water Crisis]].<ref name=\":0\" />  Since the 1970\u2019s, Exide had been operating in Vernon. In 2013, AQMD explained that upwards of 250,000 residents in East Los Angeles face a chronic health hazard from lead and arsenic exposure from Exide.<ref>South Coast Air Quality Management District, ''Lead Monitoring at Exide Technologies'', 2014.</ref> Communities living near Exide such as Boyle Heights and Maywood are more than 90% Latino and rank among the top 10% of most environmentally burdened areas in California.<ref name=\":0\" /> More than 90% of homes in the area were built before the 1978 ban on lead paint and many directly neighbor freeways and truck routes which resulted in decades of exposure to leaded gasoline which contaminated soil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://egis3.lacounty.gov/dataportal/2017/12/12/assessor-parcels-2016-tax-roll/|title=Assessor Parcels \u2013 2016 Tax Roll|date=2017-12-12|website=Los Angeles County GIS Data Portal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref><ref>Mielke, HW, et al, Science of the Total Environment 408; (2010) 3965\u20133975</ref><ref>Laidlaw MAS, Zahran S, Pingitore N, Clague J, Devlin G, Taylor MP. 2014. Identification of lead sources in residential environments: Sydney, Australia. Environ Pollut 184: 238\u2013246.</ref> Lead exposure is especially prevalent in soil, water, and dust; it has the most impact on the children and workers around Vernon. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2019, a study conducted by the University of Southern California found a high amount of lead in baby teeth of children in Boyle Heights, Maywood, East Los Angeles, Commerce, and Huntington park.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.usc.eduhttps//news.usc.edu/156523/lead-in-baby-teeth-exide-battery-plant/|title=Lead contamination found in baby teeth of children living near Exide battery plant|date=2019-05-06|website=USC News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Johnston|first=Jill E.|last2=Franklin|first2=Meredith|last3=Roh|first3=Hannah|last4=Austin|first4=Christine|last5=Arora|first5=Manish|date=2019-05-21|title=Lead and Arsenic in Shed Deciduous Teeth of Children Living Near a Lead-Acid Battery Smelter|journal=Environmental Science & Technology|volume=53|issue=10|pages=6000\u20136006|doi=10.1021/acs.est.9b00429|pmid=31056909|issn=0013-936X|bibcode=2019EnST...53.6000J}}</ref> The lead in the baby teeth matched with soil contamination data from the California Department of Toxic Substances Control.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Truth Fairy study revealed that children in Boyle Heights and East L.A. have the highest exposure to lead, which most likely came through winds carrying soil in utero from their mother or post birth. The study urges legislators to create initiatives to prevent lead exposure. Jill Johnston, co author of the study and professor of preventive medicine explains, \u201chigher lead in teeth means higher lead in the brain, kidney and bones. Testing women for lead during pregnancy, or even earlier, as they enter child-bearing age, may be needed to decrease lead exposure to their future offspring.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Testing and clean-up===\n[[File:DRAFT-EXIDE-OPTION-1E.JPG|thumb|DTSC Preliminary Area of Investigation map]]\n\nThe facility closure is overseen by the California Department of Toxic Substances Control (DTSC) and the South Coast Air Quality Management District (SCAQMD). The closure includes dismantling the former recycling facility under a full enclosure tent, under negative pressure, preventing emissions from leaving the premises. Hazardous materials from the facility are recycled or disposed of under DTSC oversight.<ref>American Integrated Services, Inc. (2017, October 22). Closure Implementation Plan. Retrieved February 25, 2020, from <nowiki>https://dtsc.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/31/2018/03/Closure-Implementation-Plan_10-22-17.pdf</nowiki></ref>\n\nThe cleanup of the soil contaminated with lead is being overseen by the [[California Department of Toxic Substances Control]].<ref name=\"LAT 2016-01-26\" /> In August 2015, the department announced that soil testing had shown that the toxic dust had deposited lead in as many as 10,000 homes.  Department officials said that they had not previously been involved in a lead cleanup case in which the number of properties was this high.<ref name=\"LAT 2015-08-17\" />\n\nNineteen homes received first priority for cleanup starting in December 2014 based on the test results.<ref name=\"NBC 2014-12=05\"/> The residents of two neighborhoods in Boyle Heights and Maywood were notified in August 2015 that they could have their soil tested for lead after being identified by the [[South Coast Air Quality Management District]] as the communities most likely to have been contaminated by the lead emissions. Contaminated soil was removed and replaced at 146 of the homes closest to the facility in these communities.<ref name=\"LAT 2015-08-17\"/><ref name=\"KPPC 2016-6-10\"/>\n\nIn October 2015 the [[Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors]], frustrated with the slow pace by the state, designated $2 million to \u201cfacilitate\" the cleanup effort by hiring contractors and consultants, performing soil testing at 1,000 homes during the following two months, and sending community outreach workers to neighborhoods around the plant. A timeline and strategy was also included in the resolution to force state regulators, Exide \"and other responsible parties to fully fund and undertake this cleanup.\u201d The state had used all but $1 million of $9 million Exide placed in a trust fund for residential cleanup.<ref name=\"LAT 2015-10-27\"/> By the end of February 2016, county crews began testing soil at homes in Commerce.<ref name=\"KPPC 2016-2-29\"/> The state allocated $176.6 million for the cost of testing and cleanup of about 2,500 of the most contaminated yards. Job training program for community members to be employed in cleanup has been planned by the Department of Toxic Substances Control. It is also establishing a local office to improve and coordinate information-sharing efforts. Local community groups are working with the agency for outreach in signing up residents for testing.<ref name=\"Marketplace\"/>\n\nHigh lead levels were found in the soil at Lorena and Rowan Elementary Schools in the summer of 2015 by the Department of Toxic Substances Control.<ref name=\"KPPC 2016-8-23\"/><ref name=\"LAT 2017-6-30\"/>\n\nIn fall 2017, the Department of Toxic Substances Control began to implement their plans to remove lead-contaminated soil from 2,500 residential properties near the closed Exide Technologies lead acid battery plant in Vernon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-exide-cleanup-plan-20170706-story.html|title=State releases plan to clean lead contamination from 2,500 parcels near closed battery recycler Exide|date=July 7, 2017|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> It is believed to be the largest environmental cleanup effort of its kind in California history, encompassing seven (7) Los Angeles County neighborhoods. California state regulators estimate that Exide's operations may have threatened the health of an estimated 100,000 people and 10,000 residential properties.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\"/> A total of $192 million has been authorized by the state for the massive cleanup effort; $176.6 million of which was approved by Governor Jerry Brown in April 2016.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\"/>\n\nThe $192 million set aside by the State will only allow for cleanup of 2,500 of the estimated 10,000 homes and properties believed to have been contaminated by Exide's decades of pollution. Total costs to clean up the estimated 10,000 homes contaminated by Exide's pollution is believed to be over $500 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/news/11613080/state-aims-to-close-funding-gap-for-lead-contamination-cleanup-neighbors-skeptical|title=State Aims to Close Funding Gap for Lead Contamination Cleanup, Neighbors Skeptical|date=August 24, 2017|website=KQED}}</ref> By August 2016, over $42 million of the $192 million had already been spent.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\"/>\n\nFacing mounting pressure from community activists, residents, and elected officials, to hold Exide, and not taxpayers, accountable for millions of dollars of additional money needed to clean up Exide's toxic lead mess in east L.A. County, the South Coast Air Quality Management District filed claims against Exide totaling over $80 million.<ref name=\"law360_1007567\">{{cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/1007567/exide-says-air-regulator-s-claim-is-barred-by-ch-11-plan|title=Exide Says Air Regulator's Claim Is Barred By Ch. 11 Plan - Law360|website=www.law360.com}}</ref> Exide filed its own lawsuit<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.documentcloud.org/documents/3893790-April-2016-lawsuit-filed-by-Exide-Technologies.html|title=April 2016 lawsuit filed by Exide Technologies against California...|first=Tony Barboza (Los Angeles|last=Times)|website=www.documentcloud.org}}</ref> in 2016 seeking blood lead data on people tested in L.A. County, including each person's age, city and ZIP Code; the age of the home in which each person lived; and any causes of lead poisoning. The state is fighting the lawsuit in court, calling it an attempt by Exide to dodge financial responsibility and blame the contamination on lead paint and gasoline.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\"/> Paying for the cleanup might admit guilt that could lead to criminal charges and jail time for executives.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\"/>\n\nOn January 31, 2018, Exide Technologies told a bankruptcy judge that their company is not responsible for the $80 million in additional cleanup costs the state of California is trying to recoup, and that the State's claim should be discharged as part of the company's Chapter 11 bankruptcy plan in 2015.<ref name=\"law360_1007567\"/>  Unless the bankruptcy judge rules against Exide, it is likely that taxpayers will be pay for the clean up.{{Fact|date=January 2020}}\n\nCalifornia\u2019s state auditor will investigate how the Department of Toxic Substances Control is handling cleanup after the Joint Committee on Legislative Audit voted in February 2020 to probe contracts, cleanup times, and other issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.bloombergenvironment.com/environment-and-energy/california-to-probe-former-battery-recycling-site-cleanup|title=California to Probe Former Battery Recycling Site Cleanup|last=Dooley|first=Emily C.|date=February 26, 2020|website=Bloomberg Environment|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\n\nThe state had dedicated about $7 million to test and clean up homes in 2015.<ref name=\"LAT 2016-01-26\"/>  The state assembly voted in 2016 to provide $176.6 million for the cleanup.<ref name=\"Sac Bee 14Apr2016\"/><ref name=CAP-Radio/> State legislators held an informational hearing at the Capitol on January 26, 2016 where Assemblyman [[Jimmy Gomez]] (D-Echo Park) noted the rapid mobilization for the [[Porter Ranch gas leak]] near a wealthier community while the slow progress in these neighborhoods where most residents are Latino and low-income should be disheartening to all legislators. Gomez said \"We don't want to send the wrong message. That if you live ... in Porter Ranch that you're more important than the folks that live in East ... or Southeast Los Angeles.\"<ref name=\"LAT 2016-01-26\"/>\n\nAt the January 26, 2016 hearing, Assembly Speaker [[Anthony Rendon (politician)|Anthony Rendon]] (D-Lakewood) said the Department of Toxic Substances Control \"has not done a good job\" and that he would urge officials to act more urgently on the clean-up.<ref name=\"LAT 2016-01-26\"/> The extent and duration of the lead contamination has raised concerns about longstanding problems at the department. The Governor and state legislators saw this as an wake-up call to seek new laws, hold oversight hearings, and work on other reform efforts.<ref name=\"LAT 2016-05-28\"/>\n\nIn May 2018, the CA state Assembly approved a budget action<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abgt.assembly.ca.gov/sites/abgt.assembly.ca.gov/files/May%20Revise%20Sub%203%20%20May%2023%20-%20Energy%20and%20Transportation.pdf |title=Energy and Transportation |website=abgt.assembly.ca.gov |access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> and legislation, AB 2189, to commit $16 million in funds for cleaning public parkways.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billTextClient.xhtml?bill_id=201720180AB2189|title=Bill Text - AB-2189 Hazardous substances: lead: cleanup: Exide Technologies facility.|website=leginfo.legislature.ca.gov}}</ref> The funding would come from a bill the CA state legislature passed in 2016 to raise about $176 million to help clean-up Exide's toxic lead contamination mess in Vernon, and surrounding neighborhoods, by levying a fee on batteries for all battery manufacturers and consumers.<ref name=\"LAT 2018-05-22\"/>\n\nIf AB 2189 is made law, it would raise the cost of the taxpayer-funded Exide cleanup to over $200 million.<ref name=\"LAT 2018-05-22\"/>\n\n==Exide contamination record elsewhere in the U.S.==\n{{Empty-section|date=July 2019}}\n\n==Environmental contamination record==\n\nThe EPA's Lead National Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS) Non-attainment Designations list designates a total of 21 areas and parts of 22 counties across 15 states and Puerto Rico that are in violation of federal air quality health standards for lead emissions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leadfreefrisco.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/LeadNAAreaList.pdf |title=Listings |website=leadfreefrisco.com}}</ref>\n\nExide has operations in six (6) out of the 21 areas that do not meet safe air quality laws; accounting for nearly one-third of the violators (more than any other company).<ref name=\"leadfreefrisco.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leadfreefrisco.com/2011/11/update-epa-list-exide-has-most-plants-in-violation-of-air-safety-laws-for-lead-emissions/|title=UPDATED EPA REPORT - Exide has most plants in violation of air safety laws for lead emissions - Lead Free Frisco|website=www.leadfreefrisco.com}}</ref> The Exide plants in violation of EPA lead emission standards are in Frisco, TX, Vernon, CA, Muncie, IN, Salina, KS, Reading, PA, and Bristol, TN.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.epa.gov/lead-designations|title=Lead Designations - US EPA|first=US|last=EPA, OAR|website=US EPA|date=December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Muncie, IN==\nBetween 1989 and 2015, Exide Technologies released more than 227,275 pounds of toxic pollutants, including dangerous lead, sulfuric acid and arsenic, into the air and water in Muncie, Indiana where they operate a secondary lead acid battery smelter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/opinion/readers/2017/12/16/letters-editor-dec-17/957150001/|title=Letters to the editor, Dec. 17|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref> \nIn November 2010, the City of Muncie, Indiana and Delaware County were placed on the U.S. EPA's nonattainment list for concentrations of toxic lead in the air that are too high to meet national air quality standards for lead due to emissions from the Exide plant in Muncie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ens-newswire.com/ens/nov2010/2010-11-17-091.html|title=Areas Violating Lead Standards Host Smelters, Battery Recyclers|last=staff|website=www.ens-newswire.com}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Exide Technologies agreed to pay an $820,000 civil penalty to settle a lawsuit for violating the Clean Air Act at its Muncie lead smelter plant. According to the U.S. EPA, the violations resulted in increased emissions of lead and particulate matter and may have resulted in increased emissions of total hydrocarbons, volatile organic compounds and dioxin/furans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/news/local/2015/03/18/exide-fined-muncie-pollution/24983753/|title=Exide fined $820,000 for Muncie pollution|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, the Department of Justice and Exide Technologies rejected pleas from the mayor of Muncie, environmental/health groups and three neighborhood associations to install a $31 million in pollution-control equipment at the company's battery recycling facility; like their competitor Quemetco did for their similar lead acid battery plant in nearby Indianapolis. More than a dozen public health, neighborhood, environmental, and public health organizations, led by the Hoosier Environmental Council, had urged the U.S. Department of Justice to add additional pollution controls to the proposed settlement to better protect people in Muncie from lead and arsenic released into the air by Exide. The organizations also asked the DOJ to require Exide to include monitoring for pollutants at Exide's fenceline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muncievoice.com/13035/exide-technologies-gets-a-pass-to-keep-polluting-muncie/|title=Exide Technologies Gets a Pass to Keep Polluting Muncie - Muncie Voice|date=6 October 2015|website=muncievoice.com}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, the Exide plant in Muncie experienced three explosions and leakage issues that were not fully or timely disclosed to the relevant state and federal agencies responsible for ensuring Exide's compliance with state and federal laws and safety protocols.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/news/local/2018/01/05/state-complaint-reveals-explosions-exide/1006794001/|title=State complaint reveals explosions at Exide|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref> Local residents were not made aware of these explosions until nearly a year later, January 2018, raising concerns about any risks to the environment and to the health and safety of hundreds of families that live near the Exide facility.\n\nA year later, in February 2018, it was reported that a local pediatrician and the Delaware County Health Department had informed Indiana state officials in 2017 of cases of Exide Technologies\u2019 workers tracking lead home on their clothing and exposing their children to the toxic metal<ref name=\"thestarpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/news/local/2018/02/07/exide-employees-muncie-reportedly-exposed-kids-lead/314661002/|title=Exide employees in Muncie reportedly exposed kids to lead|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theindychannel.com/news/local-news/delaware-county/parents-who-work-at-delaware-county-plant-may-be-exposing-their-children-to-lead|title=Parents who work at Delaware County plant may be exposing their children to lead|first=Graham Hunter, Katie|last=Cox|date=14 February 2018|website=theindychannel.com}}</ref><ref name=\"wthr.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wthr.com/article/concerns-mount-over-lead-exposure-from-muncie-plant|title=Concerns mount over lead exposure from Muncie plant|date=8 February 2018|website=wthr.com}}</ref>\n\nIt was also reported that the local health department made a complaint on June 20 to the Indiana Department of Environmental Management about \"a recent increase in the amount of elevated blood lead level cases\" reported to local health officials in the community, and that \"several of these cases have revealed connections to the Exide plant\u201d with the \u201cbusiness's activities\u201d being a \u201clikely source of this lead exposure.\"<ref name=\"thestarpress.com\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"wthr.com\"/>\n\nFollowing reports that Exide workers may have exposed their families to lead contamination in Muncie, residents there have expressed broader concerns about Exide's lead-acid battery plant and the toll that Exide's decades of toxic emissions of lead and other contaminants may have had on the health and safety of hundreds of residents that live near the plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/news/local/2018/02/09/idem-denies-public-hearing-exide-permit/318803002/|title=IDEM denies public hearing on Exide permit|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theindychannel.com/news/local-news/delaware-county/muncie/couple-has-lead-concerns-near-muncie-plant|title=Couple has lead concerns living by Muncie plant|first=Graham|last=Hunter|date=14 February 2018|website=theindychannel.com|access-date=23 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215084053/https://www.theindychannel.com/news/local-news/delaware-county/muncie/couple-has-lead-concerns-near-muncie-plant|archive-date=15 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the Indiana Department of Environmental Management's (IDEM) decision not to hold a public meeting on Exide's five-year general operating permit in 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/opinion/contributors/2018/02/24/idem-idle-while-indianas-businesses-pollute-environment/366735002/,|title=IDEM idle while Indiana's businesses pollute environment|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref> dozens of residents took to the streets near the Exide plant in Muncie to decry IDEM's decision and to push for testing of the air, soil and water at the hundreds of homes and properties located near the lead-acid battery plant<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theindychannel.com/news/local-news/delaware-county/dozens-protest-outside-exide-technologies-in-muncie|title=Dozens protest outside Exide Technologies in Muncie|first=TheIndyChannel.com|last=Staff|date=26 February 2018|website=theindychannel.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/news/local/2018/02/25/demonstrators-march-front-exide-lead-plant/371400002/|title=Demonstrators march in front of Exide lead plant|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/indiana/articles/2018-02-26/indiana-residents-protest-lead-plant |title=Indiana Residents Protest Lead Plant|date=February 26, 2018|access-date=31 March 2018|agency=Associated Press|website=usnews.com}}</ref>\n\n==Salina, KS (Elevated lead levels in children)==\nExide Technologies operates a large lead-acid battery plant in Salina, KS. Between 1987 and 2015, Exide released over 166,077 pounds of lead, antimony, arsenic and other contaminates into the air and water in Salina.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.homefacts.com/environmentalhazards/Kansas/Saline-County/Salina/Polluter-Exide-Technologies-67401xdbtt413eb.html|title=Exide Technologies in Salina, KS &#124; Homefacts|website=www.homefacts.com}}</ref> Between 2010-2013, and in 2016, Exide exceeded allowed lead concentration release limits over 18 times, in violation of the Clean Air Act,<ref>[http://www.kdheks.gov/bar/airmonitor/lead/Updated_Lead_Monitoring_Results.pdf ]{{dead link|date=July 2019}}</ref> and in 2010, the plant was largely  responsible for the area being designated as one of 16 areas in the nation with concentrations of toxic lead in the air too high to meet national air quality standards for lead according to the EPA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ens-newswire.com/ens/nov2010/2010-11-17-091.html|title=Areas Violating Lead Standards Host Smelters, Battery Recyclers|website=www.ens-newswire.com}}</ref>\n\nGiven Exide's occupation and long history of violations for excessive lead emissions and safety in Salina, several residents over the years have expressed concerns about the plant and have asked about possible correlations to troubling reports and data showing higher numbers of blood lead levels in children in Saline County, where Exide operates, than in surrounding counties and communities in Kansas.<ref name=\"kmuw_saline\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kmuw.org/post/saline-county-residents-express-concerns-about-lead-exposure|title=Saline County Residents Express Concerns About Lead Exposure|first=Bryan|last=Thompson|website=www.kmuw.org}}</ref> Between 2000-2010, the mean blood lead levels in Saline Co. averaged 16.5&nbsp;ug/dL, more than double that of all other counties in Kansas which averaged 7.5&nbsp;ug/dL<ref name=\"keap_EPHT\">{{cite web|url=https://keap.kdhe.state.ks.us/EPHT/misc_reports/Preliminary%20Analysis%20of%20Blood%20Lead%20Levels%20in%20Saline%20County%20and%20other%20Selected%20Areas%20in%20Kansas.pdf?AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1 |title=report |website=keap.kdhe.state.ks.us |access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n\n{{cite web|url=https://keap.kdhe.state.ks.us/EPHT/misc_reports/Preliminary%20Analysis%20of%20Blood%20Lead%20Levels%20in%20Saline%20County%20and%20other%20Selected%20Areas%20in%20Kansas.pdf?AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1 |title=Energy and Transportation |website=keap.kdhe.state.ks.us |access-date=2019-07-17}} and children living in the city of Salina, had a significantly higher mean blood lead level (3.00&nbsp;\u00b5g/dL) compared to children living in all other Kansas zip codes (2.86&nbsp;\u00b5g/dL<ref name=\"keap_EPHT\"/>\n\nIn 2016, the Kansas Department of Health and Environment (KDHE) organized a meeting after tests by local doctors in 2016 found elevated lead levels in the blood of 32 Saline County children \u2014 most of them from Salina.<ref name=\"kmuw_health\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kmuw.org/post/health-officials-concerned-about-lead-exposure-saline-county-kids|title=Health Officials Concerned About Lead Exposure In Saline County Kids|first=Bryan|last=Thompson|website=www.kmuw.org}}</ref> This came on the heels of reports of elevated blood levels being found in 84 Saline County children between 2013-2015.<ref name=\"kmuw_health\"/>\n\nA few residents at the 2016 community meeting asked whether local officials and agencies were investigating any potential correlation or links to the number of children in Salina with elevated levels of toxic lead in their blood, and Exide's lead acid-battery plant in Salina.<ref name=\"kmuw_saline\"/> \nHowever, representatives at KDHE tried to avert the inquires by noting that the Exide plant had reduced their lead emissions each year since 2012, following the EPA's stricter requirements on lead emissions, and some plant renovations, and glossed over the fact that Exide still sent a total of 6,720 pounds of lead into the air during that period (2012-2015).<ref name=\"kmuw_saline\"/> KDHE also failed to mention the potentially bigger problem of cumulative lead and other toxic contaminate build up in the soil and water within a 1-3 mile radius of the plant over the decades the plant has been in operation, and did not demonstrate any intention to test the soil or groundwater of homes and public spaces near the plant for elevated levels of lead and other toxic contaminants.\n\nKDHE representatives also helped point the arrow away from Exide by releasing a map showing where the 32 children with elevated blood levels live, many not adjacent to Exide's plant.<ref name=\"kmuw_saline\"/> However, KDHE representatives failed to mention that no comprehensive blood testing was conducted for families that live near the plant, that results included only reported cases from local doctors whose parents brought their child in for a medical issue or check-in, and that the children of employees who work at the plant, who are exposed daily to lead, live all over the city and not just adjacent to the plant.\n\nTo date, no substantive government action has been taken to address this issue. The contamination source(s) for the disproportionate number of children with elevated blood lead levels in Salina, KS and Saline County, remains an apparent mystery.\n\n==Columbus, GA==\nExide used to operate a secondary lead recycling plant in Columbus that was taken out of service in 1999 and now the plant continues to operate as a lead-acid battery manufacturing facility at 3639 Joy Road.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2017/07/10/epd-fines-columbus-battery-maker-for-lead-release.html |title=News article |website=bizjournals.com}}</ref> Between 1987-2015, Exide released 362,102 pounds of toxic pollutants, including lead and arsenic, in the air and water near their plant in Columbus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://echo.epa.gov/facilities/facility-search|title=Facility Search \u2013 Enforcement and Compliance Data - ECHO - US EPA|website=echo.epa.gov}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Exide was forced to clean up contaminated groundwater in Columbus resulting from their plant and practices. Costs for supplemental investigations, remediation and site closure are ongoing and currently estimated at $13.5 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/813781/000119312504111307/d10k.htm|title=Form 10-K - Exide Technologies|website=www.sec.gov}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Exide received $34.3 million in federal taxpayer money and over $15 million in local tax incentives to boost production of next gen batteries and create more jobs at their plants in Columbus and Bristol, TN but came under fire after shuttering their plant in Bristol not long after taking the taxpayer money and incentives.<ref name=\"leadfreefrisco.com\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Georgia's Environmental Protection Division fined Exide Technologies $41,000 for violating federal emissions standards on lead at their Columbus lead acid battery plant in November and December 2016 and January 2017.<ref>[https://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2017/07/10/epd-fines-columbus-battery-maker-for-lead-release.htm]{{dead link|date=March 2018}}</ref> l<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ledger-enquirer.com/news/local/article160505644.html|title=Columbus battery plant fined $41,000 by state for lead emissions|website=ledger-enquirer.com}}</ref>\n\nJust recently, in 2018, Exide Technologies was fined $11,328 by the state of Georgia for once again not being in compliance with toxic emissions standards and safety. Inspectors found that Exide was emitting high levels of lead particulate into the air; over 200% more than the legal limit allows.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtvm.com/story/37688488/exclusive-columbus-battery-plant-fined-after-excessive-amounts-of-lead-pumped-into-the-air|title=EXCLUSIVE: Columbus battery plant fined after excessive amounts of lead pumped into the air|first=Jasmine Agyemang, Chandler|last=Morgan|website=wtvm.com}}</ref> News of Exide's excessive lead emissions has raised concerns among thousands of residents and families that live near Exide's plant on what Exide's practices mean for their health and safety. Several residents have asked that something be done to ensure they and their families are safe and are not exposed to dangerous levels of lead contamination in the air, soil and water where they live.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==Reading, PA (Toxic contamination and ongoing cleanup)==\nExide operates a lead smelter and recycled lead batteries in Reading, PA. The EPA found that Exide contributed to lead emissions and toxic contaminant releases that impacted the soils in the surrounding community and conditions at the site that required extensive cleanup and remediation of toxic contaminants in the area in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.epa.gov/hwcorrectiveactionsites/hazardous-waste-cleanup-exide-technologies-reading-pennsylvania|title=Hazardous Waste Cleanup: Exide Technologies in Reading, Pennsylvania - US EPA|first=US|last=EPA, OSWER, ORCR, PIID|website=US EPA|date=2015-12-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Exide announced plans to idle their lead-recycling operations in Reading/Laureldale and laid off 150 workers with plans to keep their permits active should they decide to re-open in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.readingeagle.com/article.aspx?id=426179|title=Reading Eagle - Reading, PA - Our City - readingeagle.com|website=www2.readingeagle.com}}</ref> In 2015, Berks County pursued legal action to strengthen air-pollution monitoring near the Exide facility to better protect residents\u2019 health and safety but a federal appeals court denied the County's request to relocate a pollution monitor or install an additional air monitor near the plant. County Commissioner Mark C. Scott noted that the appeal was filed as a preemptive measure to protect the community from air pollution if the Exide plant decides to reopen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/county-keeping-tabs-on-pollution-at-exide-site|title=County keeping tabs on pollution at Exide site - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref>\n\n===Lead contamination from Exide Plant resurfaces after cleanup===\nIn 2017, the Reading Eagle newspaper published a series of stories that focused on a study that found lead levels remain high in the borough despite remediation efforts ordered by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency about two decades ago at hundreds of properties near the Exide plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/how-the-study-was-conducted|title=How the study was conducted - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref>  A team of reporters worked in collaboration with a chemistry professor at Metropolitan State University in Denver to conduct soil studies in Laureldale and found strong signs that decades of toxic emissions from the Exide Technologies' battery factory in Reading are taking their toll on neighboring properties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/editorial-investigation-of-lead-problem-produces-some-results|title=Editorial: Investigation of lead problem produces some results - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref>\n\nNews of the study has raised strong concerns from residents in the community about Exide's past practices and pollution and any impacts it may have had on the health and safety of residents that live near the plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/findings-of-soil-study-show-more-are-warranted-near-exide-plant|title=Findings of soil study show more are warranted near Exide plant - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=Reading Eagle}}</ref> For example, there was a story about one Reading family's plea for help on social media for an investigation into the cause of lead poisoning in their family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/plea-for-help-on-social-media-leads-to-lead-investigation|title=Plea for help on social media leads to lead investigation (VIDEO) - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=Reading Eagle}}</ref> And there was a story about a local high school reunion and \u201ca darker truth\u201d that \u201clocal industry and the pollutants it creates may be to blame\u201d for the above average loss of many classmates over the years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/muhlenberg-grads-remember-classmates|title=Muhlenberg grads remember classmates - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the study and findings of elevated levels of lead near the idled Exide plant, State Sen. Judy Schwank called for review of the original Reading/Laureldale cleanup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/state-sen-judy-schwank-calls-for-review-of-laureldale-cleanup|title=State Sen. Judy Schwank calls for review of Laureldale cleanup - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref> A bipartisan group of lawmakers also created a task force to assess the scope of Pennsylvania's lead problem and recommend changes to the way the state tests and remediates lead contamination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/lawmakers-seek-panel-to-assess-lead-problem|title=Lawmakers seek panel to assess lead problem - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref> The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers grabbed soil samples from six residential properties in Laureldale and Muhlenberg Township to test whether lead concentrations pose a public health risk as part of a federal follow-up to a recent soil study that found high lead concentrations in properties that should have been remediated a decade ago near a now idled battery plant owned by Exide Technologies Inc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20170511/NEWS/305119938/1009|title=Digging for lead again in Laureldale, Muhlenberg Township - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref> In late 2017, the federal EPA commenced cleanup of soil contaminated with lead from the idled Exide plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/epa-cleaning-up-soil-contamined-with-lead-in-muhlenberg#.WkvByVVKupo|title=EPA cleaning up soil contaminated with lead in Muhlenberg - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref> The breadth and cost of the cleanup is ongoing and there is no reporting to suggest that Exide is being held financially accountable for the toxic cleanup; taxpayers appear to be on the hook for the new remediation and cleanup costs.\n\n==Bristol, TN==\nIn 2008, it was reported that Exide was emitting two times the amount of pollutants allowed into the environment at their secondary lead acid battery smelter plant in Bristol, TN.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldcourier.com/news/focus-on-exide-s-pollution-too/article_df31f2ac-d121-5a51-937a-175fa9c63e21.html|title=Focus On Exide's Pollution, Too|first=Letters to The|last=Editor|website=heraldcourier.com}}</ref> Instead of correcting their behavior, Exide asked the state to raise the emissions limit by two times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldcourier.com/news/battery-maker-seeks-permission-to-increase-release-of-pollutants/article_d42be6eb-24c2-590d-a39a-80076f0cf70a.html|title=Battery maker seeks permission to increase release of pollutants|first=Gary B. Gray/Bristol Herald|last=Courier|website=heraldcourier.com}}</ref> It was also reported that Exide was doing its own testing and that the Tennessee Division of Air Pollution Control appeared to have no idea of the level of pollution coming from the Bristol plant.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nIn 2013, Exide idled the facility and laid off hundreds of Bristol employees after having received $34.3 million in federal taxpayer stimulus money and as much as $15 million in state tax incentives for their plants in Bristol, TN and Columbus, GA. Instead of investing that taxpayer money, as promised, in Bristol, and creating new jobs, Exide closed the plant \"as part of a strategic initiative to have other manufacturing locations running near capacity.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sullivan-county.com/w/exide.htm|title=Sorry Saga of Exide in Bristol Tennessee|first=Lewis|last=Loflin|website=www.sullivan-county.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldcourier.com/news/local/exide-issues-permanent-layoff-notices-to-employees/article_5db1e594-c987-11e2-8e2f-0019bb30f31a.html |title= Exide issues permanent layoff notices to 68 employees |first= Kevin |last=Castle|newspaper=[[Bristol Herald Courier]] |date=May 30, 2013|access-date=31 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Exide filed an application with the State of Tennessee to resume partial operations at the idled facility in Bristol, TN. Hundreds of residents expressed concerns about Exide's resumed operation of the plant in Bristol and demanded a public meeting on Exide's application.;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldcourier.com/news/exide-wants-to-restart-part-of-bristol-battery-plant-local/article_20e1c5d2-3b3f-51d5-85d8-8f1cdab53e17.html|title=Exide wants to restart part of Bristol battery plant; local residents worried about air quality |first= Tammy |last=Childress |date=March 15, 2017 |newspaper=[[Bristol Herald Courier]]|access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://patch.com/tennessee/east-nashville/keep-bristol-safe-say-no-exide-s-plans-pollute-bristol |title=Keep Bristol Safe \u2013 Say NO to Exide's Plans to Pollute in Bristol |date=29 March 2017 |website= patch.com}}</ref> Giving in to mounting pressure for a public meeting and a cry for more safety monitoring in light of Exide's long record of fines and violations for emissions and safety practices, Exide elected to withdraw their application to resume operations in Bristol in April 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wcyb.com/news/tennessee/bristol-tn/exide-technologies-withdraws-application-to-reopen-news-5-uncovers-dozens-of-violations-in-its-past/515028850|title=Exide Technologies withdraws...|first=Kristi|last=OConnor|website=wcyb.com|date=2017-05-26}}</ref>\n\n==Frisco, TX (Toxic contamination and cleanup)==\nFrom 2001 to 2012, Exide Technologies received 50 written notices of violation for unsafe working conditions at their Frisco lead-acid battery recycling plant.<ref name=\"leadfreefrisco.com1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leadfreefrisco.com/2012/05/connect-the-dotsmedia-round-up-thanks-to-tceq-friscos-lead-legacy-continues-exide-gets-13-more-months-to-dump-another-ton-of-lead-over-frisco/|title=CONNECT THE DOTS/MEDIA ROUND-UP: Thanks to TCEQ, Frisco's Lead Legacy continues; Exide gets 13 more months to dump another ton of lead over Frisco - Lead Free Frisco|website=www.leadfreefrisco.com}}</ref> The Texas Commission on Environmental Quality (TCEQ) found 27 violations at the plant that occurred between March 31, 2009 and June 30, 2010. The TCEQ listed 12 violations which included soil and water contamination and evidence of toxic discharges that raised concerns about effects on downstream waters. Between May and June 2011, the TCEQ conducted four separate investigations on Exide's Frisco facility and found dangerous levels of lead and cadmium compounds that qualify the facility for [[Superfund]] site status.<ref name=\"leadfreefrisco.com1\"/>\n \nThe Exide plant ceased operations in 2012 following a $45 million agreement with the city of Frisco to transfer a 180-acre buffer zone surrounding the plant to the city while the company would keep the 90 acres of land the plant occupies. As part of the requirements of the deal, Exide is required to clean the land to federally acceptable standards before transferring it to the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://starlocalmedia.com/friscoenterprise/news/former-exide-employee-says-plant-fabricated-incident-reports/article_5bc1e4c9-4c28-5232-bf45-c53ed16f9a09.html|title=Former Exide employee says plant fabricated incident reports|first=Anthony Tosie, atosie@starlocalnews.com, @anthonytosie on|last=Twitter|website=starlocalmedia.com}}</ref> Exide has been unwilling to cooperate with the City of Frisco who has shown that Exide has been downplaying the amount of pollution on its site to minimize the cost of the remediation that is required for the site closure. In addition, Frisco's spokesperson Dana Baird, said that the city's estimated $20 million allocated for remediation would not be enough to for the cleanup cost.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/frisco/2014/10/11/frisco-accuses-exide-of-minimizing-cleanup-at-closed-plant|title=Frisco accuses Exide of minimizing cleanup at closed plant|date=11 October 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.friscotexas.gov/459/Exide-Technologies-Related-Information|title=Exide Technologies & Related Information - Frisco, TX - Official Website|website=www.friscotexas.gov}}</ref>\n\n==Community's responses==\nCommunity activists are driving a growing national conversation about environmental justice, the idea that communities of all races and incomes should have the same kind of environmental quality and protection.<ref name=\"governing.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.governing.com/topics/transportation-infrastructure/gov-mark-lopez-east-yard-environmental-justice-exide-lead-poisoning.html|title=The Fight for Environmental Justice and the Rise of Citizen Activism|website=www.governing.com}}</ref> One of the leaders of this movement, mark! Lopez, recently received the 2017 Goldman Environmental Prize, for the work he did with his Southeast L.A. based community group, East Yard Communities for Environmental Justice<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eycej.org/author/mlopez/|title=mark! Lopez|website=East Yard Communities for Environmental Justice}}</ref> addressing the devastating lead contamination in east and southeast L.A., where the Exide lead-acid battery recycling plant had violated environmental regulations for more than 30 years as state regulators turned a blind eye.<ref name=\"governing.com\"/> Lopez et al. pressured state lawmakers to take action on the Exide plant after decades of complaints about the plant from residents went unanswered.<ref name=\"governing.com\"/>\n\nCommunity activists and environmental scholars, have effectively argued that major industrial polluters, like Exide, have been able to release massive amounts of pollution by exploiting government inaction regarding poor and minority populations that often live near these major sources of pollution.<ref name=\"wellesley.edu\">{{cite web |url=https://repository.wellesley.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1012&context=library_awards |title=Fighting for Environmental Health and Justice: A Case Study of Exide Technologies in Southeast Los Angeles, California|publisher=[[Wellesley College]]|department=Wellesley College Digital Scholarship and Archive|first=Idalmis |last=Vaquero|website=hrepository.wellesley.edu}}</ref> Specifically, it has been proposed that Exide has been protected by local regulatory agencies so that the company has little responsibility in low-income, minority communities.<ref name=\"wellesley.edu\"/> For example, at a South Coast Air Quality Management District (SCAQMD) board hearing, the mayor of Maywood, Oscar Magana, thought that the Department of Toxic Substances Control and the SCAQMD, would have closed the Exide plant in Vernon much sooner if it had been placed in Beverly Hills, or another affluent community.<ref name=\"wellesley.edu\"/>\n\n==Sears Battery fraud scandal==\nIn March 2001, Exide plead guilty to fraud conspiracy charges and agreed to pay a fine of $27.5 million to end a federal criminal investigation into auto battery sales to customers of [[Sears, Roebuck & Company]]. The case arose from investigations and accusations that Exide conspired with Sears to sell used batteries as new to Sears customers and that Exide officials had paid [[bribes]] to conceal the [[fraud]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/24/business/exide-will-pay-27-million-in-fraud-case.html|title=Exide Will Pay $27 Million in Fraud Case|work=Bloomberg News|date= March 24, 2001|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn 2002, two former top executives of Exide Technologies were sentenced to prison for their scheme to sell defective batteries to Sears, Roebuck & Co. Former Exide president Douglas N. Pearson was sentenced to five years and four months in prison and ordered to pay a $150,000 fine. Pearson's accomplice, former Exide chief executive Arthur M. Hawkins, was sentenced to 10 years in prison and ordered to pay a $1 million fine. The two were convicted of [[wire fraud]] and [[conspiracy]] to commit wire fraud in a huge scheme to sell defective Exide batteries to Sears for its [[DieHard (brand)|Die-hard battery]] line.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michigansthumb.com/news/article/Ex-Exide-CEO-Sentenced-to-10-Years-7351677.php|title=Ex-Exide CEO Sentenced to 10 Years|website=michigansthumb.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lead contamination in Oakland]]\n*[[Lead contamination in Washington, D.C. drinking water]]\n*[[Lead poisoning epidemics]]\n*[[Flint water crisis]]\n*[[Pemaco Maywood]]: former chemical mixing facility located on the [[Los Angeles River]]\n*[[Porter Ranch gas leak]]\n*[[Eight Mile, Alabama]] - site of mercaptan spill\n*{{C|Superfund sites in California}}\n\n==References==\n\n<!--List-defined references are placed below in chronological order by date of publication instead of in body of article. Please invoke each reference in the content using <ref name=\"name\"/>.-->\n\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"NYT 2011-12-09\">{{Citation |last1=Rosenthal |first1=Elisabeth |last2=Lehren |first2=Andrew W. |last3=Zabludovsky |first3=Karla |last4=Agren |first4=David |last-author-amp=yes|date=8 Dec 2011 |accessdate=5 February 2016 |title=Lead From Old U.S. Batteries Sent to Mexico Raises Risks |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/09/science/earth/recycled-battery-lead-puts-mexicans-in-danger.html }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"KPPC \">{{cite web|url=http://projects.scpr.org/timelines/exide-shutdown-timeline/|title=Timeline: Exide's run-ins with regulators |work=[[Southern California Public Radio]]|access-date=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2014-08-16\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/science/la-me-0816-exide-feds-20140816-story.html|title=Federal grand jury investigating Exide Technologies over Vernon plant|first=Tony |last=Barboza|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 15, 2014|access-date=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NBC 2014-12=05\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Second-Phase-of-Exide-Recycling-Plant-Cleanup-Due-to-Begin-in-Vernon-284856471.html|title=Second Phase of Exide Recycling Plant Cleanup Begins|work=[[NBC Southern California]]|first1=Michael |last1=Larkin |first2=Toni |last2=Guinyard|last-author-amp=yes|date=December 5, 2014|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2015-03-12\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-exide-plant-closes-victory-20150312-htmlstory.html|title=Q&A: Exide closure a long-sought win for working-class neighborhood|first1= Ruben |last1=Vives |first2=Shelby |last2=Grad|last-author-amp=yes|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date= March 12, 2015 |access-date=5 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2015-08-17\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-exide-cleanup-20150817-story.html|title=Exide cleanup: Toxic lead removal could be California's biggest yet|first=Tony |last=Barboza|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date= August 18, 2015|access-date=5 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2015-10-27\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-la-exide-cleanup-county-supervisors-20151027-story.html|title=Exide cleanup: L.A. County approves $2 million to speed lead removal at homes|first=Tony |last=Barboza|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date= October 27, 2015|accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2015-12-21\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-exide-cleanup-story-so-far-20151121-story.html|title=How a battery recycler contaminated L.A.-area homes for decades|first=Tony |last=Barboza|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date= December 21, 2015|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2016-01-26\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-sac-exide-cleanup-legislators-20160126-story.html|title=L.A.-area and state officials call for quicker cleanup of Exide plant contamination|first=Melanie |last=Mason|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date= January 26, 2016|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"KPPC 2016-2-29\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2016/02/29/58081/exide-la-county-crews-begin-testing-soil-for-lead/|title=Exide: LA County crews begin testing soil for lead in Commerce|first=Elizabeth |last=Aguilera |date=February 29, 2016|work=[[Southern California Public Radio]]|accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Sac Bee 14Apr2016\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article71858527.html |title=California Assembly spends millions to clean up Exide plant |first=Jeremy B. |last=White |newspaper=[[Sacramento Bee]] |date=April 14, 2016 |access-date=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=CAP-Radio>{{cite news |url=http://www.capradio.org/71044 |title=Assembly Approves $177M Boost For Battery Plant Clean-Up |first=Ben |last=Bradford |work=[[Capital Public Radio]] |date=April 14, 2016|access-date=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2016-05-28\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-exide-accountability-20160524-snap-story.html |title=For public officials, accountability for Exide lead contamination has been scant |first=Tony |last=Barboza |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date= May 28, 2016 |access-date=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Marketplace\">{{cite news|url=http://www.marketplace.org/2016/05/03/world/cleaning-lead-tougher-without-communitys-trust |title=In Los Angeles, lack of trust makes lead cleanup tougher |first=Jed |last=Kim |work=[[Marketplace (radio program)|Marketplace]] |date=May 5, 2016|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"KPPC 2016-6-10\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2016/06/10/61498/environmental-review-will-delay-expanded-exide-cle/ |title=Environmental review will delay expanded Exide cleanup about a year |work=[[Southern California Public Radio]] |first=Elizabeth |last=Aguilera |date=June 10, 2016 |access-date=12 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"KPPC 2016-8-23\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2016/08/23/63871/lausd-to-begin-removing-lead-tainted-soil-from-2-s/ |title=LAUSD to begin removing lead-tainted soil from 2 schools near Exide |work=[[Southern California Public Radio]] |first=Elizabeth |last=Aguilera |date=August 23, 2016 |access-date=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2017-6-30\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-exide-health-survey-20170630-story.html|title=Many near the Exide plant are concerned about lead poisoning and dissastisfied with its cleanup, survey finds|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=Tony |last=Barboza|date= June 30, 2017|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-ln-exide-what-we-know-20170806-htmlstory.html|title=What we know about California's largest toxic cleanup: Thousands of L.A. County homes tainted with lead|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first1=Tony |last1=Barboza |first2=Ben |last2=Poston|date=August 6, 2017|access-date=1 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2018-05-22\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-exide-parkways-20180522-story.html|title=Lawmakers seek $16 million to expand Exide lead cleanup beyond yards|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=Tony |last=Barboza|date=May 23, 2018|access-date=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT Video\">{{cite web|title=Unsettled: The Exide Story | work=Video: Inside the fight to shut down a dangerous polluter|first1=Bethany |last1=Mollenkof |first2=Spencer |last2=Bakalar |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=14 June 2018|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/85366771-132.html}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Exide lead contamination}}\n* [https://www.dtsc.ca.gov/HazardousWaste/Projects/exide.cfm Project page] at the [[California Department of Toxic Substances Control]]\n* [http://www.aqmd.gov/home/regulations/compliance/exide-updates Project page] at the [[South Coast Air Quality Management District]]\n* [http://www.cityofvernon.org/exide-update Project page] at [[Vernon, California|City of Vernon]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Greater Los Angeles|Environment|California}}\n\n{{Coord|34|0|19|N|118|11|36|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:2015 in California]]\n[[Category:2015 in the environment]]\n[[Category:2015 industrial disasters]]\n[[Category:2015 disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:2015 health disasters]]\n[[Category:Air pollution in California]]\n[[Category:Disasters in California]]\n[[Category:Environmental disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Environmental issues in California]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of Los Angeles County, California]]\n[[Category:Lead poisoning incidents]]\n", "text_old": "{{Tone|date=July 2019}}\n[[File:Pallet of scrap lead-acid automotive batteries (right side).jpg|thumb|Pallet of scrap lead-acid automotive batteries ready to be recycled]]\n[[Exide]] is one of the world's largest producers, distributors and [[Battery recycling|recyclers]] of [[lead-acid batteries]]. Lead-acid batteries are used in automobiles, golf carts, fork-lifts, and motorcycles.  They are recycled by grinding them open, neutralizing the sulfuric acid, and separating the [[polymers]] from the [[lead]] and [[copper]]. In the US, 97 percent of the lead from car batteries is recycled - which is the highest recycling rate for any commodity. Most states require stores to take back old batteries.<ref name=\"NYT 2011-12-09\"/>\n\nSince 2010, operations at seven Exide lead-acid battery plants have been linked to ambient heavy metal levels that posed a health risk to the environment and thousands of residents in neighborhoods surrounding the Exide plants.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/29/local/la-me-exide-pollute-20130530|title=Battery recycler Exide's problems aren't just local|first1=Kim|last1=Christensen|first2=Jessica|last2=Garrison|date=29 May 2013|newspaper=LA Times|access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref> Exide has been found to be a significant source of lead emissions and/or contamination in [[Los Angeles County]]; [[Frisco, Texas]]; [[Muncie, Indiana]]; [[Salina, Kansas]]; [[Bristol, Tennessee]]; [[Reading, Pennsylvania]]; and [[Forest City, Missouri]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Los Angeles County, California (Vernon)==\n[[File:Recycling lead in a lead-acid battery recovery facility.jpg|thumb|right|Recycling lead in a lead-acid battery recovery facility]]\n\nA [[battery recycling]] plant in southeast Los Angeles County, California, United States, emitted toxic metal dust over decades that contaminated as many as 10,000 homes in half a dozen [[working-class]], [[Latino]] communities near the plant.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\"/>  Lead is a neurotoxin that causes harm to most organs, but it most commonly causes cognitive deficits, neurodevelopmental delays, and psychological impairments.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Johnston|first=Jill E.|last2=Hricko|first2=Andrea|date=2017-10-01|title=Industrial Lead Poisoning in Los Angeles: Anatomy of a Public Health Failure|journal=Environmental Justice |volume=10|issue=5|pages=162\u2013167|doi=10.1089/env.2017.0019|issn=1939-4071|pmc=5783279|pmid=30687453}}</ref> [[Exide Technologies]], owner of the [[lead-acid battery]] [[Lead smelter|smelter]] located in [[Vernon, California|Vernon]], agreed in 2015 to close the facility during the massive cleanup of the [[contaminated soil]], which will take years and cost hundreds of millions of dollars.<ref name=\"LAT 2015-12-21\"/>\n\n===Background===\nThe 15-acre battery recycling plant (6.1 ha) is located in Vernon, CA \u2013 a heavily industrialized city in Southeast Los Angeles county<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cityofvernon.org/about-vernon|title=City of Vernon - About Vernon|website=www.cityofvernon.org|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>. The smelter was issued an \u201cinterim status document\u201d by the California Department of Health Services in 1981 and operated under a provisional permit while documented violations were occurring. Exide took ownership of the smelter when they purchased the Gould-National Battery and its assets in 2000.<ref name=\"KPPC \"/><ref name=\"LAT 2015-03-12\"/> In 2013, Exide was under federal criminal investigation for emitting high levels of harmful pollutants from its battery recycling plant in Vernon, CA.<ref name=\"LAT 2014-08-16\"/> Hundreds of residents had complained for years about Exide's toxic emissions before state and federal agencies acted.<ref name=\"LAT Video\"/> In March 2015, the company signed an agreement with the U.S. attorney's office to close permanently.<ref name=\"graphics_exide\">{{Cite web |url=http://graphics.latimes.com/exide-battery-plant/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-06-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404234600/http://graphics.latimes.com/exide-battery-plant/ |archive-date=2018-04-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The deal allowed Exide and its employees to avoid prosecution for years of environmental crimes, including illegal storage, disposal and shipment of hazardous waste, while agreeing to pay $50 million to demolish and clean the plant and surrounding communities, including $9 million set aside for removing lead from homes.<ref name=\"graphics_exide\"/>\n\n===Environmental impact===\n\nThe soil beneath the facility tests high for [[toxic metals]]. The groundwater was also polluted from the operation of the plant and corrosive and irritating sulfates drained onto public streets.<ref name=\"LAT 2015-03-12\"/>\n\nStudies have indicated that as many as 10,000 homes in half a dozen working-class, Latino communities near the plant have had their homes and yards contaminated by the lead emissions. The decades of [[air pollution]] from the Exide Technologies facility has potentially contaminated the nearby communities of  [[Boyle Heights]], [[Maywood, California|Maywood]] [[East Los Angeles, California|East Los Angeles]], [[Commerce, California|Commerce]], [[Bell, California|Bell]], and [[Huntington Park, California|Huntington Park]].<ref name=\"LAT 2015-03-12\"/>\n\nResidents had long been concerned about the air pollution from the plant that was found to have emitted lead, arsenic and other dangerous pollutants over decades. Lead is a potent [[neurotoxin]] that puts children at-risk for [[learning disabilities]], lower [[IQ]]s and other [[Developmental disability|developmental problems]] who may have acquired [[lead poisoning]] from playing outdoors.<ref name=\"LAT 2015-12-21\"/>\n\n=== Public Health Impacts in East Los Angeles ===\nThroughout history, lead exposure has led to public health problems, specifically for workers in factories or other industrial entities.<ref name=\":0\" /> While past measures that prevent lead exposure in the first place have been successful, \u201csecondary prevention\u201d is emphasized by public health agencies now, leaving the people who have already been exposed or who will continually be exposed at risk because lead is still used in the manufacture of batteries, buses, trucks, tractors, and motorcycles.<ref name=\":0\" /> As a result, Low income communities and communities of color face a major gap in the public health system for lead exposure prevention.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAccording to \u201cIndustrial Lead Poisoning in Los Angeles: Anatomy of a Public Health Failure\u201d in the Journal of Environmental Justice, Southeastern Los Angeles has similar gaps and failures of lead prevention as in the [[Flint water crisis|Flint Michigan Water Crisis]].<ref name=\":0\" />  Since the 1970\u2019s, Exide had been operating in Vernon. In 2013, AQMD explained that upwards of 250,000 residents in East Los Angeles face a chronic health hazard from lead and arsenic exposure from Exide.<ref>South Coast Air Quality Management District, ''Lead Monitoring at Exide Technologies'', 2014.</ref> Communities living near Exide such as Boyle Heights and Maywood are more than 90% Latino and rank among the top 10% of most environmentally burdened areas in California.<ref name=\":0\" /> More than 90% of homes in the area were built before the 1978 ban on lead paint and many directly neighbor freeways and truck routes which resulted in decades of exposure to leaded gasoline which contaminated soil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://egis3.lacounty.gov/dataportal/2017/12/12/assessor-parcels-2016-tax-roll/|title=Assessor Parcels \u2013 2016 Tax Roll|date=2017-12-12|website=Los Angeles County GIS Data Portal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref><ref>Mielke, HW, et al, Science of the Total Environment 408; (2010) 3965\u20133975</ref><ref>Laidlaw MAS, Zahran S, Pingitore N, Clague J, Devlin G, Taylor MP. 2014. Identification of lead sources in residential environments: Sydney, Australia. Environ Pollut 184: 238\u2013246.</ref> Lead exposure is especially prevalent in soil, water, and dust; it has the most impact on the children and workers around Vernon. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2019, a study conducted by the University of Southern California found a high amount of lead in baby teeth of children in Boyle Heights, Maywood, East Los Angeles, Commerce, and Huntington park.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.usc.eduhttps//news.usc.edu/156523/lead-in-baby-teeth-exide-battery-plant/|title=Lead contamination found in baby teeth of children living near Exide battery plant|date=2019-05-06|website=USC News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Johnston|first=Jill E.|last2=Franklin|first2=Meredith|last3=Roh|first3=Hannah|last4=Austin|first4=Christine|last5=Arora|first5=Manish|date=2019-05-21|title=Lead and Arsenic in Shed Deciduous Teeth of Children Living Near a Lead-Acid Battery Smelter|journal=Environmental Science & Technology|volume=53|issue=10|pages=6000\u20136006|doi=10.1021/acs.est.9b00429|pmid=31056909|issn=0013-936X|bibcode=2019EnST...53.6000J}}</ref> The lead in the baby teeth matched with soil contamination data from the California Department of Toxic Substances Control.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Truth Fairy study revealed that children in Boyle Heights and East L.A. have the highest exposure to lead, which most likely came through winds carrying soil in utero from their mother or post birth. The study urges legislators to create initiatives to prevent lead exposure. Jill Johnston, co author of the study and professor of preventive medicine explains, \u201chigher lead in teeth means higher lead in the brain, kidney and bones. Testing women for lead during pregnancy, or even earlier, as they enter child-bearing age, may be needed to decrease lead exposure to their future offspring.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Testing and clean-up===\n[[File:DRAFT-EXIDE-OPTION-1E.JPG|thumb|DTSC Preliminary Area of Investigation map]]\n\nThe facility closure is overseen by the California Department of Toxic Substances Control (DTSC) and the South Coast Air Quality Management District (SCAQMD). The closure includes dismantling the former recycling facility under a full enclosure tent, under negative pressure, preventing emissions from leaving the premises. Hazardous materials from the facility are recycled or disposed of under DTSC oversight.<ref>American Integrated Services, Inc. (2017, October 22). Closure Implementation Plan. Retrieved February 25, 2020, from <nowiki>https://dtsc.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/31/2018/03/Closure-Implementation-Plan_10-22-17.pdf</nowiki></ref>\n\nThe cleanup of the soil contaminated with lead is being overseen by the [[California Department of Toxic Substances Control]].<ref name=\"LAT 2016-01-26\" /> In August 2015, the department announced that soil testing had shown that the toxic dust had deposited lead in as many as 10,000 homes.  Department officials said that they had not previously been involved in a lead cleanup case in which the number of properties was this high.<ref name=\"LAT 2015-08-17\" />\n\nNineteen homes received first priority for cleanup starting in December 2014 based on the test results.<ref name=\"NBC 2014-12=05\"/> The residents of two neighborhoods in Boyle Heights and Maywood were notified in August 2015 that they could have their soil tested for lead after being identified by the [[South Coast Air Quality Management District]] as the communities most likely to have been contaminated by the lead emissions. Contaminated soil was removed and replaced at 146 of the homes closest to the facility in these communities.<ref name=\"LAT 2015-08-17\"/><ref name=\"KPPC 2016-6-10\"/>\n\nIn October 2015 the [[Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors]], frustrated with the slow pace by the state, designated $2 million to \u201cfacilitate\" the cleanup effort by hiring contractors and consultants, performing soil testing at 1,000 homes during the following two months, and sending community outreach workers to neighborhoods around the plant. A timeline and strategy was also included in the resolution to force state regulators, Exide \"and other responsible parties to fully fund and undertake this cleanup.\u201d The state had used all but $1 million of $9 million Exide placed in a trust fund for residential cleanup.<ref name=\"LAT 2015-10-27\"/> By the end of February 2016, county crews began testing soil at homes in Commerce.<ref name=\"KPPC 2016-2-29\"/> The state allocated $176.6 million for the cost of testing and cleanup of about 2,500 of the most contaminated yards. Job training program for community members to be employed in cleanup has been planned by the Department of Toxic Substances Control. It is also establishing a local office to improve and coordinate information-sharing efforts. Local community groups are working with the agency for outreach in signing up residents for testing.<ref name=\"Marketplace\"/>\n\nHigh lead levels were found in the soil at Lorena and Rowan Elementary Schools in the summer of 2015 by the Department of Toxic Substances Control.<ref name=\"KPPC 2016-8-23\"/><ref name=\"LAT 2017-6-30\"/>\n\nIn fall 2017, the Department of Toxic Substances Control began to implement their plans to remove lead-contaminated soil from 2,500 residential properties near the closed Exide Technologies lead acid battery plant in Vernon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-exide-cleanup-plan-20170706-story.html|title=State releases plan to clean lead contamination from 2,500 parcels near closed battery recycler Exide|date=July 7, 2017|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> It is believed to be the largest environmental cleanup effort of its kind in California history, encompassing seven (7) Los Angeles County neighborhoods. California state regulators estimate that Exide's operations may have threatened the health of an estimated 100,000 people and 10,000 residential properties.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\"/> A total of $192 million has been authorized by the state for the massive cleanup effort; $176.6 million of which was approved by Governor Jerry Brown in April 2016.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\"/>\n\nThe $192 million set aside by the State will only allow for cleanup of 2,500 of the estimated 10,000 homes and properties believed to have been contaminated by Exide's decades of pollution. Total costs to clean up the estimated 10,000 homes contaminated by Exide's pollution is believed to be over $500 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/news/11613080/state-aims-to-close-funding-gap-for-lead-contamination-cleanup-neighbors-skeptical|title=State Aims to Close Funding Gap for Lead Contamination Cleanup, Neighbors Skeptical|date=August 24, 2017|website=KQED}}</ref> By August 2016, over $42 million of the $192 million had already been spent.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\"/>\n\nFacing mounting pressure from community activists, residents, and elected officials, to hold Exide, and not taxpayers, accountable for millions of dollars of additional money needed to clean up Exide's toxic lead mess in east L.A. County, the South Coast Air Quality Management District filed claims against Exide totaling over $80 million.<ref name=\"law360_1007567\">{{cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/1007567/exide-says-air-regulator-s-claim-is-barred-by-ch-11-plan|title=Exide Says Air Regulator's Claim Is Barred By Ch. 11 Plan - Law360|website=www.law360.com}}</ref> Exide filed its own lawsuit<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.documentcloud.org/documents/3893790-April-2016-lawsuit-filed-by-Exide-Technologies.html|title=April 2016 lawsuit filed by Exide Technologies against California...|first=Tony Barboza (Los Angeles|last=Times)|website=www.documentcloud.org}}</ref> in 2016 seeking blood lead data on people tested in L.A. County, including each person's age, city and ZIP Code; the age of the home in which each person lived; and any causes of lead poisoning. The state is fighting the lawsuit in court, calling it an attempt by Exide to dodge financial responsibility and blame the contamination on lead paint and gasoline.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\"/> Paying for the cleanup might admit guilt that could lead to criminal charges and jail time for executives.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\"/>\n\nOn January 31, 2018, Exide Technologies told a bankruptcy judge that their company is not responsible for the $80 million in additional cleanup costs the state of California is trying to recoup, and that the State's claim should be discharged as part of the company's Chapter 11 bankruptcy plan in 2015.<ref name=\"law360_1007567\"/>  Unless the bankruptcy judge rules against Exide, it is likely that taxpayers will be pay for the clean up.{{Fact|date=January 2020}}\n\nCalifornia\u2019s state auditor will investigate how the Department of Toxic Substances Control is handling cleanup after the Joint Committee on Legislative Audit voted in February 2020 to probe contracts, cleanup times, and other issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.bloombergenvironment.com/environment-and-energy/california-to-probe-former-battery-recycling-site-cleanup|title=California to Probe Former Battery Recycling Site Cleanup|last=Dooley|first=Emily C.|date=February 26, 2020|website=Bloomberg Environment|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\n\nThe state had dedicated about $7 million to test and clean up homes in 2015.<ref name=\"LAT 2016-01-26\"/>  The state assembly voted in 2016 to provide $176.6 million for the cleanup.<ref name=\"Sac Bee 14Apr2016\"/><ref name=CAP-Radio/> State legislators held an informational hearing at the Capitol on January 26, 2016 where Assemblyman [[Jimmy Gomez]] (D-Echo Park) noted the rapid mobilization for the [[Porter Ranch gas leak]] near a wealthier community while the slow progress in these neighborhoods where most residents are Latino and low-income should be disheartening to all legislators. Gomez said \"We don't want to send the wrong message. That if you live ... in Porter Ranch that you're more important than the folks that live in East ... or Southeast Los Angeles.\"<ref name=\"LAT 2016-01-26\"/>\n\nAt the January 26, 2016 hearing, Assembly Speaker [[Anthony Rendon (politician)|Anthony Rendon]] (D-Lakewood) said the Department of Toxic Substances Control \"has not done a good job\" and that he would urge officials to act more urgently on the clean-up.<ref name=\"LAT 2016-01-26\"/> The extent and duration of the lead contamination has raised concerns about longstanding problems at the department. The Governor and state legislators saw this as an wake-up call to seek new laws, hold oversight hearings, and work on other reform efforts.<ref name=\"LAT 2016-05-28\"/>\n\nIn May 2018, the CA state Assembly approved a budget action<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abgt.assembly.ca.gov/sites/abgt.assembly.ca.gov/files/May%20Revise%20Sub%203%20%20May%2023%20-%20Energy%20and%20Transportation.pdf |title=Energy and Transportation |website=abgt.assembly.ca.gov |access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> and legislation, AB 2189, to commit $16 million in funds for cleaning public parkways.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billTextClient.xhtml?bill_id=201720180AB2189|title=Bill Text - AB-2189 Hazardous substances: lead: cleanup: Exide Technologies facility.|website=leginfo.legislature.ca.gov}}</ref> The funding would come from a bill the CA state legislature passed in 2016 to raise about $176 million to help clean-up Exide's toxic lead contamination mess in Vernon, and surrounding neighborhoods, by levying a fee on batteries for all battery manufacturers and consumers.<ref name=\"LAT 2018-05-22\"/>\n\nIf AB 2189 is made law, it would raise the cost of the taxpayer-funded Exide cleanup to over $200 million.<ref name=\"LAT 2018-05-22\"/>\n\n==Exide contamination record elsewhere in the U.S.==\n{{Empty-section|date=July 2019}}\n\n==Environmental contamination record==\n\nThe EPA's Lead National Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS) Non-attainment Designations list designates a total of 21 areas and parts of 22 counties across 15 states and Puerto Rico that are in violation of federal air quality health standards for lead emissions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leadfreefrisco.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/LeadNAAreaList.pdf |title=Listings |website=leadfreefrisco.com}}</ref>\n\nExide has operations in six (6) out of the 21 areas that do not meet safe air quality laws; accounting for nearly one-third of the violators (more than any other company).<ref name=\"leadfreefrisco.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leadfreefrisco.com/2011/11/update-epa-list-exide-has-most-plants-in-violation-of-air-safety-laws-for-lead-emissions/|title=UPDATED EPA REPORT - Exide has most plants in violation of air safety laws for lead emissions - Lead Free Frisco|website=www.leadfreefrisco.com}}</ref> The Exide plants in violation of EPA lead emission standards are in Frisco, TX, Vernon, CA, Muncie, IN, Salina, KS, Reading, PA, and Bristol, TN.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.epa.gov/lead-designations|title=Lead Designations - US EPA|first=US|last=EPA, OAR|website=US EPA|date=December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Muncie, IN==\nBetween 1989 and 2015, Exide Technologies released more than 227,275 pounds of toxic pollutants, including dangerous lead, sulfuric acid and arsenic, into the air and water in Muncie, Indiana where they operate a secondary lead acid battery smelter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/opinion/readers/2017/12/16/letters-editor-dec-17/957150001/|title=Letters to the editor, Dec. 17|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref> \nIn November 2010, the City of Muncie, Indiana and Delaware County were placed on the U.S. EPA's nonattainment list for concentrations of toxic lead in the air that are too high to meet national air quality standards for lead due to emissions from the Exide plant in Muncie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ens-newswire.com/ens/nov2010/2010-11-17-091.html|title=Areas Violating Lead Standards Host Smelters, Battery Recyclers|last=staff|website=www.ens-newswire.com}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Exide Technologies agreed to pay an $820,000 civil penalty to settle a lawsuit for violating the Clean Air Act at its Muncie lead smelter plant. According to the U.S. EPA, the violations resulted in increased emissions of lead and particulate matter and may have resulted in increased emissions of total hydrocarbons, volatile organic compounds and dioxin/furans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/news/local/2015/03/18/exide-fined-muncie-pollution/24983753/|title=Exide fined $820,000 for Muncie pollution|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, the Department of Justice and Exide Technologies rejected pleas from the mayor of Muncie, environmental/health groups and three neighborhood associations to install a $31 million in pollution-control equipment at the company's battery recycling facility; like their competitor Quemetco did for their similar lead acid battery plant in nearby Indianapolis. More than a dozen public health, neighborhood, environmental, and public health organizations, led by the Hoosier Environmental Council, had urged the U.S. Department of Justice to add additional pollution controls to the proposed settlement to better protect people in Muncie from lead and arsenic released into the air by Exide. The organizations also asked the DOJ to require Exide to include monitoring for pollutants at Exide's fenceline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muncievoice.com/13035/exide-technologies-gets-a-pass-to-keep-polluting-muncie/|title=Exide Technologies Gets a Pass to Keep Polluting Muncie - Muncie Voice|date=6 October 2015|website=muncievoice.com}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, the Exide plant in Muncie experienced three explosions and leakage issues that were not fully or timely disclosed to the relevant state and federal agencies responsible for ensuring Exide's compliance with state and federal laws and safety protocols.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/news/local/2018/01/05/state-complaint-reveals-explosions-exide/1006794001/|title=State complaint reveals explosions at Exide|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref> Local residents were not made aware of these explosions until nearly a year later, January 2018, raising concerns about any risks to the environment and to the health and safety of hundreds of families that live near the Exide facility.\n\nA year later, in February 2018, it was reported that a local pediatrician and the Delaware County Health Department had informed Indiana state officials in 2017 of cases of Exide Technologies\u2019 workers tracking lead home on their clothing and exposing their children to the toxic metal<ref name=\"thestarpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/news/local/2018/02/07/exide-employees-muncie-reportedly-exposed-kids-lead/314661002/|title=Exide employees in Muncie reportedly exposed kids to lead|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theindychannel.com/news/local-news/delaware-county/parents-who-work-at-delaware-county-plant-may-be-exposing-their-children-to-lead|title=Parents who work at Delaware County plant may be exposing their children to lead|first=Graham Hunter, Katie|last=Cox|date=14 February 2018|website=theindychannel.com}}</ref><ref name=\"wthr.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wthr.com/article/concerns-mount-over-lead-exposure-from-muncie-plant|title=Concerns mount over lead exposure from Muncie plant|date=8 February 2018|website=wthr.com}}</ref>\n\nIt was also reported that the local health department made a complaint on June 20 to the Indiana Department of Environmental Management about \"a recent increase in the amount of elevated blood lead level cases\" reported to local health officials in the community, and that \"several of these cases have revealed connections to the Exide plant\u201d with the \u201cbusiness's activities\u201d being a \u201clikely source of this lead exposure.\"<ref name=\"thestarpress.com\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"wthr.com\"/>\n\nFollowing reports that Exide workers may have exposed their families to lead contamination in Muncie, residents there have expressed broader concerns about Exide's lead-acid battery plant and the toll that Exide's decades of toxic emissions of lead and other contaminants may have had on the health and safety of hundreds of residents that live near the plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/news/local/2018/02/09/idem-denies-public-hearing-exide-permit/318803002/|title=IDEM denies public hearing on Exide permit|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theindychannel.com/news/local-news/delaware-county/muncie/couple-has-lead-concerns-near-muncie-plant|title=Couple has lead concerns living by Muncie plant|first=Graham|last=Hunter|date=14 February 2018|website=theindychannel.com|access-date=23 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215084053/https://www.theindychannel.com/news/local-news/delaware-county/muncie/couple-has-lead-concerns-near-muncie-plant|archive-date=15 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the Indiana Department of Environmental Management's (IDEM) decision not to hold a public meeting on Exide's five-year general operating permit in 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/opinion/contributors/2018/02/24/idem-idle-while-indianas-businesses-pollute-environment/366735002/,|title=IDEM idle while Indiana's businesses pollute environment|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref> dozens of residents took to the streets near the Exide plant in Muncie to decry IDEM's decision and to push for testing of the air, soil and water at the hundreds of homes and properties located near the lead-acid battery plant<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theindychannel.com/news/local-news/delaware-county/dozens-protest-outside-exide-technologies-in-muncie|title=Dozens protest outside Exide Technologies in Muncie|first=TheIndyChannel.com|last=Staff|date=26 February 2018|website=theindychannel.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestarpress.com/story/news/local/2018/02/25/demonstrators-march-front-exide-lead-plant/371400002/|title=Demonstrators march in front of Exide lead plant|website=thestarpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/indiana/articles/2018-02-26/indiana-residents-protest-lead-plant |title=Indiana Residents Protest Lead Plant|date=February 26, 2018|access-date=31 March 2018|agency=Associated Press|website=usnews.com}}</ref>\n\n==Salina, KS (Elevated lead levels in children)==\nExide Technologies operates a large lead-acid battery plant in Salina, KS. Between 1987 and 2015, Exide released over 166,077 pounds of lead, antimony, arsenic and other contaminates into the air and water in Salina.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.homefacts.com/environmentalhazards/Kansas/Saline-County/Salina/Polluter-Exide-Technologies-67401xdbtt413eb.html|title=Exide Technologies in Salina, KS &#124; Homefacts|website=www.homefacts.com}}</ref> Between 2010-2013, and in 2016, Exide exceeded allowed lead concentration release limits over 18 times, in violation of the Clean Air Act,<ref>[http://www.kdheks.gov/bar/airmonitor/lead/Updated_Lead_Monitoring_Results.pdf ]{{dead link|date=July 2019}}</ref> and in 2010, the plant was largely  responsible for the area being designated as one of 16 areas in the nation with concentrations of toxic lead in the air too high to meet national air quality standards for lead according to the EPA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ens-newswire.com/ens/nov2010/2010-11-17-091.html|title=Areas Violating Lead Standards Host Smelters, Battery Recyclers|website=www.ens-newswire.com}}</ref>\n\nGiven Exide's occupation and long history of violations for excessive lead emissions and safety in Salina, several residents over the years have expressed concerns about the plant and have asked about possible correlations to troubling reports and data showing higher numbers of blood lead levels in children in Saline County, where Exide operates, than in surrounding counties and communities in Kansas.<ref name=\"kmuw_saline\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kmuw.org/post/saline-county-residents-express-concerns-about-lead-exposure|title=Saline County Residents Express Concerns About Lead Exposure|first=Bryan|last=Thompson|website=www.kmuw.org}}</ref> Between 2000-2010, the mean blood lead levels in Saline Co. averaged 16.5&nbsp;ug/dL, more than double that of all other counties in Kansas which averaged 7.5&nbsp;ug/dL<ref name=\"keap_EPHT\">{{cite web|url=https://keap.kdhe.state.ks.us/EPHT/misc_reports/Preliminary%20Analysis%20of%20Blood%20Lead%20Levels%20in%20Saline%20County%20and%20other%20Selected%20Areas%20in%20Kansas.pdf?AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1 |title=report |website=keap.kdhe.state.ks.us |access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n\n{{cite web|url=https://keap.kdhe.state.ks.us/EPHT/misc_reports/Preliminary%20Analysis%20of%20Blood%20Lead%20Levels%20in%20Saline%20County%20and%20other%20Selected%20Areas%20in%20Kansas.pdf?AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1 |title=Energy and Transportation |website=keap.kdhe.state.ks.us |access-date=2019-07-17}} and children living in the city of Salina, had a significantly higher mean blood lead level (3.00&nbsp;\u00b5g/dL) compared to children living in all other Kansas zip codes (2.86&nbsp;\u00b5g/dL<ref name=\"keap_EPHT\"/>\n\nIn 2016, the Kansas Department of Health and Environment (KDHE) organized a meeting after tests by local doctors in 2016 found elevated lead levels in the blood of 32 Saline County children \u2014 most of them from Salina.<ref name=\"kmuw_health\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kmuw.org/post/health-officials-concerned-about-lead-exposure-saline-county-kids|title=Health Officials Concerned About Lead Exposure In Saline County Kids|first=Bryan|last=Thompson|website=www.kmuw.org}}</ref> This came on the heels of reports of elevated blood levels being found in 84 Saline County children between 2013-2015.<ref name=\"kmuw_health\"/>\n\nA few residents at the 2016 community meeting asked whether local officials and agencies were investigating any potential correlation or links to the number of children in Salina with elevated levels of toxic lead in their blood, and Exide's lead acid-battery plant in Salina.<ref name=\"kmuw_saline\"/> \nHowever, representatives at KDHE tried to avert the inquires by noting that the Exide plant had reduced their lead emissions each year since 2012, following the EPA's stricter requirements on lead emissions, and some plant renovations, and glossed over the fact that Exide still sent a total of 6,720 pounds of lead into the air during that period (2012-2015).<ref name=\"kmuw_saline\"/> KDHE also failed to mention the potentially bigger problem of cumulative lead and other toxic contaminate build up in the soil and water within a 1-3 mile radius of the plant over the decades the plant has been in operation, and did not demonstrate any intention to test the soil or groundwater of homes and public spaces near the plant for elevated levels of lead and other toxic contaminants.\n\nKDHE representatives also helped point the arrow away from Exide by releasing a map showing where the 32 children with elevated blood levels live, many not adjacent to Exide's plant.<ref name=\"kmuw_saline\"/> However, KDHE representatives failed to mention that no comprehensive blood testing was conducted for families that live near the plant, that results included only reported cases from local doctors whose parents brought their child in for a medical issue or check-in, and that the children of employees who work at the plant, who are exposed daily to lead, live all over the city and not just adjacent to the plant.\n\nTo date, no substantive government action has been taken to address this issue. The contamination source(s) for the disproportionate number of children with elevated blood lead levels in Salina, KS and Saline County, remains an apparent mystery.\n\n==Columbus, GA==\nExide used to operate a secondary lead recycling plant in Columbus that was taken out of service in 1999 and now the plant continues to operate as a lead-acid battery manufacturing facility at 3639 Joy Road.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2017/07/10/epd-fines-columbus-battery-maker-for-lead-release.html |title=News article |website=bizjournals.com}}</ref> Between 1987-2015, Exide released 362,102 pounds of toxic pollutants, including lead and arsenic, in the air and water near their plant in Columbus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://echo.epa.gov/facilities/facility-search|title=Facility Search \u2013 Enforcement and Compliance Data - ECHO - US EPA|website=echo.epa.gov}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Exide was forced to clean up contaminated groundwater in Columbus resulting from their plant and practices. Costs for supplemental investigations, remediation and site closure are ongoing and currently estimated at $13.5 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/813781/000119312504111307/d10k.htm|title=Form 10-K - Exide Technologies|website=www.sec.gov}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Exide received $34.3 million in federal taxpayer money and over $15 million in local tax incentives to boost production of next gen batteries and create more jobs at their plants in Columbus and Bristol, TN but came under fire after shuttering their plant in Bristol not long after taking the taxpayer money and incentives.<ref name=\"leadfreefrisco.com\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Georgia's Environmental Protection Division fined Exide Technologies $41,000 for violating federal emissions standards on lead at their Columbus lead acid battery plant in November and December 2016 and January 2017.<ref>[https://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2017/07/10/epd-fines-columbus-battery-maker-for-lead-release.htm]{{dead link|date=March 2018}}</ref> l<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ledger-enquirer.com/news/local/article160505644.html|title=Columbus battery plant fined $41,000 by state for lead emissions|website=ledger-enquirer.com}}</ref>\n\nJust recently, in 2018, Exide Technologies was fined $11,328 by the state of Georgia for once again not being in compliance with toxic emissions standards and safety. Inspectors found that Exide was emitting high levels of lead particulate into the air; over 200% more than the legal limit allows.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtvm.com/story/37688488/exclusive-columbus-battery-plant-fined-after-excessive-amounts-of-lead-pumped-into-the-air|title=EXCLUSIVE: Columbus battery plant fined after excessive amounts of lead pumped into the air|first=Jasmine Agyemang, Chandler|last=Morgan|website=wtvm.com}}</ref> News of Exide's excessive lead emissions has raised concerns among thousands of residents and families that live near Exide's plant on what Exide's practices mean for their health and safety. Several residents have asked that something be done to ensure they and their families are safe and are not exposed to dangerous levels of lead contamination in the air, soil and water where they live.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==Reading, PA (Toxic contamination and ongoing cleanup)==\nExide operates a lead smelter and recycled lead batteries in Reading, PA. The EPA found that Exide contributed to lead emissions and toxic contaminant releases that impacted the soils in the surrounding community and conditions at the site that required extensive cleanup and remediation of toxic contaminants in the area in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.epa.gov/hwcorrectiveactionsites/hazardous-waste-cleanup-exide-technologies-reading-pennsylvania|title=Hazardous Waste Cleanup: Exide Technologies in Reading, Pennsylvania - US EPA|first=US|last=EPA, OSWER, ORCR, PIID|website=US EPA|date=2015-12-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Exide announced plans to idle their lead-recycling operations in Reading/Laureldale and laid off 150 workers with plans to keep their permits active should they decide to re-open in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.readingeagle.com/article.aspx?id=426179|title=Reading Eagle - Reading, PA - Our City - readingeagle.com|website=www2.readingeagle.com}}</ref> In 2015, Berks County pursued legal action to strengthen air-pollution monitoring near the Exide facility to better protect residents\u2019 health and safety but a federal appeals court denied the County's request to relocate a pollution monitor or install an additional air monitor near the plant. County Commissioner Mark C. Scott noted that the appeal was filed as a preemptive measure to protect the community from air pollution if the Exide plant decides to reopen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/county-keeping-tabs-on-pollution-at-exide-site|title=County keeping tabs on pollution at Exide site - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref>\n\n===Lead contamination from Exide Plant resurfaces after cleanup===\nIn 2017, the Reading Eagle newspaper published a series of stories that focused on a study that found lead levels remain high in the borough despite remediation efforts ordered by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency about two decades ago at hundreds of properties near the Exide plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/how-the-study-was-conducted|title=How the study was conducted - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref>  A team of reporters worked in collaboration with a chemistry professor at Metropolitan State University in Denver to conduct soil studies in Laureldale and found strong signs that decades of toxic emissions from the Exide Technologies' battery factory in Reading are taking their toll on neighboring properties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/editorial-investigation-of-lead-problem-produces-some-results|title=Editorial: Investigation of lead problem produces some results - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref>\n\nNews of the study has raised strong concerns from residents in the community about Exide's past practices and pollution and any impacts it may have had on the health and safety of residents that live near the plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/findings-of-soil-study-show-more-are-warranted-near-exide-plant|title=Findings of soil study show more are warranted near Exide plant - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=Reading Eagle}}</ref> For example, there was a story about one Reading family's plea for help on social media for an investigation into the cause of lead poisoning in their family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/plea-for-help-on-social-media-leads-to-lead-investigation|title=Plea for help on social media leads to lead investigation (VIDEO) - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=Reading Eagle}}</ref> And there was a story about a local high school reunion and \u201ca darker truth\u201d that \u201clocal industry and the pollutants it creates may be to blame\u201d for the above average loss of many classmates over the years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/muhlenberg-grads-remember-classmates|title=Muhlenberg grads remember classmates - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the study and findings of elevated levels of lead near the idled Exide plant, State Sen. Judy Schwank called for review of the original Reading/Laureldale cleanup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/state-sen-judy-schwank-calls-for-review-of-laureldale-cleanup|title=State Sen. Judy Schwank calls for review of Laureldale cleanup - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref> A bipartisan group of lawmakers also created a task force to assess the scope of Pennsylvania's lead problem and recommend changes to the way the state tests and remediates lead contamination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/lawmakers-seek-panel-to-assess-lead-problem|title=Lawmakers seek panel to assess lead problem - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref> The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers grabbed soil samples from six residential properties in Laureldale and Muhlenberg Township to test whether lead concentrations pose a public health risk as part of a federal follow-up to a recent soil study that found high lead concentrations in properties that should have been remediated a decade ago near a now idled battery plant owned by Exide Technologies Inc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20170511/NEWS/305119938/1009|title=Digging for lead again in Laureldale, Muhlenberg Township - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref> In late 2017, the federal EPA commenced cleanup of soil contaminated with lead from the idled Exide plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingeagle.com/news/article/epa-cleaning-up-soil-contamined-with-lead-in-muhlenberg#.WkvByVVKupo|title=EPA cleaning up soil contaminated with lead in Muhlenberg - Reading Eagle - NEWS|website=readingeagle.com}}</ref> The breadth and cost of the cleanup is ongoing and there is no reporting to suggest that Exide is being held financially accountable for the toxic cleanup; taxpayers appear to be on the hook for the new remediation and cleanup costs.\n\n==Bristol, TN==\nIn 2008, it was reported that Exide was emitting two times the amount of pollutants allowed into the environment at their secondary lead acid battery smelter plant in Bristol, TN.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldcourier.com/news/focus-on-exide-s-pollution-too/article_df31f2ac-d121-5a51-937a-175fa9c63e21.html|title=Focus On Exide's Pollution, Too|first=Letters to The|last=Editor|website=heraldcourier.com}}</ref> Instead of correcting their behavior, Exide asked the state to raise the emissions limit by two times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldcourier.com/news/battery-maker-seeks-permission-to-increase-release-of-pollutants/article_d42be6eb-24c2-590d-a39a-80076f0cf70a.html|title=Battery maker seeks permission to increase release of pollutants|first=Gary B. Gray/Bristol Herald|last=Courier|website=heraldcourier.com}}</ref> It was also reported that Exide was doing its own testing and that the Tennessee Division of Air Pollution Control appeared to have no idea of the level of pollution coming from the Bristol plant.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nIn 2013, Exide idled the facility and laid off hundreds of Bristol employees after having received $34.3 million in federal taxpayer stimulus money and as much as $15 million in state tax incentives for their plants in Bristol, TN and Columbus, GA. Instead of investing that taxpayer money, as promised, in Bristol, and creating new jobs, Exide closed the plant \"as part of a strategic initiative to have other manufacturing locations running near capacity.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sullivan-county.com/w/exide.htm|title=Sorry Saga of Exide in Bristol Tennessee|first=Lewis|last=Loflin|website=www.sullivan-county.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldcourier.com/news/local/exide-issues-permanent-layoff-notices-to-employees/article_5db1e594-c987-11e2-8e2f-0019bb30f31a.html |title= Exide issues permanent layoff notices to 68 employees |first= Kevin |last=Castle|newspaper=[[Bristol Herald Courier]] |date=May 30, 2013|access-date=31 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Exide filed an application with the State of Tennessee to resume partial operations at the idled facility in Bristol, TN. Hundreds of residents expressed concerns about Exide's resumed operation of the plant in Bristol and demanded a public meeting on Exide's application.;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldcourier.com/news/exide-wants-to-restart-part-of-bristol-battery-plant-local/article_20e1c5d2-3b3f-51d5-85d8-8f1cdab53e17.html|title=Exide wants to restart part of Bristol battery plant; local residents worried about air quality |first= Tammy |last=Childress |date=March 15, 2017 |newspaper=[[Bristol Herald Courier]]|access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://patch.com/tennessee/east-nashville/keep-bristol-safe-say-no-exide-s-plans-pollute-bristol |title=Keep Bristol Safe \u2013 Say NO to Exide's Plans to Pollute in Bristol |date=29 March 2017 |website= patch.com}}</ref> Giving in to mounting pressure for a public meeting and a cry for more safety monitoring in light of Exide's long record of fines and violations for emissions and safety practices, Exide elected to withdraw their application to resume operations in Bristol in April 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wcyb.com/news/tennessee/bristol-tn/exide-technologies-withdraws-application-to-reopen-news-5-uncovers-dozens-of-violations-in-its-past/515028850|title=Exide Technologies withdraws...|first=Kristi|last=OConnor|website=wcyb.com|date=2017-05-26}}</ref>\n\n==Frisco, TX (Toxic contamination and cleanup)==\nFrom 2001 to 2012, Exide Technologies received 50 written notices of violation for unsafe working conditions at their Frisco lead-acid battery recycling plant.<ref name=\"leadfreefrisco.com1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leadfreefrisco.com/2012/05/connect-the-dotsmedia-round-up-thanks-to-tceq-friscos-lead-legacy-continues-exide-gets-13-more-months-to-dump-another-ton-of-lead-over-frisco/|title=CONNECT THE DOTS/MEDIA ROUND-UP: Thanks to TCEQ, Frisco's Lead Legacy continues; Exide gets 13 more months to dump another ton of lead over Frisco - Lead Free Frisco|website=www.leadfreefrisco.com}}</ref> The Texas Commission on Environmental Quality (TCEQ) found 27 violations at the plant that occurred between March 31, 2009 and June 30, 2010. The TCEQ listed 12 violations which included soil and water contamination and evidence of toxic discharges that raised concerns about effects on downstream waters. Between May and June 2011, the TCEQ conducted four separate investigations on Exide's Frisco facility and found dangerous levels of lead and cadmium compounds that qualify the facility for [[Superfund]] site status.<ref name=\"leadfreefrisco.com1\"/>\n \nThe Exide plant ceased operations in 2012 following a $45 million agreement with the city of Frisco to transfer a 180-acre buffer zone surrounding the plant to the city while the company would keep the 90 acres of land the plant occupies. As part of the requirements of the deal, Exide is required to clean the land to federally acceptable standards before transferring it to the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://starlocalmedia.com/friscoenterprise/news/former-exide-employee-says-plant-fabricated-incident-reports/article_5bc1e4c9-4c28-5232-bf45-c53ed16f9a09.html|title=Former Exide employee says plant fabricated incident reports|first=Anthony Tosie, atosie@starlocalnews.com, @anthonytosie on|last=Twitter|website=starlocalmedia.com}}</ref> Exide has been unwilling to cooperate with the City of Frisco who has shown that Exide has been downplaying the amount of pollution on its site to minimize the cost of the remediation that is required for the site closure. In addition, Frisco's spokesperson Dana Baird, said that the city's estimated $20 million allocated for remediation would not be enough to for the cleanup cost.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/frisco/2014/10/11/frisco-accuses-exide-of-minimizing-cleanup-at-closed-plant|title=Frisco accuses Exide of minimizing cleanup at closed plant|date=11 October 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.friscotexas.gov/459/Exide-Technologies-Related-Information|title=Exide Technologies & Related Information - Frisco, TX - Official Website|website=www.friscotexas.gov}}</ref>\n\n==Community's responses==\nCommunity activists are driving a growing national conversation about environmental justice, the idea that communities of all races and incomes should have the same kind of environmental quality and protection.<ref name=\"governing.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.governing.com/topics/transportation-infrastructure/gov-mark-lopez-east-yard-environmental-justice-exide-lead-poisoning.html|title=The Fight for Environmental Justice and the Rise of Citizen Activism|website=www.governing.com}}</ref> One of the leaders of this movement, mark! Lopez, recently received the 2017 Goldman Environmental Prize, for the work he did with his Southeast L.A. based community group, East Yard Communities for Environmental Justice<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eycej.org/author/mlopez/|title=mark! Lopez|website=East Yard Communities for Environmental Justice}}</ref> addressing the devastating lead contamination in east and southeast L.A., where the Exide lead-acid battery recycling plant had violated environmental regulations for more than 30 years as state regulators turned a blind eye.<ref name=\"governing.com\"/> Lopez et al. pressured state lawmakers to take action on the Exide plant after decades of complaints about the plant from residents went unanswered.<ref name=\"governing.com\"/>\n\nCommunity activists and environmental scholars, have effectively argued that major industrial polluters, like Exide, have been able to release massive amounts of pollution by exploiting government inaction regarding poor and minority populations that often live near these major sources of pollution.<ref name=\"wellesley.edu\">{{cite web |url=https://repository.wellesley.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1012&context=library_awards |title=Fighting for Environmental Health and Justice: A Case Study of Exide Technologies in Southeast Los Angeles, California|publisher=[[Wellesley College]]|department=Wellesley College Digital Scholarship and Archive|first=Idalmis |last=Vaquero|website=hrepository.wellesley.edu}}</ref> Specifically, it has been proposed that Exide has been protected by local regulatory agencies so that the company has little responsibility in low-income, minority communities.<ref name=\"wellesley.edu\"/> For example, at a South Coast Air Quality Management District (SCAQMD) board hearing, the mayor of Maywood, Oscar Magana, thought that the Department of Toxic Substances Control and the SCAQMD, would have closed the Exide plant in Vernon much sooner if it had been placed in Beverly Hills, or another affluent community.<ref name=\"wellesley.edu\"/>\n\n==Sears Battery fraud scandal==\nIn March 2001, Exide plead guilty to fraud conspiracy charges and agreed to pay a fine of $27.5 million to end a federal criminal investigation into auto battery sales to customers of [[Sears, Roebuck & Company]]. The case arose from investigations and accusations that Exide conspired with Sears to sell used batteries as new to Sears customers and that Exide officials had paid [[bribes]] to conceal the [[fraud]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/24/business/exide-will-pay-27-million-in-fraud-case.html|title=Exide Will Pay $27 Million in Fraud Case|work=Bloomberg News|date= March 24, 2001|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn 2002, two former top executives of Exide Technologies were sentenced to prison for their scheme to sell defective batteries to Sears, Roebuck & Co. Former Exide president Douglas N. Pearson was sentenced to five years and four months in prison and ordered to pay a $150,000 fine. Pearson's accomplice, former Exide chief executive Arthur M. Hawkins, was sentenced to 10 years in prison and ordered to pay a $1 million fine. The two were convicted of [[wire fraud]] and [[conspiracy]] to commit wire fraud in a huge scheme to sell defective Exide batteries to Sears for its [[DieHard (brand)|Die-hard battery]] line.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michigansthumb.com/news/article/Ex-Exide-CEO-Sentenced-to-10-Years-7351677.php|title=Ex-Exide CEO Sentenced to 10 Years|website=michigansthumb.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lead contamination in Oakland]]\n*[[Lead contamination in Washington, D.C. drinking water]]\n*[[Lead poisoning epidemics]]\n*[[Flint water crisis]]\n*[[Pemaco Maywood]]: former chemical mixing facility located on the [[Los Angeles River]]\n*[[Porter Ranch gas leak]]\n*[[Eight Mile, Alabama]] - site of mercaptan spill\n*{{C|Superfund sites in California}}\n\n==References==\n\n<!--List-defined references are placed below in chronological order by date of publication instead of in body of article. Please invoke each reference in the content using <ref name=\"name\"/>.-->\n\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"NYT 2011-12-09\">{{Citation |last1=Rosenthal |first1=Elisabeth |last2=Lehren |first2=Andrew W. |last3=Zabludovsky |first3=Karla |last4=Agren |first4=David |last-author-amp=yes|date=8 Dec 2011 |accessdate=5 February 2016 |title=Lead From Old U.S. Batteries Sent to Mexico Raises Risks |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/09/science/earth/recycled-battery-lead-puts-mexicans-in-danger.html }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"KPPC \">{{cite web|url=http://projects.scpr.org/timelines/exide-shutdown-timeline/|title=Timeline: Exide's run-ins with regulators |work=[[Southern California Public Radio]]|access-date=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2014-08-16\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/science/la-me-0816-exide-feds-20140816-story.html|title=Federal grand jury investigating Exide Technologies over Vernon plant|firs