tml|title=L.A.-area and state officials call for quicker cleanup of Exide plant contamination|first=Melanie |last=Mason|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date= January 26, 2016|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"KPPC 2016-2-29\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2016/02/29/58081/exide-la-county-crews-begin-testing-soil-for-lead/|title=Exide: LA County crews begin testing soil for lead in Commerce|first=Elizabeth |last=Aguilera |date=February 29, 2016|work=[[Southern California Public Radio]]|accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Sac Bee 14Apr2016\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article71858527.html |title=California Assembly spends millions to clean up Exide plant |first=Jeremy B. |last=White |newspaper=[[Sacramento Bee]] |date=April 14, 2016 |access-date=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=CAP-Radio>{{cite news |url=http://www.capradio.org/71044 |title=Assembly Approves $177M Boost For Battery Plant Clean-Up |first=Ben |last=Bradford |work=[[Capital Public Radio]] |date=April 14, 2016|access-date=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2016-05-28\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-exide-accountability-20160524-snap-story.html |title=For public officials, accountability for Exide lead contamination has been scant |first=Tony |last=Barboza |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date= May 28, 2016 |access-date=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Marketplace\">{{cite news|url=http://www.marketplace.org/2016/05/03/world/cleaning-lead-tougher-without-communitys-trust |title=In Los Angeles, lack of trust makes lead cleanup tougher |first=Jed |last=Kim |work=[[Marketplace (radio program)|Marketplace]] |date=May 5, 2016|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"KPPC 2016-6-10\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2016/06/10/61498/environmental-review-will-delay-expanded-exide-cle/ |title=Environmental review will delay expanded Exide cleanup about a year |work=[[Southern California Public Radio]] |first=Elizabeth |last=Aguilera |date=June 10, 2016 |access-date=12 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"KPPC 2016-8-23\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2016/08/23/63871/lausd-to-begin-removing-lead-tainted-soil-from-2-s/ |title=LAUSD to begin removing lead-tainted soil from 2 schools near Exide |work=[[Southern California Public Radio]] |first=Elizabeth |last=Aguilera |date=August 23, 2016 |access-date=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2017-6-30\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-exide-health-survey-20170630-story.html|title=Many near the Exide plant are concerned about lead poisoning and dissastisfied with its cleanup, survey finds|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=Tony |last=Barboza|date= June 30, 2017|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2017-8-6\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-ln-exide-what-we-know-20170806-htmlstory.html|title=What we know about California's largest toxic cleanup: Thousands of L.A. County homes tainted with lead|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first1=Tony |last1=Barboza |first2=Ben |last2=Poston|date=August 6, 2017|access-date=1 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT 2018-05-22\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-exide-parkways-20180522-story.html|title=Lawmakers seek $16 million to expand Exide lead cleanup beyond yards|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=Tony |last=Barboza|date=May 23, 2018|access-date=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LAT Video\">{{cite web|title=Unsettled: The Exide Story | work=Video: Inside the fight to shut down a dangerous polluter|first1=Bethany |last1=Mollenkof |first2=Spencer |last2=Bakalar |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=14 June 2018|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/85366771-132.html}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Exide lead contamination}}\n* [https://www.dtsc.ca.gov/HazardousWaste/Projects/exide.cfm Project page] at the [[California Department of Toxic Substances Control]]\n* [http://www.aqmd.gov/home/regulations/compliance/exide-updates Project page] at the [[South Coast Air Quality Management District]]\n* [http://www.cityofvernon.org/exide-update Project page] at [[Vernon, California|City of Vernon]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Greater Los Angeles|Environment|California}}\n\n{{Coord|34|0|19|N|118|11|36|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:2015 in California]]\n[[Category:2015 in the environment]]\n[[Category:2015 industrial disasters]]\n[[Category:2015 disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:2015 health disasters]]\n[[Category:Air pollution in California]]\n[[Category:Disasters in California]]\n[[Category:Environmental disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Environmental issues in California]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of Los Angeles County, California]]\n[[Category:Lead poisoning incidents]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLatino(link changed toHispanic and Latino Americans) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exide_lead_contamination"}
{"title_page": "Esta Noche (gay bar)", "text_new": "{{short description|Bar in San Francisco, California, USA}}\n{{Coord missing|San Francisco County, California}}\n[[File:Vanity Ytinav in front of Esta Noche.png|thumb|Vanity Ytinav in front of Esta Noche]]'''Esta Noche''' \"Tonight\" in [[English language|English]], was a [[gay bar]] located at 3079 16th & [[Mission Street]] in [[San Francisco|San Francisco, California]]. It was the first gay [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]] bar in San Francisco, and it was attractive to many people from the Latino community because it provided a space to drink, party, engage in [[hookup culture]], organize and perform.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://works.bepress.com/horacio_roqueramirez/4/|title=\"\"'Mira, Yo Soy Boricua y Estoy Aqu\u00ed': Rafa Negr\u00f3n's Pan Dulce and the Queer Sonic Latinaje of San Francisco\"\" by Horacio N Roque Ramirez|last=Press|first=Berkeley Electronic|website=works.bepress.com|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> The bar first opened in 1979 and was the last Latino bar standing on 16th Street by 1997.<ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ram\u00edrez|first=Horacio N. Roque|date=2003-01-01|title=\"That's My Place!\": Negotiating Racial, Sexual, and Gender Politics in San Francisco's Gay Latino Alliance, 1975-1983|jstor=3704613|journal=Journal of the History of Sexuality|volume=12|issue=2|pages=224\u2013258|doi=10.1353/sex.2003.0078}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nEsta Noche was founded by two openly gay community members, Anthony Lopez and Manuel Quijano.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online {{!}}|website=Bay Area Reporter|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIt is historically placed as the first gay Latino gay bar, and it has significance due to the discrimination LGBT [[Person of color|people of color]] faced in traditionally popular white gay bars, especially in the [[Castro District, San Francisco|Castro district]]. LGBT people of color often experienced racial slurs, [[Microaggression theory|microaggressions]], and [[Fetishism|fetishization]], as the bars where LGBT people were able to socialize and party were mostly dominated by white men.<ref name=\":0\" /> LGBT people of color were often asked to show multiple forms of identification in these spaces.<ref name=\":0\" />  In addition, Latino men in those spaces would experience racist remarks as well as being overly fetishized for their culture.<ref name=\":0\" /> These experiences led to the creation of Esta Noche.<ref name=\":0\" />  The co-founder of the group [[Gay American Indians]] (GAI), Randy Burns, said that the frustration at this discrimination was also what led his group to form, and members often met at Esta Noche.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=70699|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online {{!}} Gay American Indians <br />celebrate 40 years|website=Bay Area Reporter|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref>\n\nEsta Noche also has its roots in the Gay Latino Alliance (GALA), as one of the GALA members sold their house to buy the bar.<ref name=\":0\" /> GALA and Esta Noche worked together in advertising the space as the gay Latino bar of the [[Mission District, San Francisco|Mission District]] in [[San Francisco]], which ultimately resurfaced tensions that the organization was dealing with.<ref name=\":0\" /> With the establishment of Esta Noche came the shift of gay Latino representation from GALA to the bar life.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:Esta Noche side.jpg|thumb|In March 2008]]\nEsta Noche is defined as a \"[[Working class|working-class]]\" bar.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ramos|first=Iv\u00e1n A.|date=2015-04-03|title=The Dirt That Haunts: Looking at Esta Noche|journal=Studies in Gender and Sexuality|volume=16|issue=2|pages=135\u2013136|doi=10.1080/15240657.2015.1038195|issn=1524-0657}}</ref> The bar served more than people looking for a good time and party; it also provided an important space for those seeking to network with other LGBT people of color. Esta Noche has been defined as a \"community organizing center and host to many fundraisers for health clinics, people with AIDS, and other lower-income populations.\"<ref name=\"The Bay Area Reporter Online\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online |website=Bay Area Reporter|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe bar gave room for comedy nights where famous Latina comedian [[Marga Gomez]] starred.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ebar.com/botg/article.php?sec=botg|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online {{!}}|website=Bay Area Reporter|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> Esta Noche was also famously known for their drag shows; there were sometimes even six shows a week.<ref name=\"sfweekly.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/exhibitionist/2014/03/18/drag-queens-say-farewell-to-mission-institution-esta-noche|title=Drag Queens Say Farewell to Mission Institution Esta Noche|website=SF Weekly|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> A popular drag show was the [[Selena]] nights, in which drag queens dressed and performed as Selena.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.colorlines.com/articles/san-francisco-says-goodbye-iconic-gay-latino-bar-esta-noche|title=San Francisco Says Goodbye to Iconic Gay Latino Bar 'Esta Noche'|last=cl_admin|date=2014-02-27|website=Colorlines|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> Another notable person that Esta Noche collaborated with was [[Diane Felix]].<ref name=\":0\" /> People who went to the bar recalled it as a space where people of color, Latinos in particular, could come together and have a space where they would not receive racist [[discrimination]] or [[homophobia]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o0CRAgAAQBAJ|title=The Routledge Queer Studies Reader|last=Hall|first=Donald E.|last2=Jagose|first2=Annamarie|date=2012-06-04|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135719449|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Recognition ===\nEsta Noche was nominated for the [[San Francisco Pride]] Marshalls. However, they lost to the [[Billy DeFrank Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Community Center|Billy DeFrank LGBT Community Center]] in San Jose, California. They were running against the UCSF Positive Health Program.<ref name=\"The Bay Area Reporter Online\"/>\n\nEsta Noche was featured in the HBO series ''[[Looking (TV series)|Looking]]'' for 2 seasons.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/thesnitch/2014/09/19/looking-is-the-only-action-esta-noche-is-getting-these-days|title=Looking Is The Only Action Esta Noche Is Getting These Days|website=SF Weekly|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> By the recording of the second season in November 2014, the bar was already closed.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n== Closing ==\nIn 2013, Esta Noche was threatened with closure, after the [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors]] adopted new laws related to licensing and permit fees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiegogo.com/projects/393630/fblk|title=Save Esta Noche|website=Indiegogo|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> The club launched a crowdfunding campaign on [[Indiegogo]], but it was unable to secure enough funds to stay open.<ref name=\":2\" /> In early 2014, it was announced the club was closing down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sfist.com/2014/02/26/esta_noche_closing_straight_bar_mov/|title=Esta Noche Closing: SFist|date=2014-02-26|website=SFist - San Francisco News, Restaurants, Events, & Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115173119/https://sfist.com/2014/02/26/esta_noche_closing_straight_bar_mov/|archive-date=2019-11-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> The closing was treated as a significant loss to community members, and the bar was generally perceived as another victim of [[gentrification]]. Many efforts were made to stop the closing of the bar; for example the \"queens of San Francisco drag queens, [[Heklina]] and Anna Conda spearheaded a fundraiser to try to save the venue in May 2014. However, they were unable to save the bar.<ref name=\"sfweekly.com\"/> The closing of the bar has been tied to the increasing of [[property tax]] in the area, which has caused [[gentrification]]. Gentrification has also affected many other Latino bars, which have had to close.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww2.kqed.org/pop/2014/02/27/esta-noche-to-close-nothing-is-sacred-san-francisco/|title=Esta Noche to Close. Nothing is Sacred.|website=KQED Pop|language=en-us|access-date=2016-04-11|date=2014-02-27}}</ref> By 1997, Esta Noche was the only Latino-owned bar standing in 16th Street.\n\nBond, another night club, now sits in place of Esta Noche.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bondbarsf.com/#intro|title=Home|website=Bond Bar|access-date=2016-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[LGBT culture in San Francisco]] \n* [[Racism in the LGBT community]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:1979 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:2014 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:Defunct LGBT nightclubs in California| ]]\n[[Category:LGBT drinking establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bar in San Francisco, California, USA}}\n{{Coord missing|San Francisco County, California}}\n[[File:Vanity Ytinav in front of Esta Noche.png|thumb|Vanity Ytinav in front of Esta Noche]]'''Esta Noche''' \"Tonight\" in [[English language|English]], was a [[gay bar]] located at 3079 16th & [[Mission Street]] in [[San Francisco|San Francisco, California]]. It was the first gay [[Latino]] bar in San Francisco, and it was attractive to many people from the Latino community because it provided a space to drink, party, engage in [[hookup culture]], organize and perform.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://works.bepress.com/horacio_roqueramirez/4/|title=\"\"'Mira, Yo Soy Boricua y Estoy Aqu\u00ed': Rafa Negr\u00f3n's Pan Dulce and the Queer Sonic Latinaje of San Francisco\"\" by Horacio N Roque Ramirez|last=Press|first=Berkeley Electronic|website=works.bepress.com|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> The bar first opened in 1979 and was the last Latino bar standing on 16th Street by 1997.<ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ram\u00edrez|first=Horacio N. Roque|date=2003-01-01|title=\"That's My Place!\": Negotiating Racial, Sexual, and Gender Politics in San Francisco's Gay Latino Alliance, 1975-1983|jstor=3704613|journal=Journal of the History of Sexuality|volume=12|issue=2|pages=224\u2013258|doi=10.1353/sex.2003.0078}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nEsta Noche was founded by two openly gay community members, Anthony Lopez and Manuel Quijano.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online {{!}}|website=Bay Area Reporter|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIt is historically placed as the first gay Latino gay bar, and it has significance due to the discrimination LGBT [[Person of color|people of color]] faced in traditionally popular white gay bars, especially in the [[Castro District, San Francisco|Castro district]]. LGBT people of color often experienced racial slurs, [[Microaggression theory|microaggressions]], and [[Fetishism|fetishization]], as the bars where LGBT people were able to socialize and party were mostly dominated by white men.<ref name=\":0\" /> LGBT people of color were often asked to show multiple forms of identification in these spaces.<ref name=\":0\" />  In addition, Latino men in those spaces would experience racist remarks as well as being overly fetishized for their culture.<ref name=\":0\" /> These experiences led to the creation of Esta Noche.<ref name=\":0\" />  The co-founder of the group [[Gay American Indians]] (GAI), Randy Burns, said that the frustration at this discrimination was also what led his group to form, and members often met at Esta Noche.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=70699|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online {{!}} Gay American Indians <br />celebrate 40 years|website=Bay Area Reporter|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref>\n\nEsta Noche also has its roots in the Gay Latino Alliance (GALA), as one of the GALA members sold their house to buy the bar.<ref name=\":0\" /> GALA and Esta Noche worked together in advertising the space as the gay Latino bar of the [[Mission District, San Francisco|Mission District]] in [[San Francisco]], which ultimately resurfaced tensions that the organization was dealing with.<ref name=\":0\" /> With the establishment of Esta Noche came the shift of gay Latino representation from GALA to the bar life.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:Esta Noche side.jpg|thumb|In March 2008]]\nEsta Noche is defined as a \"[[Working class|working-class]]\" bar.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ramos|first=Iv\u00e1n A.|date=2015-04-03|title=The Dirt That Haunts: Looking at Esta Noche|journal=Studies in Gender and Sexuality|volume=16|issue=2|pages=135\u2013136|doi=10.1080/15240657.2015.1038195|issn=1524-0657}}</ref> The bar served more than people looking for a good time and party; it also provided an important space for those seeking to network with other LGBT people of color. Esta Noche has been defined as a \"community organizing center and host to many fundraisers for health clinics, people with AIDS, and other lower-income populations.\"<ref name=\"The Bay Area Reporter Online\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online |website=Bay Area Reporter|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe bar gave room for comedy nights where famous Latina comedian [[Marga Gomez]] starred.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ebar.com/botg/article.php?sec=botg|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online {{!}}|website=Bay Area Reporter|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> Esta Noche was also famously known for their drag shows; there were sometimes even six shows a week.<ref name=\"sfweekly.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/exhibitionist/2014/03/18/drag-queens-say-farewell-to-mission-institution-esta-noche|title=Drag Queens Say Farewell to Mission Institution Esta Noche|website=SF Weekly|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> A popular drag show was the [[Selena]] nights, in which drag queens dressed and performed as Selena.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.colorlines.com/articles/san-francisco-says-goodbye-iconic-gay-latino-bar-esta-noche|title=San Francisco Says Goodbye to Iconic Gay Latino Bar 'Esta Noche'|last=cl_admin|date=2014-02-27|website=Colorlines|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> Another notable person that Esta Noche collaborated with was [[Diane Felix]].<ref name=\":0\" /> People who went to the bar recalled it as a space where people of color, Latinos in particular, could come together and have a space where they would not receive racist [[discrimination]] or [[homophobia]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o0CRAgAAQBAJ|title=The Routledge Queer Studies Reader|last=Hall|first=Donald E.|last2=Jagose|first2=Annamarie|date=2012-06-04|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135719449|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Recognition ===\nEsta Noche was nominated for the [[San Francisco Pride]] Marshalls. However, they lost to the [[Billy DeFrank Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Community Center|Billy DeFrank LGBT Community Center]] in San Jose, California. They were running against the UCSF Positive Health Program.<ref name=\"The Bay Area Reporter Online\"/>\n\nEsta Noche was featured in the HBO series ''[[Looking (TV series)|Looking]]'' for 2 seasons.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/thesnitch/2014/09/19/looking-is-the-only-action-esta-noche-is-getting-these-days|title=Looking Is The Only Action Esta Noche Is Getting These Days|website=SF Weekly|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> By the recording of the second season in November 2014, the bar was already closed.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n== Closing ==\nIn 2013, Esta Noche was threatened with closure, after the [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors]] adopted new laws related to licensing and permit fees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiegogo.com/projects/393630/fblk|title=Save Esta Noche|website=Indiegogo|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> The club launched a crowdfunding campaign on [[Indiegogo]], but it was unable to secure enough funds to stay open.<ref name=\":2\" /> In early 2014, it was announced the club was closing down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sfist.com/2014/02/26/esta_noche_closing_straight_bar_mov/|title=Esta Noche Closing: SFist|date=2014-02-26|website=SFist - San Francisco News, Restaurants, Events, & Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115173119/https://sfist.com/2014/02/26/esta_noche_closing_straight_bar_mov/|archive-date=2019-11-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> The closing was treated as a significant loss to community members, and the bar was generally perceived as another victim of [[gentrification]]. Many efforts were made to stop the closing of the bar; for example the \"queens of San Francisco drag queens, [[Heklina]] and Anna Conda spearheaded a fundraiser to try to save the venue in May 2014. However, they were unable to save the bar.<ref name=\"sfweekly.com\"/> The closing of the bar has been tied to the increasing of [[property tax]] in the area, which has caused [[gentrification]]. Gentrification has also affected many other Latino bars, which have had to close.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww2.kqed.org/pop/2014/02/27/esta-noche-to-close-nothing-is-sacred-san-francisco/|title=Esta Noche to Close. Nothing is Sacred.|website=KQED Pop|language=en-us|access-date=2016-04-11|date=2014-02-27}}</ref> By 1997, Esta Noche was the only Latino-owned bar standing in 16th Street.\n\nBond, another night club, now sits in place of Esta Noche.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bondbarsf.com/#intro|title=Home|website=Bond Bar|access-date=2016-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[LGBT culture in San Francisco]] \n* [[Racism in the LGBT community]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:1979 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:2014 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:Defunct LGBT nightclubs in California| ]]\n[[Category:LGBT drinking establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLatino(link changed toHispanic and Latino Americans) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esta_Noche_(gay_bar)"}
{"title_page": "Grey-headed honeyeater", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Grey-headed honeyeater\n| image = Grey-fronted honeyeater, crop.jpg\n| image_caption = At [[Trephina Gorge]], Northern Territory\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| genus = Ptilotula\n| species = keartlandi\n| authority = ([[Alfred John North|North]], 1895)\n| synonyms = ''Lichenostomus keartlandi''\n| range_map = P. keartlandi records of occurrence.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Location records from Ebird data available to the Atlas of Living Australia under Creative Commons Zero (CC0).\n}}\nThe '''grey-headed honeyeater''' (''Ptilotula keartlandi'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Meliphagidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Australia]].\n\n== Nomenclature, taxonomy and evolutionary history ==\nFirst described as ''Ptilotis keartlandi'' in 1895 by [[ornithologist]], [[Alfred John North]], the grey-headed honeyeater is named in honour of the ornithological collector, [[George Arthur Keartland]], who collected the [[Type (biology)|type specimen]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=North|first=A J.|date=1895|title=Preliminary Descriptions of a new Genus of five new Species of Central Australian Birds|url=|journal=Ibis|volume=XXVI|pages=339\u2013346|via=}}</ref> The [[taxonomy (biology)|taxonomy]] of the species has been complex since its description. For example, the species was listed in the genus ''[[Meliphaga]]'' in 1926 by the Royal Australian Ornithological Union Official Checklist of Birds,<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Official Checklist of the Birds of Australia, Second Edition. |last=Wolstenholme |first=H. |publisher=Government Printer. Melbourne|year=1926|isbn=|location=Melbourne|pages=}}</ref> and then in the genus ''[[Lichenostomus]]'' by [[Richard Schodde|Schodde]] in 1975.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Interim List of Australian Songbirds, Passerines |last=Schodde |first=R. |publisher=Research Publications Pty Ltd|year=1975|isbn=|location=Surrey Hills, Victoria|pages=}}</ref> Most recently, the grey-headed honeyeater has been placed in the genus ''[[Ptilotula]]'', which contains five other [[Australia]]n [[species]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Ny\u00e1ri, A.S and Joseph, L.|date=2011|title=Systematic dismantlement of\u00a0Lichenostomus\u00a0improves the basis for understanding relationships within the honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) and historical development of Australo\u2013Papuan bird communities |journal=Emu |volume=111 |pages=202\u2013211 |doi=10.1071/MU10047}}</ref> that all share characteristically plain faces, subtended by a black proximal and yellow or white distal plume across the side of the neck.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Christidis, L. and Schodde. R. |date=1993 |title=Relationships and Radiations in the Meliphagine Honeyeaters, Meliphaga, Lichenostomus and Xanthotis (Aves: Meliphagidae): Protein Evidence and its Integration with Morphology and Ecogeography. |journal=Australian Journal of Zoology |volume=41 |issue=3 |pages=293\u2013316 |doi=10.1071/ZO9930293}}</ref>\n\nWhile the species in ''[[Ptilotula]]'' occupy a wide range of forest, woodland, arid and semi-arid habitats<ref name=\":1\" />, they share a common ancestor, which inhabited the dry woodlands of central Australia.<ref name=\":7\" /> A fossil leg-bone from an unnamed [[Pliocene]] species found in [[Australian Fossil Mammal Sites (Riversleigh)|Riversleigh]], [[Queensland]], described by Walter Boles, may well belong to this [[ancestor]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boles |first=W.|date=2005|title=Fossil honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) from the Late Tertiary of Riversleigh, north-western Queensland |journal=Emu |volume=105 |pages=21\u201326 |doi=10.1071/MU03024}}</ref>\n\n== Description and identifying features ==\nGrey-headed honeyeaters are relatively small for [[honeyeater]]s<ref name=\":4\" /> with a total body length of 13 \u2013 16.5 centimetres and weight of between 12 \u2013 18 grams.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds. Volume 5. Tyrant-flycatchers to Chats|last=Higgins, P. J. Peter, J. M. and Steele. W. K (Eds).|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2001|isbn=|location=Melbourne|pages=}}</ref> Individual wing length ranges from 67 - 81 millimetres, the tail is between 55 - 69 millimetres long<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Grey-headed Honeyeater|last=Australian Bird Study Association Inc.|publisher=Australian Bird Study Association Inc.|year=2018|isbn=|location=Online at www.absa.asn.au|pages=}}</ref> and the bill is between 14.5 \u2013 18.5 millimetres in length.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n[[File:Lichenostomus keartlandi g2g2 - Christopher Watson.jpg|left|thumb|An adult grey-headed honeyeater feeding.]]\nAdults have a distinctive grey crown above a black facial mask with the nape and remaining upper body parts coloured dark fawn-grey.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=The Australian Bird Guide|last=Menkhorst, P. Rogers, D. Clarke, R. Davies, J. Marsack, P. and Franklin, K.|publisher=CSIRO Publications|year=2017|isbn=|location=Victoria|pages=}}</ref> The black facial mask extends from the base of the bill to the rear of the ear coverts and comprises a black [[Lore (anatomy)|lores]], eye rings, feathers behind the eye and grey-black ear coverts.<ref name=\":2\" /> The base of the mask is bordered by a thin, bright yellow plume which extends below and behind the ear coverts and a pale yellow moustachial stripe located between the lores and throat.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe bill is black, short and slightly down-curved with a yellow base on the lower mandible,<ref name=\":2\" /> although it may become fully black during breeding.<ref name=\":4\" /> The [[iris (anatomy)|iris]] is black to dark brown while the [[gape]] is yellow, turning black during breeding.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe breast, belly, flanks and throat are light olive-yellow streaked with brown while the rump is light grey-brown.<ref name=\":2\" /> The flight [[feather]]s are olive-brown,<ref name=\":2\" /> edged with olive-yellow which gives the wing a yellow panel when folded.<ref name=\":4\" /> The tail [[feather]]s are dark olive-brown edged in olive-yellow.<ref name=\":2\" /> There are ten [[Flight feather|primary flight feathers,]] ten secondaries and twelve tail feathers.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThere is no [[plumage]] difference between the sexes; however, there is some [[sexual dimorphism]] as males are slightly heavier and larger than females.<ref name=\":3\" /> There is no geographical variation in [[plumage]] across the species range.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nJuveniles have similar [[plumage]] to adults but are generally paler with a lighter grey-brown face mask.<ref name=\":2\" /> Juveniles also have grey-black [[Beak|bills]] with an orange-brown base, yellow gapes and a lighter grey crown.<ref name=\":2\" /> \u00a0Juveniles partially [[Moulting|moult]] into immature [[plumage]] soon after fledging and, while immature [[plumage]] is similar to adult plumage, juvenile tail and flight feathers are retained and immatures can be identified by the presence of fault bars in the tail.<ref name=\":3\" /> Moult into adult plumage occurs in the first year.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe grey-headed honeyeater produces a continuous, peevish ''chip'' call when feeding<ref name=\":2\" /> and a ''wee-wee-wee'' song.<ref name=\":4\" /> Other vocalisations include a loud single ''kwoyt'' and ''chee-toyt''  which is possibly only emitted during breeding.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nThe grey-headed honeyeater has an extensive range covering much of central arid and semi-arid [[Australia]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://datazone.birdlife.org/species/factsheet/Grey-headed-Honeyeater|title=BirdLife International. (2019). Species factsheet: Ptilotula\u00a0keartlandi. Downloaded on 11/06/2019.}}</ref> The [[extent of occurrence]] is estimated at 4,360,000 [[square kilometre]]s.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe grey-headed honeyeater mostly frequents ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' scrub and woodlands in stony hill country and timbered gullies within ranges; however, it can be observed on sand-plains when [[vegetation]] is flowering.<ref name=\":4\" /> The species has also been recorded in Mulga and Mallee woodlands, [[river]]ine areas dominated by [[Eucalyptus camaldulensis|River Red Gum]] (''Eucalyptus camaldulensis'') and occasionally in Mitchell grasslands.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe grey-headed honeyeater is thought to be largely sedentary<ref name=\":2\" />; however, it undertakes nomadic movements in response to vegetation flowering events.<ref name=\":4\" /> While these movements are predominately local, some larger movements have been recorded.<ref name=\":4\" /> For example, one individual has been recorded in East Point, [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], 270 kilometres north of its previously documented range following major ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' flowering events.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Kyne, M. P. and Jackson, V. M.|date=2010|title=An extralimital record of Grey-headed Honeyeater ''Lichenostomus keartlandi'' from Darwin Northern Territory |url=https://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=520401235884288;res=IELHSS;subject=Painting|journal=Northern Territory Naturalist |volume=22 |pages=75\u201378 |via=}}</ref>\n\n== Ecology ==\n\n=== Diet and behaviour ===\nThe grey-headed honeyeater gleans and probes for [[invertebrate]]s on vegetation foliage and branches but will also take [[insect]]s on the wing.<ref name=\":4\" /> Like many honeyeaters, the species will also consume nectar from flowering trees, particularly Hakeas, [[Eucalyptus|Eucalypts]], [[Grevillea|''Grevilleas'']],<ref name=\":2\" /> Mallee <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tischler, M. Dickman, R, C. and Wardle. M, G.|date=2013|title=Avian functional group responses to rainfall across four vegetation types in the Simpson Desert, central Australia|journal=Austral Ecology|volume=38|issue=7|pages=809\u2013819|doi=10.1111/aec.12065}}</ref> and has been known to take occasional fruit.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe grey-headed honeyeater is usually seen individually or in pairs; however, small parties of 5 to 20 have been recorded congregating around a food source.<ref name=\":2\" /> The species is active, vocal, inquisitive and pugnacious.<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Intraspecific competition|Intraspecific]] and [[Interspecific competition|interspecific]]<ref name=\":6\" /> aggression and [[Agonistic behaviour|agonistic]] behaviour including territorial calls, bill snapping, chasing and fighting have been recorded during feeding and possibly breeding.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Breeding ===\n[[File:Specimen 04124. P keartlandi eggs.png|thumb|Grey-headed honeyeater eggs]]\nThe breeding ecology of the grey-headed honeyeater is poorly understood.<ref name=\":2\" /> Breeding is thought to mainly occur during winter and spring; however, it may occur at any time across the species range, possibly following rainfall.<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Nest]]s are constructed low in a live tree or shrub within a dry creek bed or bank but usually not near water.<ref name=\":2\" /> The nest is a small, open, compact cup-shaped structure made from dried plant stems, grass and bark bound by spider webs.<ref name=\":2\" /> The nest is lined with plant down, feathers and animal hair and suspended from the tree or shrub.<ref name=\":2\" /> Clutch size is thought to be two eggs variously described as oval, lengthened, rounded, glossy, lustreless, white, pink, sometimes unmarked or with light brown or purple spots.<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[Incubation period|incubation]] period is unknown and it is thought that only a single brood is raised annually.<ref name=\":2\" /> Both sexes have been recorded performing distraction displays when nests are approached.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Conservation status, threats and conservation actions ==\n\n=== Conservation status ===\nBecause the population is considered stable, and due to its extensive range, the grey-headed honeyeater is listed as [[Least-concern species|Least Concern]] under the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]] [[IUCN Red List|Red List of Threatened Species]].<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/22704082/30037478|title=BirdLife International\u00a0(2009). Ptilotula keartlandi.\u00a0The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species\u00a02009: e.T22704082A30037478.\u00a0Downloaded on\u00a008 June 2019.}}</ref> The species is also considered [[Least-concern species|Least Concern]] under [[Australia]]n state and Commonwealth law.\n\n=== Threats ===\nWhile the [[population]] is considered stable, its actual size has not been quantified<ref name=\":8\" /> and the species is regarded as uncommon or locally common in some areas, suggesting it may occur at low densities.<ref name=\":4\" /> Nest [[predation]] and [[Brood parasite|nest parasitism]] events have been recorded; however, insufficient information is available to determine whether these are significant threats.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe grey-headed honeyeater is considered threatened by [[climate change]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|title=Climate change adaptation strategies for Australian birds|last=Garnet, S. Franklin, D. Ehmke, G. VanDerWal, J. Hodgson, L. Pavey, C. Reside, A. Welbergen, J. Butchart, S. Perkins, G. and Williams, S.|publisher=National Climate Change Adaptation Research Facility|year=2013|isbn=|location=Gold Coast|pages=}}</ref> Its diet and potential reliance on rainfall to breed likely leaves it vulnerable to changed climatic conditions and the species may experience habitat contractions or loss of habitat suitability due to [[climate change]].<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Conservation actions ===\nThe [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]] does not identify any conservation actions for the species.<ref name=\":8\" /> However, the Climate Change Adaptation Strategies for Australian Birds lists general measures which may inadvertently benefit the species.<ref name=\":9\" /> These include improved land management, purchasing land for protection, establishing new habitat and maintenance and improvement of existing habitat quality.<ref name=\":9\" /> Additionally, the range of the grey-headed honeyeater overlaps several [[Australian Wildlife Conservancy|Australian Wildlife Conservancy refuges,]] notably Newhaven, Bowra and Pungalina and several National Parks, and management actions in these areas may also inadvertently benefit the species.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=190 style=\"font-size:100%; line-height:130%\">\nGrey-headed Honeyeater 2506.jpg|Near [[Corella Dam|Lake Corella]], western Queensland\nGrey-headed Honeyeater newhaven sep04.jpg|At Newhaven, Northern Territory\nLichenostomus keartlandi - Christopher Watson.jpg|A juvenile showing the orange-brown base to bill\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Ptilotula keartlandi}}\n{{Wikispecies|Lichenostomus keartlandi}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075256}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:honeyeater, grey-headed}}\n[[Category:Ptilotula|grey-headed honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1895|grey-headed honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Alfred John North|grey-headed honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Grey-headed honeyeater\n| image = Grey-fronted honeyeater, crop.jpg\n| image_caption = At [[Trephina Gorge]], Northern Territory\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| genus = Ptilotula\n| species = keartlandi\n| authority = ([[Alfred John North|North]], 1895)\n| synonyms = ''Lichenostomus keartlandi''\n| range_map = P. keartlandi records of occurrence.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Location records from Ebird data available to the Atlas of Living Australia under Creative Commons Zero (CC0).\n}}\nThe '''grey-headed honeyeater''' (''Ptilotula keartlandi'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Meliphagidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Australia]].\n\n== Nomenclature, taxonomy and evolutionary history ==\nFirst described as ''Ptilotis keartlandi'' in 1895 by [[ornithologist]], [[Alfred John North]], the grey-headed honeyeater is named in honour of the ornithological collector, [[George Arthur Keartland]], who collected the [[Type (biology)|type specimen]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=North|first=A J.|date=1895|title=Preliminary Descriptions of a new Genus of five new Species of Central Australian Birds|url=|journal=Ibis|volume=XXVI|pages=339\u2013346|via=}}</ref> The [[taxonomy (biology)|taxonomy]] of the species has been complex since its description. For example, the species was listed in the genus ''[[Meliphaga]]'' in 1926 by the Royal Australian Ornithological Union Official Checklist of Birds<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Official Checklist of the Birds of Australia, Second Edition. |last=Wolstenholme |first=H. |publisher=Government Printer. Melbourne|year=1926|isbn=|location=Melbourne|pages=}}</ref>, and then in the genus ''[[Lichenostomus]]'' by [[Richard Schodde|Schodde]] in 1975.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Interim List of Australian Songbirds, Passerines |last=Schodde |first=R. |publisher=Research Publications Pty Ltd|year=1975|isbn=|location=Surrey Hills, Victoria|pages=}}</ref> Most recently, the grey-headed honeyeater has been placed in the genus ''[[Ptilotula]]'', which contains five other [[Australia]]n [[species]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Ny\u00e1ri, A.S and Joseph, L.|date=2011|title=Systematic dismantlement of\u00a0Lichenostomus\u00a0improves the basis for understanding relationships within the honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) and historical development of Australo\u2013Papuan bird communities |journal=Emu |volume=111 |pages=202\u2013211 |doi=10.1071/MU10047}}</ref> that all share characteristically plain faces, subtended by a black proximal and yellow or white distal plume across the side of the neck.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Christidis, L. and Schodde. R. |date=1993 |title=Relationships and Radiations in the Meliphagine Honeyeaters, Meliphaga, Lichenostomus and Xanthotis (Aves: Meliphagidae): Protein Evidence and its Integration with Morphology and Ecogeography. |journal=Australian Journal of Zoology |volume=41 |issue=3 |pages=293\u2013316 |doi=10.1071/ZO9930293}}</ref>\n\nWhile the species in ''[[Ptilotula]]'' occupy a wide range of forest, woodland, arid and semi-arid habitats<ref name=\":1\" />, they share a common ancestor, which inhabited the dry woodlands of central Australia.<ref name=\":7\" /> A fossil leg-bone from an unnamed [[Pliocene]] species found in [[Australian Fossil Mammal Sites (Riversleigh)|Riversleigh]], [[Queensland]], described by Walter Boles, may well belong to this [[ancestor]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boles |first=W.|date=2005|title=Fossil honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) from the Late Tertiary of Riversleigh, north-western Queensland |journal=Emu |volume=105 |pages=21\u201326 |doi=10.1071/MU03024}}</ref>\n\n== Description and identifying features ==\nGrey-headed honeyeaters are relatively small for [[honeyeater]]s<ref name=\":4\" /> with a total body length of 13 \u2013 16.5 centimetres and weight of between 12 \u2013 18 grams.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds. Volume 5. Tyrant-flycatchers to Chats|last=Higgins, P. J. Peter, J. M. and Steele. W. K (Eds).|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2001|isbn=|location=Melbourne|pages=}}</ref> Individual wing length ranges from 67 - 81 millimetres, the tail is between 55 - 69 millimetres long<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Grey-headed Honeyeater|last=Australian Bird Study Association Inc.|publisher=Australian Bird Study Association Inc.|year=2018|isbn=|location=Online at www.absa.asn.au|pages=}}</ref> and the bill is between 14.5 \u2013 18.5 millimetres in length.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n[[File:Lichenostomus keartlandi g2g2 - Christopher Watson.jpg|left|thumb|An adult grey-headed honeyeater feeding.]]\nAdults have a distinctive grey crown above a black facial mask with the nape and remaining upper body parts coloured dark fawn-grey.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=The Australian Bird Guide|last=Menkhorst, P. Rogers, D. Clarke, R. Davies, J. Marsack, P. and Franklin, K.|publisher=CSIRO Publications|year=2017|isbn=|location=Victoria|pages=}}</ref> The black facial mask extends from the base of the bill to the rear of the ear coverts and comprises a black [[Lore (anatomy)|lores]], eye rings, feathers behind the eye and grey-black ear coverts.<ref name=\":2\" /> The base of the mask is bordered by a thin, bright yellow plume which extends below and behind the ear coverts and a pale yellow moustachial stripe located between the lores and throat.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe bill is black, short and slightly down-curved with a yellow base on the lower mandible,<ref name=\":2\" /> although it may become fully black during breeding.<ref name=\":4\" /> The [[iris (anatomy)|iris]] is black to dark brown while the [[gape]] is yellow, turning black during breeding.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe breast, belly, flanks and throat are light olive-yellow streaked with brown while the rump is light grey-brown.<ref name=\":2\" /> The flight [[feather]]s are olive-brown,<ref name=\":2\" /> edged with olive-yellow which gives the wing a yellow panel when folded.<ref name=\":4\" /> The tail [[feather]]s are dark olive-brown edged in olive-yellow.<ref name=\":2\" /> There are ten [[Flight feather|primary flight feathers,]] ten secondaries and twelve tail feathers.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThere is no [[plumage]] difference between the sexes; however, there is some [[sexual dimorphism]] as males are slightly heavier and larger than females.<ref name=\":3\" /> There is no geographical variation in [[plumage]] across the species range.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nJuveniles have similar [[plumage]] to adults but are generally paler with a lighter grey-brown face mask.<ref name=\":2\" /> Juveniles also have grey-black [[Beak|bills]] with an orange-brown base, yellow gapes and a lighter grey crown.<ref name=\":2\" /> \u00a0Juveniles partially [[Moulting|moult]] into immature [[plumage]] soon after fledging and, while immature [[plumage]] is similar to adult plumage, juvenile tail and flight feathers are retained and immatures can be identified by the presence of fault bars in the tail.<ref name=\":3\" /> Moult into adult plumage occurs in the first year.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe grey-headed honeyeater produces a continuous, peevish ''chip'' call when feeding<ref name=\":2\" /> and a ''wee-wee-wee'' song.<ref name=\":4\" /> Other vocalisations include a loud single ''kwoyt'' and ''chee-toyt''  which is possibly only emitted during breeding.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nThe grey-headed honeyeater has an extensive range covering much of central arid and semi-arid [[Australia]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://datazone.birdlife.org/species/factsheet/Grey-headed-Honeyeater|title=BirdLife International. (2019). Species factsheet: Ptilotula\u00a0keartlandi. Downloaded on 11/06/2019.}}</ref> The [[extent of occurrence]] is estimated at 4,360,000 [[square kilometre]]s.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe grey-headed honeyeater mostly frequents ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' scrub and woodlands in stony hill country and timbered gullies within ranges; however, it can be observed on sand-plains when [[vegetation]] is flowering.<ref name=\":4\" /> The species has also been recorded in Mulga and Mallee woodlands, [[river]]ine areas dominated by [[Eucalyptus camaldulensis|River Red Gum]] (''Eucalyptus camaldulensis'') and occasionally in Mitchell grasslands.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe grey-headed honeyeater is thought to be largely sedentary<ref name=\":2\" />; however, it undertakes nomadic movements in response to vegetation flowering events.<ref name=\":4\" /> While these movements are predominately local, some larger movements have been recorded.<ref name=\":4\" /> For example, one individual has been recorded in East Point, [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], 270 kilometres north of its previously documented range following major ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' flowering events.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Kyne, M. P. and Jackson, V. M.|date=2010|title=An extralimital record of Grey-headed Honeyeater ''Lichenostomus keartlandi'' from Darwin Northern Territory |url=https://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=520401235884288;res=IELHSS;subject=Painting|journal=Northern Territory Naturalist |volume=22 |pages=75\u201378 |via=}}</ref>\n\n== Ecology ==\n\n=== Diet and behaviour ===\nThe grey-headed honeyeater gleans and probes for [[invertebrate]]s on vegetation foliage and branches but will also take [[insect]]s on the wing.<ref name=\":4\" /> Like many honeyeaters, the species will also consume nectar from flowering trees, particularly Hakeas, [[Eucalyptus|Eucalypts]], [[Grevillea|''Grevilleas'']],<ref name=\":2\" /> Mallee <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tischler, M. Dickman, R, C. and Wardle. M, G.|date=2013|title=Avian functional group responses to rainfall across four vegetation types in the Simpson Desert, central Australia|journal=Austral Ecology|volume=38|issue=7|pages=809\u2013819|doi=10.1111/aec.12065}}</ref> and has been known to take occasional fruit.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe grey-headed honeyeater is usually seen individually or in pairs; however, small parties of 5 to 20 have been recorded congregating around a food source.<ref name=\":2\" /> The species is active, vocal, inquisitive and pugnacious.<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Intraspecific competition|Intraspecific]] and [[Interspecific competition|interspecific]]<ref name=\":6\" /> aggression and [[Agonistic behaviour|agonistic]] behaviour including territorial calls, bill snapping, chasing and fighting have been recorded during feeding and possibly breeding.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Breeding ===\n[[File:Specimen 04124. P keartlandi eggs.png|thumb|Grey-headed honeyeater eggs]]\nThe breeding ecology of the grey-headed honeyeater is poorly understood.<ref name=\":2\" /> Breeding is thought to mainly occur during winter and spring; however, it may occur at any time across the species range, possibly following rainfall.<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Nest]]s are constructed low in a live tree or shrub within a dry creek bed or bank but usually not near water.<ref name=\":2\" /> The nest is a small, open, compact cup-shaped structure made from dried plant stems, grass and bark bound by spider webs.<ref name=\":2\" /> The nest is lined with plant down, feathers and animal hair and suspended from the tree or shrub.<ref name=\":2\" /> Clutch size is thought to be two eggs variously described as oval, lengthened, rounded, glossy, lustreless, white, pink, sometimes unmarked or with light brown or purple spots.<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[Incubation period|incubation]] period is unknown and it is thought that only a single brood is raised annually.<ref name=\":2\" /> Both sexes have been recorded performing distraction displays when nests are approached.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Conservation status, threats and conservation actions ==\n\n=== Conservation status ===\nBecause the population is considered stable, and due to its extensive range, the grey-headed honeyeater is listed as [[Least-concern species|Least Concern]] under the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]] [[IUCN Red List|Red List of Threatened Species]].<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/22704082/30037478|title=BirdLife International\u00a0(2009). Ptilotula keartlandi.\u00a0The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species\u00a02009: e.T22704082A30037478.\u00a0Downloaded on\u00a008 June 2019.}}</ref> The species is also considered [[Least-concern species|Least Concern]] under [[Australia]]n state and Commonwealth law.\n\n=== Threats ===\nWhile the [[population]] is considered stable, its actual size has not been quantified<ref name=\":8\" /> and the species is regarded as uncommon or locally common in some areas, suggesting it may occur at low densities.<ref name=\":4\" /> Nest [[predation]] and [[Brood parasite|nest parasitism]] events have been recorded; however, insufficient information is available to determine whether these are significant threats.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe grey-headed honeyeater is considered threatened by [[climate change]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|title=Climate change adaptation strategies for Australian birds|last=Garnet, S. Franklin, D. Ehmke, G. VanDerWal, J. Hodgson, L. Pavey, C. Reside, A. Welbergen, J. Butchart, S. Perkins, G. and Williams, S.|publisher=National Climate Change Adaptation Research Facility|year=2013|isbn=|location=Gold Coast|pages=}}</ref> Its diet and potential reliance on rainfall to breed likely leaves it vulnerable to changed climatic conditions and the species may experience habitat contractions or loss of habitat suitability due to [[climate change]].<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Conservation actions ===\nThe [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]] does not identify any conservation actions for the species.<ref name=\":8\" /> However, the Climate Change Adaptation Strategies for Australian Birds lists general measures which may inadvertently benefit the species.<ref name=\":9\" /> These include improved land management, purchasing land for protection, establishing new habitat and maintenance and improvement of existing habitat quality.<ref name=\":9\" /> Additionally, the range of the grey-headed honeyeater overlaps several [[Australian Wildlife Conservancy|Australian Wildlife Conservancy refuges,]] notably Newhaven, Bowra and Pungalina and several National Parks, and management actions in these areas may also inadvertently benefit the species.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=190 style=\"font-size:100%; line-height:130%\">\nGrey-headed Honeyeater 2506.jpg|Near [[Corella Dam|Lake Corella]], western Queensland\nGrey-headed Honeyeater newhaven sep04.jpg|At Newhaven, Northern Territory\nLichenostomus keartlandi - Christopher Watson.jpg|A juvenile showing the orange-brown base to bill\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Ptilotula keartlandi}}\n{{Wikispecies|Lichenostomus keartlandi}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075256}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:honeyeater, grey-headed}}\n[[Category:Ptilotula|grey-headed honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1895|grey-headed honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Alfred John North|grey-headed honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNomenclature, taxonomy and evolutionary history:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey-headed_honeyeater"}
{"title_page": "City of Bell scandal", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Robert Rizzo|the German musician|Robert Hunecke-Rizzo}}\n\nThe '''Bell scandal''' involved the misappropriation of public funds in [[Bell, California|Bell]], [[California]], [[United States]], over a period of several years in the late 2000s. In July 2010, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' published an [[investigative journalism|investigative article]] on possible malfeasance in the neighboring city of [[Maywood, California|Maywood]], revealing that the city officials of Bell received salaries that were reported as the highest in the nation.<ref name=\"latimes11\">{{cite news|author=Jeff Gottlieb|author2=Ruben Vives|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/bell-city-manager-might-highest-paid-in-nation-787637-a-year.html|title=Bell city manager could possibly be highest paid in nation: $787,637 a year|publisher=Latimesblogs.latimes.com|date=2010-07-14|accessdate=2010-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722021336/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/bell-city-manager-might-highest-paid-in-nation-787637-a-year.html|archive-date=2010-07-22|url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequent investigations found atypically high [[property tax]] rates, allegations of [[voter fraud]] in municipal elections and other irregularities which heightened the ensuing [[scandal]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|last=Fund|first=John|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703309704575413393066886472?mod=googlenews_wsj|title=It All Starts with Vote Fraud|publisher=Online.wsj.com|date=2010-08-07|accessdate=2010-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819233801/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703309704575413393066886472?mod=googlenews_wsj|archive-date=2017-08-19|url-status=live}}</ref> These and other reports led to widespread criticism and a demand for city officials to resign.<ref name=\"latimes2\">{{cite news|first=Jeff|last=Gottlieb|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/787000-salary-for-bell-city-manager-is-outrageous-assemblyman-hector-de-la-torre-says.html|title=$787,000 salary for Bell city manager is outrageous, assemblyman says|publisher=Latimesblogs.latimes.com|date=2010-07-16|accessdate=2010-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719224103/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/787000-salary-for-bell-city-manager-is-outrageous-assemblyman-hector-de-la-torre-says.html|archive-date=2010-07-19|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes3\">{{cite news|last=Knoll|first=Corina|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0716-bell-residents-20100716,0,4326515.story|title=Residents of Bell unhappy over perceived high salaries for city employees|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-07-16|accessdate=2010-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812021930/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0716-bell-residents-20100716,0,4326515.story|archive-date=2010-08-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the end, seven Bell city officials, including former mayor Oscar Hernandez, former city administrator Robert Rizzo, assistant city administrator Angela Spaccia, and four city council members were convicted on [[graft (politics)|graft]] and [[corruption]] charges, and were given sentences ranging from [[probation]] to twelve years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Knoll|first1=Corina|last2=Gottlieb|first2=Jeff|title=Bell corruption case ends, last defendant gets a year in jail|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-final-bell-defendant-sentenced-20140801-story.html|accessdate=13 May 2015|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=1 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150513013834/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-final-bell-defendant-sentenced-20140801-story.html|archive-date=13 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==The community==\n[[Bell, California|Bell]], [[California]], is a small suburb of [[Los Angeles]] that covers {{convert|2.5|sqmi|km2|sigfig=2}}, with a population of approximately 38,000.<ref name=\"The Expose\">{{cite news|title=Is a city manager worth $800,000?|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715,0,7352605.story|first1=Jeff|last1=Gottlieb|first2=Ruben|last2=Vives|date=July 15, 2010|publisher=Los Angeles Times|access-date=July 29, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729035031/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715,0,7352605.story|archive-date=July 29, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> It is one of the poorer cities in [[Los Angeles County]],<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-20/california-official-s-800-000-salary-in-city-of-38-000-triggers-protests.html | work=Bloomberg | first=Christopher | last=Palmeri | title=California Official's $800,000 Salary in City of 38,000 Triggers Protests | date=2010-07-20 | access-date=2017-03-06 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110182042/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-20/california-official-s-800-000-salary-in-city-of-38-000-triggers-protests.html | archive-date=2015-01-10 | url-status=live }}</ref> with almost one in six residents lives below the poverty line.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-22/california-s-bell-used-as-cash-drawer-state-controller-says-after-audit.html |title=California's Bell Used as 'Cash Drawer,' State Controller Says After Audit |access-date=2017-03-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025030716/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-22/california-s-bell-used-as-cash-drawer-state-controller-says-after-audit.html |archive-date=2013-10-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2009, Bell's per capita income was about $24,800 and 90% of its residents were [[Hispanic people|Hispanic]] or [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]]. In 2010, only 43.3% held a high school degree or equivalent, while just 6.0% held a post-secondary degree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=bkmk|title=American FactFinder - Results|last=Bureau|first=U.S. Census|website=factfinder.census.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160205101044/http://www.census.gov/prod/2013pubs/acs-22.pdf|archive-date=2016-02-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> Small businesses, auto shops, markets, ''[[carniceria]]s'', and ''[[panaderia]]s'' dominate the streets of Bell.<ref name=\"people\"/> The city\u2019s unemployment level is 16%.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bowes|first=Peter|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-10798426|title=BBC News - California city pay scandal highlights media cuts|publisher=Bbc.co.uk|date=2010-07-31|accessdate=2010-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100910180207/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-10798426|archive-date=2010-09-10|url-status=live}}</ref> As with other cities in California, all of Bell's local elections are nonpartisan.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2010-09-21-bell-california-scandal_N.htm | work=USA Today | title=Corruption charges bring cheers, tears in California suburb | date=2010-09-22 | access-date=2013-10-03 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005044338/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2010-09-21-bell-california-scandal_N.htm | archive-date=2013-10-05 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Charter votes and irregularities===\nIn 2005, a measure approved by Bell voters exempted the city from a state law enacted earlier that year which limited the salary of council members of [[California#Cities.2C towns and counties|general-law cities]] &ndash; cities without a [[city charter|charter]] of their own. All five members of the Bell City Council signed a statement in favor of the \"little-noticed city ballot measure\", which converted Bell into a [[charter city]] and was \"billed as one that would give the city more control,\" yet failed to mention that Bell became exempted from the salary regulations. The measure passed, 336 votes in favor and 54 against.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/bell-council-found-loophole-in-law-to-allow-big-salaries.html |title=Jeff Gottlieb, \"Bell Council Found Loophole in Law to Allow Big Salaries,\" ''Los Angeles Times,'' July 22, 2010 |access-date=July 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725210352/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/bell-council-found-loophole-in-law-to-allow-big-salaries.html |archive-date=July 25, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe salaries and pensions scandal in Bell also brought into question the issue of [[voter fraud]]. In the 2005 election, fewer than 400 votes were cast in a special election that cleared the way for City Council members to dramatically boost their own salaries. In that election, more than half the votes cast were [[absentee ballot]]s, the most vulnerable method to manipulate fraudulent votes. One resident of Bell, on condition of anonymity, told the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' that he was assigned the chore of retrieving absentee ballots: \"Our objective was to collect absentee ballots, and if they were not filled out, instruct them how to fill it out, and if not, fill it out for them\", he said. It is estimated that less than 1% of registered voters actually showed up to cast their ballot.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> It has been reported that some residents went to the [[polling place]], only to find that their votes had already been cast.<ref>NBC news, August 9, 2010</ref>\n\n===Voter fraud led to scandal===\nAssertions about discrepancies in the 2009 election were also examined by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] and California's Secretary of State. A source at the FBI confirmed that they were aware of the accusations. In the police report were listed the names of 19 voters who allegedly were either living in [[Lebanon]], or were deceased at the time that their votes were cast.<ref>{{cite news|last=Winton|first=Richard|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-elections-20100728,0,4351844.story|title=Bell city scandal: L.A. County D.A. expands probe into Bell city government|publisher=latimes.com|date=2009-06-17|accessdate=2010-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730034358/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-elections-20100728,0,4351844.story|archive-date=2010-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref> As L.A. prosecutors investigated potential voter fraud, several citizens allegedly told the ''Times'' that city officials encouraged them to fill out absentee ballots in a manner that election experts said has significantly raised the possibility that state law has been violated.<ref>{{cite news|last=Esquivel|first=Paloma|url=http://www.latimes.com/la-me-election-fraud-bell-20100806,0,249341.story|title=Voters in Bell tell of possible fraud|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-08-05|accessdate=2010-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628202704/http://www.latimes.com/la-me-election-fraud-bell-20100806,0,249341.story|archive-date=2011-06-28|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Under state law, this is not to be done unless someone is ill or disabled. If, in fact, the election itself has been tainted by improper electioneering or other violations of state law, then that involves civil \u2014 maybe even criminal \u2014 penalties, and in some circumstances, you can overturn the election itself\", Attorney General [[Jerry Brown]] said. \"If (officials) met in a back room and said, 'How can we run an election where nobody shows up so we can then fatten our own salaries and pensions...that could constitute a violation that would bring into question the entire election.\"<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\n==The scandal==\nA series of [[investigative journalism|investigative article]]s published by the ''Times'' in July 2010 revealed that several city officials in Bell were being paid salaries significantly higher than those in other cities.<ref name=\"latimes11\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Gottlieb|first=Jeff|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715,0,7352605.story|title=Is a city manager worth $800,000?|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-07-15|accessdate=2010-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812022053/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715,0,7352605.story|archive-date=2010-08-12|url-status=live}}</ref> The two main reporters involved in the investigations were Ruben Vives and Jeff Gottlieb, and [[Kimi Yoshino]] was the guiding editor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/readers-rep/la-me-rr-kimi-yoshino-named-la-times-business-editor-20140320-story.html|title=Kimi Yoshino named L.A. Times Business editor|last=Edgar|first=Deirdre|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-01-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129140431/http://www.latimes.com/local/readers-rep/la-me-rr-kimi-yoshino-named-la-times-business-editor-20140320-story.html|archive-date=2018-01-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=130108851|title=How The L.A. Times Broke The Bell Corruption Story|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-01-28|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129080624/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=130108851|archive-date=2018-01-29|url-status=live}}</ref> In a press release issued through the Bell City Clerk's office, [[Mayor]] Oscar Hernandez claimed that \"salaries of the City Manager and other top city staff have been in line with similar positions over the period of their tenure,\" and then accused the ''Times'' of having a \"skewed view of the facts.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/scavenger/detail?entry_id=68800|work=The San Francisco Chronicle|first=Aileen|last=Yoo|title=Bell official made $700K+ while city laid off workers|date=2010-07-27|access-date=2010-08-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100829023950/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/scavenger/detail?entry_id=68800|archive-date=2010-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bellcityclerk.org/ftp/City%20of%20Bell%20Statement_072210.pdf |title=Bell City Clerk's office website |access-date=2010-08-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429174838/http://www.bellcityclerk.org/ftp/City%20of%20Bell%20Statement_072210.pdf |archive-date=2014-04-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Hernandez later apologized for what he called the city's \"indefensible administrative salaries\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Christopher Palmeri|url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-07-26/california-mayor-regrets-indefensible-salaries.html|title=California Mayor Regrets 'Indefensible' Salaries|publisher=BusinessWeek|date=2010-07-26|accessdate=2010-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730080245/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-07-26/california-mayor-regrets-indefensible-salaries.html|archive-date=2010-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref> He was later recalled, arrested, and indicted for [[fraud]] and other charges.\n\nBell City Council members later voted to reduce their pay to that of what one councilman, Lorenzo Velez, was being paid: $8,076 a year. Prior to that meeting, all of the other council members were making at least ten times that figure.<ref name=\"salary\">{{cite news|author=CNN Wire Staff|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/POLITICS/07/27/california.salaries/index.html?section=cnn_latest|title=California officials reduce salaries in response to outcry|publisher=CNN.com|date=2010-07-27|accessdate=2010-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109110055/http://www.cnn.com/2010/POLITICS/07/27/california.salaries/index.html?section=cnn_latest|archive-date=2012-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref>  [[State Controller]] [[John Chiang (California politician)|John Chiang]] said that the salaries in Bell had been \"outrageous and unjustifiable\" and a voter fraud hotline was set up.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wavenewspapers.com/news/Attorney-General-Jerry-Brown-subpoenas-Bell-officials-sets-up-voter-fraud-hotline-100321659.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722142250/http://www.wavenewspapers.com/news/Attorney-General-Jerry-Brown-subpoenas-Bell-officials-sets-up-voter-fraud-hotline-100321659.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-07-22|title=AG Jerry Brown subpoenas Bell officials, sets up voter fraud hotline &#124;|publisher=Wavenewspapers.com|date=2010-08-10|accessdate=2010-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Trussell|first=Donna|url=http://www.politicsdaily.com/2010/08/03/california-will-post-city-officials-salaries-after-bell-scandal|title=California Will Post City Officials' Salaries After Bell Scandal|publisher=Politicsdaily.com|accessdate=2010-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100805030126/http://www.politicsdaily.com/2010/08/03/california-will-post-city-officials-salaries-after-bell-scandal/|archive-date=2010-08-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDocuments released to the ''Times'' revealed that the [[California Public Employees' Retirement System]] (CalPERS) knew four years previously that Rizzo had received a 47% pay increase to $442,000. Then-[[Attorney General of California|California Attorney General]] [[Jerry Brown]] maintained that such a large increase should have aroused suspicion from CalPERS.<ref name=\"latimes10\">{{cite news|last=Halper|first=Evan|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-pensions-20100806,0,711701.story|title=Bell salaries raise more concerns about CalPERS|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-08-06|accessdate=2010-08-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812021718/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-pensions-20100806,0,711701.story|archive-date=2010-08-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\"These outrageous salaries in Bell are shocking and beyond belief,\" said Brown. \"With record deficits and painful budget cuts facing California cities, astronomical local government salaries raise serious questions and demand a thorough investigation.\"<ref name=\"Palmeri\"/>\n\nThe end of August 2010 ended the California legislature\u2019s law-making season, and the bill (AB1955) that would have strictly regulated elected officials\u2019 income levels died while in the [[California State Senate]].<ref name=\"SH\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.signaltribunenewspaper.com/archives/7696 |title=Signal Hill city manager explains councilmembers\u2019 complicated salaries |access-date=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100913031942/http://www.signaltribunenewspaper.com/archives/7696 |archive-date=2010-09-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> All the related bills were vetoed by [[Governor of California|Governor]] [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]].<ref name=\"blogs.sacbee.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.sacbee.com/capitolalertlatest/2010/10/schwarzenegger-on-pension-bill.html |title=Capitol Alert: Schwarzenegger on key pension bill: \"Taxpayers deserve better\" |access-date=2010-10-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825043355/http://blogs.sacbee.com/capitolalertlatest/2010/10/schwarzenegger-on-pension-bill.html |archive-date=2011-08-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A piece of legislation that had passed before the legislature\u2019s deadline, AB1987, would have put an end to the public employee practice of pension \"spiking\" &ndash; the accumulation of vacation and sick time until the end of their tenure so their retirement benefit is increased, sometimes by tens of thousands of dollars per year;<ref name=\"SH\"/> this bill was also vetoed by Governor Schwarzenegger.<ref name=\"blogs.sacbee.com\"/>\n\n\"Frankly, Bell residents need to know if their city is solvent,\" said Supervisor [[Gloria Molina]], who chairs the board and whose district includes Bell. Molina said the audit, expected to cost about $100,000, was paid for out of her office's discretionary fund, at no cost to the city.\n\nMarcia Fritz, who heads the California Foundation for Fiscal Responsibility stated that at age 62, when Rizzo could have  begun receiving Social Security payments, his annual pension and benefits would have risen to $976,771, topping $1 million two years later. \"This guy would be our first seven-figure retiree,\" said Fritz.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE66K6BX20100721|work=Reuters|title=California city manager's pension could top $30 million|date=2010-07-21|access-date=2017-06-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924023643/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE66K6BX20100721|archive-date=2010-09-24|url-status=live}}</ref> The million-dollar pension Rizzo was expecting has been reduced to about $100,000 per year. The other seven city council members arrested for misappropriating funds received similar pension cuts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flos_angeles&id=7787134 |title=\"Bell officials won't receive massive pensions\" |access-date=2019-10-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101116005902/http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flos_angeles&id=7787134 |archive-date=2010-11-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nA week after Brown sued, Rizzo and six of the other seven people named in his suit were charged in criminal court with plundering $5.5 million from Bell.<ref name=\"lau\">{{Cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/Judge-questions-suit-over-CA-apf-1750055294.html?x=0&.v=1 |title=\"Judge questions suit over CA city's big salaries\" |access-date=2017-01-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107145417/http://finance.yahoo.com/news/Judge-questions-suit-over-CA-apf-1750055294.html?x=0&.v=1 |archive-date=2011-11-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> More secreted funds containing millions of dollars were discovered in April 2011. Judge Ralph W. Dau ruled that the parts of the lawsuit accusing Rizzo and the others of \"conflict of interest, squandering public funds and putting their own interests ahead of Bell's\" could move forward. When Brown announced the lawsuit, he said he hoped to recoup hundreds of thousands of dollars for residents. He acknowledged it was a \"novel legal approach\" but said he was \"confident his office had the authority.\"<ref name=\"lau\"/>\n\nThe city of Bell had a difficult time restoring some semblance of normality in the year following the salary scandal. Residents voted in a completely new city council, and Bell's interim city manager stabilized the shaky financial position by implementing a balanced budget that eliminated several high-ranking administrative and police positions, uses federal grant money to pay some police officers\u2019 salaries, and makes other cuts.<ref name=\"CBS2\">{{Cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/07/21/scandal-plagued-city-of-bell-may-face-layoffs-cutbacks |title=Bell faces layoffs and cutbacks\" |access-date=2011-07-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510091556/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/07/21/scandal-plagued-city-of-bell-may-face-layoffs-cutbacks/ |archive-date=2012-05-10 |url-status=live }}</ref> On August 12, 2011, the city announced that Arne Croce would serve as yet another interim city manager. He started at a weekly salary of $3,230 with no medical or retirement benefits, replacing interim city manager Kenneth Hampian<ref>[http://www.cbs47.tv/news/state/story/Troubled-city-of-Bell-selects-interim-manager/vEXquLYyVk2y_wnhS9bNog.cspx?rss=154 \"Bell selects new interim city manager\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAs Governor, Jerry Brown made it more difficult for city council members to dishonestly pad their paychecks. Brown signed into law Assemblyman [[Cameron Smyth]] (R-Santa Clarita)'s legislation, AB 23, which requires city officials to publicize when they are holding concurrent or consecutive meetings, and how much the meeting attendees will receive in salaries. \"The intent is to discourage the potential abuses by making public how much officials are being paid,\" Smyth said.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/california-politics/2011/07/bell-related-reform-bill-signed-by-governor.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=PolitiCal|date=2011-07-25|access-date=2011-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813192909/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/california-politics/2011/07/bell-related-reform-bill-signed-by-governor.html|archive-date=2011-08-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==\"Special Election\" 2011==\n33% of Bell's 10,485 registered voters turned out to vote <ref name=\"election\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ktla.com/news/landing/ktla-march-8-election-results-bell,0,1796421,full.story |title=RESULTS: March 8 Election Results - City of Bell Special Election |access-date=2011-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401165659/http://www.ktla.com/news/landing/ktla-march-8-election-results-bell,0,1796421,full.story |archive-date=2012-04-01 |url-status=live }}</ref> in a recall election for the City Council members.<ref name=\"Times8\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-elections-20110308,0,3630943.story|work=Los Angeles Times|first1=Christopher|authorlink1=Christopher Goffard|last1=Goffard|first2=Paloma|last2=Esquivel|title=Bell voters cast out the old and opt for the new|date=2011-03-09}}</ref> Mayor Hernandez, Deputy Mayor Jacobo and Council member George Mirabal, were all recalled, each with a referendum of over 95%.<ref name=\"election\"/>\nDanny Harber received 54% of the vote to gain Jacobo's seat.  Filling the short term council seat vacated by Mirabal, is Ana Maria Quintana, with 44% of the vote.<ref name=\"election\"/> The next day it was announced that Ali Saleh, Nestor Valencia and Violeta Alvarez will fill the other three council seats.\n<ref name=\"election\"/> Councilman Lorenzo Velez, the only Bell official not charged with wrongdoing,<ref name=\"nbclosangeles1\">[http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local-beat/City-of-Bell-to-Investigate-High-Salaries-98758759.html \"City of Bell Postpones Investigation of High Salaries\"]</ref> was also replaced on the city council.<ref name=\"glitch\">{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.sacbee.com/capitolalertlatest/2011/03/lawmakers-target-glitch-caused.html#mi_rss=Latest%20News |title=Capitol Alert: Lawmakers target glitch caused by Bell City Council arrests |access-date=2011-03-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324230251/http://blogs.sacbee.com/capitolalertlatest/2011/03/lawmakers-target-glitch-caused.html#mi_rss=Latest%20News |archive-date=2011-03-24 |url-status=live }}</ref> Assembly Bill 93 which allows the City Clerk to swear in the new council and also allows the [[Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors]] to validate  the March 8 election results. The new city council has been unable to take office because there was no quorum (none) of the former city council to swear them in. They were sworn in the last week of March 2011.<ref name=\"glitch\"/> The council has designated Ali Saleh as the new mayor.<ref>[https://archive.today/20120909024059/http://www.scpr.org/news/2011/04/27/new-bell-mayor-talks-about-efforts-fix-citys-budge \"New Bell Mayor Talks About Efforts to Fix City's Budget, Prevent Corruption\", April 27, 2011, Southern California Public Radio]</ref>\n\nThe California Fair Political Practices Commission said July 1, 2011, that it is investigating whether Bell's police union violated state law when the union handed out a campaign flyer supporting their candidates in the recall election. The commission said it is looking into whether the Bell Police Officers Association was properly noted as the source of the flyer. Three of the five council persons elected were those endorsed by the Bell Police Officers Association.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9NTR0K81.htm |title=Bell Police Officers Association investigated by California Fair Political Practices Commission |access-date=2011-07-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102063104/http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9NTR0K81.htm |archive-date=2012-11-02 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Corruption hearings==\n===City Council===\nThe preliminary hearing for the alleged misappropriations and misdeeds of the Bell City council members charged, began on February 7, 2011. Councilman Lorenzo Velez, the only Bell official not charged with any wrongdoing, testified that he doesn't remember participating in any of the meetings for which other council members billed the city tens of thousands of dollars. Velez testified that he doesn't recall any of the council members doing any work for any of the committees or if there were ever actually any meetings held at all.<ref name=\"abcnews1\"/> \"I should have asked more questions, I'm not denying that\", said Velez, the only member of the city council who did not take a large salary. \"If ignorance is a crime, I guess I'm guilty.\" Velez was defeated in the March 2011 election. The defendants at this preliminary hearing are Hernandez, Jacobo, Mirabal, former Mayor George Cole and former Councilmen Luis Artiga and [[Victor Bello]].<ref name=KTLA>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ktla.com/news/landing/ktla-bell-city-clerk-testimony,0,1288241.story |title=Bell Salary Scandal: \"Bell City Clerk Testifies Robert Rizzo Made Her Lie\" |access-date=2011-02-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713180355/http://www.ktla.com/news/landing/ktla-bell-city-clerk-testimony,0,1288241.story |archive-date=2011-07-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFormer city clerk, Rebecca Valez, testified at the hearing that she was instructed by Rizzo to lie to resident, Roger Ramirez, who had enquired about council members salaries. The first witness at the preliminary hearing, Ramirez testified that when he confronted Rizzo at a city council meeting, regarding  the rumors  that he was paid $400,000 a year, \"He immediately said, 'No, Mr. Ramirez, if I would be making $400,000 a year I wouldn't be working here\". Ramirez had previously filed a public records request with City Hall. The bogus records he was given showed Rizzo was earning about $15,000 per month, and City Council members a couple hundred dollars per month.<ref name=\"AP_Feb23\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2011/feb/23/differing-views-of-ca-official-crook-or-victim/ |title=Differing views of CA official: Crook or victim? |author=John Rogers, Associated Press |work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]] |date=February 23, 2011 |accessdate=February 21, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303081053/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2011/feb/23/differing-views-of-ca-official-crook-or-victim/ |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Valez, who has partial immunity, stated she prepared the documents and Rizzo changed the correct figures much lower than the actual salaries; she was ordered to show the falsified lowered figures to Ramirez.<ref name=KTLA/> She also testified that Rizzo awarded himself contracts with hefty raises without any approval from the city attorney.<ref name=\"AP_Feb23\"/>\n\nBell's administrative services director, Lourdes Garcia, said shortly before she gave Ramirez the falsified documents, City Clerk Rebecca Valdez confided to her that Rizzo had directed her to have Mayor Oscar Hernandez retroactively sign Rizzo's contracts, although Hernandez was not mayor during the period that the contracts  were written. \"She was crying\", Garcia said about Valdez. \"She was very nervous.\" Valdez testified at the earlier hearing that Rizzo had instructed her to give Ramirez the fabricated figures.<ref name =\"AP_Feb23\"/> The testimony has ended and LA Superior Court Judge Henry Hall is expected to issue a ruling after the opposing attorneys present their arguments.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/02/16/bell-corruption-hearing-nears-end |title=\"Bell Corruption Hearing Ends\" |access-date=2011-03-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131130326/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/02/16/bell-corruption-hearing-nears-end/ |archive-date=2016-01-31 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA pretrial hearing was set for May  2011 for the six defendants. They all had to be arraigned again after the judge made the decision to put them on trial. They have all pleaded not guilty to all charges <ref name=\"kfiam640.com\">[http://www.kfiam640.com/cc-common/mainheadlines3.html?feed=153218&article=8315354 \"Ex Bell Officials Plead Not Guilty\"]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe trial began January 22, 2013, with deliberations beginning February 28. Deliberations were halted February 28 after a juror admitted to discussing the trial outside of the jury room. An alternate juror was seated and deliberations continued. After 18 days of deliberations five councilmembers were found guilty on some of the charges and not guilty on an equal number of charges, with other charges split 9-3 in favor of guilt. Luis Artiga, who took office after the high pay began, was exonerated of all charges.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Verdict-Reached-in-Bell-6-Corruption-Trial-199193191.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151103003104/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Verdict-Reached-in-Bell-6-Corruption-Trial-199193191.html |archive-date=2015-11-03 |url-status=live }}</ref> Subsequently, on March 21, a juror wrote notes to the judge requesting reconsideration of past verdicts, and another juror wrote a note accusing other jurors of bad behavior. \"It seems that all hell has broken loose,\" remarked the judge to attorneys in the case. After another day of deliberation, the judge declared a mistrial on all remaining counts, leaving the prosecution to determine if they wanted the case retried.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2013/03/22/36509/strange-end-of-bell-corruption-trial-may-spur-appe/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731143929/http://www.scpr.org/news/2013/03/22/36509/strange-end-of-bell-corruption-trial-may-spur-appe/ |archive-date=2013-07-31 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Former City Manager and assistant===\nAt Rizzo's hearing, documents acquired from former Assistant City Manager Angela Spaccia's computer by District Attorney Steve Cooley show that starting in 2005, she and Rizzo created fraudulent contracts that were not sanctioned by the City Council that elevated their salaries to \"outrageous\" levels and made it almost impossible to tell how much they were being paid, according to the 19-page memorandum from Cooley. \"Rizzo and Spaccia succeeded in concealing their conduct for so long, in part by trickery ... and in part by buying loyalty of city employees,\" the memo said.<ref name=\"sfgate.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2011/02/14/state/n153217S40.DTL&type=science |title=Scandal-ridden CA city's leaders ordered to trial |work=The San Francisco Chronicle }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Rizzo is allegedly considered the ringleader among the \"Bell Eight\",  former Bell city officials (now resigned, recalled or fired), accused of bilking taxpayers out of about $5.5 million through hefty salaries, benefits and illegal loans of public money.<ref name=\"March25\"/>\n\nIn his opening presentation, Rizzo's attorney, James Spertus, stated, \"Everybody has agreed that it's not a crime to be paid too much.\"<ref name=\"AP_Feb23\"/> Later that day, February 23, 2011, Rizzo complained of chest pains and feeling light-headed and was carried out on a stretcher during his preliminary hearing. He held a towel over his face as paramedics removed him to an ambulance. He was transported to [[Good Samaritan Hospital (Los Angeles)|Good Samaritan Hospital]], and the hearing was adjourned for the day.<ref>[http://www.topix.com/city/bell-ca/2011/02/rizzo-removed-on-gurney-from-courthouse \"Rizzo Removed on Gurney From Courthouse\"]</ref> Rizzo was released from the hospital the next day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/02/ex-bell-city-administrator-rizzo-released-from-hospital.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=L.A. Now|date=2011-02-25|access-date=2011-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228232908/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/02/ex-bell-city-administrator-rizzo-released-from-hospital.html|archive-date=2011-02-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Rizzo returned to court the following Monday.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Rizzo-Returns-to-Courtroom-Bell-Preliminary-hearing-117078903.html |title=\"Rizzo Returns to Court\" |access-date=2011-03-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714161126/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Rizzo-Returns-to-Courtroom-Bell-Preliminary-hearing-117078903.html |archive-date=2011-07-14 |url-status=live }}</ref> The next day, Rizzo slept through a good part of the hearing.<ref name=\"abc\">{{Cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/bell-california-scandal-reaches-court-city-manager-dozes/story?id=13028339 |title=\"Bell, California Scandal Reaches Court, Where City Manager Dozes off at Hearing\" |access-date=2011-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628204902/http://abcnews.go.com/US/bell-california-scandal-reaches-court-city-manager-dozes/story?id=13028339 |archive-date=2011-06-28 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn Friday of the same week, the focal point was Rizzo's enormous salary and  what machinations were made for him to receive it. The main issue was who had signed Rizzo's employment contracts, since although the former city attorney acknowledged the signatures appeared to be his, he claimed he did not sign them.  The D.A. claims that Rizzo signed them himself.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flos_angeles&id=7995970&rss=rss-kabc-article-7995970 |title=\"Bell testimony centers on Robert Rizzo's big salary\" |access-date=2019-10-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628230407/http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flos_angeles&id=7995970&rss=rss-kabc-article-7995970 |archive-date=2011-06-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nA second preliminary hearing for misappropriation of public funds<ref name=\"March10\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/politics/rizzo-preliminary-hearing-ruling-117732743.html |title=\"Rizzo to Stand Trial\" |access-date=2011-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714161217/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/politics/rizzo-preliminary-hearing-ruling-117732743.html |archive-date=2011-07-14 |url-status=live }}</ref> by Rizzo, and former Assistant City Manager Angela Spaccia,  began March 22, 2011.<ref name=\"CBS\"/>  The pair have already been ordered to stand trial on the previous charges.<ref name=\"March10\"/> At that arraignment on March 24, 2011, Rizzo, Spaccia, former Mayor Hernandez and ex-councilman Luis Artiga plead not guilty to the charges that they plundered tiny Bell of millions of dollars.<ref>[http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/mar/27/us-bell-salaries ''Las Vegas Sun'' coverage of Bell scandal\"]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n====More charges for the duo====\nRizzo and Spaccia were indicted on several new allegations by the  Los Angeles Grand Jury on March 30, 2011. The allegations include  new charges of misappropriating public funds, conflict of interest, falsifying public  documents and secreting of public documents.<ref name=\"March30\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Former-Bell-City-Manager-Indicted-on-New-Charges-Rizzo-118924659.html |title=\"Former Bell City Manager Indicted on New Charges\" |access-date=2011-03-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830031235/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Former-Bell-City-Manager-Indicted-on-New-Charges-Rizzo-118924659.html |archive-date=2012-08-30 |url-status=live }}</ref> Yet another allegation claims that the duo fabricated documents  appearing to be contracts for former police Chief Randy Adams and secreted the true contracts' indication that his salary was nearly $10,000 more per pay period than purported.<ref name=\"March30\"/>  These indictments add eight charges to the public corruption case against Rizzo and seven  former Bell officials<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/31/local/la-me-0331-bell-indictment-20110331|work=Los Angeles Times|first1=Jeff|last1=Gottlieb|first2=Corina|last2=Knoll|date=2011-03-31|title=Robert Rizzo, aide accused of conspiracy in Bell corruption scandal|access-date=2011-05-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110410040257/http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/31/local/la-me-0331-bell-indictment-20110331|archive-date=2011-04-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====More money secreted away====\nOn April 25, 2011, it was revealed  that at least two more illegal retirement accounts have been discovered. An additional $4.5 million was found secreted away to  avoid retirement limits for  public employees and to benefit Rizzo, Spaccia and a select few council members.<ref name=Huff1>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/04/26/robert-rizzo-pension-fund_n_853812.html |title=\"Secret Robert Rizzo Pension Fund Contained $4.5 Million\" |access-date=2011-05-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113054921/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/04/26/robert-rizzo-pension-fund_n_853812.html |archive-date=2012-11-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another account was found to be set up to benefit only Rizzo and Spaccia, letting them  evade IRS regulations which cap government pensions.<ref name=Huff1/> Lourdes Garcia, the city's director of administrative services, testified under limited immunity that Rizzo told her in 2008 that his goal was to put $14 million in the secondary pension fund, which would be  paid by  the city.<ref name=Huff1/>\n\n====Ousted officials demanded more city funds====\nFour of the city officials have requested that the city of Bell pay their legal bills. Hernandez, Jacobo and Cole are facing corruption charges for allegedly looting the city's treasury, according to the ''[[L.A. Times]]'' in January 2011. A city audit has shown that the city is close to bankruptcy.<ref name=Jan>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/01/accused-bell-officials-want-cash-strapped-city-to-pay-their-legal-bills.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=L.A. Now|date=2011-01-10|access-date=2011-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113110903/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/01/accused-bell-officials-want-cash-strapped-city-to-pay-their-legal-bills.html|archive-date=2011-01-13|url-status=live}}</ref> Cole's attorney, Robert Kaye, claims that, although he was being paid approximately $100,000 a year for his part-time position and for attending  meetings that did not occur or lasted only a few minutes that \u201cAt that time... Mr. Cole did not believe that his actions were unlawful.\u201d <ref name=Jan/> Superior Court Judge Henry J. Hall ordered in February 2011, that no compensation be paid to city officials without approval from the court.<ref name=\"losangeles.cbslocal.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/02/17/bell-city-hall-stays-open-during-trial |title=Bell City Hall Stays Open During TrialCBS Los Angeles |access-date=2011-02-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221110220/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/02/17/bell-city-hall-stays-open-during-trial/ |archive-date=2011-02-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, in March 2011, Robert Rizzo (and two other former councilmen) persisted in their claim that they are entitled to reimbursement from the city of Bell for his legal fees spent in his defense against his charges of defrauding the city of Bell out of millions of dollars.<ref name=\"March25\">{{Cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/03/25/rizzo-asks-judge-to-order-bell-to-reimburse-legal-fees |title=\"Rizzo Asks Judge To Order Bell To Reimburse Legal Fees\" |access-date=2011-03-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131130326/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/03/25/rizzo-asks-judge-to-order-bell-to-reimburse-legal-fees/ |archive-date=2016-01-31 |url-status=live }}</ref> Former Bell City Attorney Edward Lee confirmed during a testimony in 2010 that he outlined the  clause in Rizzo\u2019s contract that was intended to guarantee the former city manager defense funds \"against any type of claim\", according the court papers.<ref name=\"March25\"/> \"All of the claims triggered a defense obligation from the city of Bell under Mr. Rizzo's employment agreement and he sent the claims to the city for a defense, but the tenders were all denied by the city\", Rizzo's updated court papers attested. In June  2011, there was a hearing  regarding Rizzo's request<ref name=\"March25\"/> and the issue of ''intent'' in the employment agreement.\n\n==Hearings==\nA two-sentence order denying the petition was later signed without comment by Justices Dennis M. Perluss and Laurie D. Zelon of the 2nd District Court of Appeal in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"denial\">{{cite news | url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-appeal-20120101,0,4281581.story?track=rss | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Jeff | last=Gottlieb | title=Six former Bell council members lose appeal | date=2011-12-31 | access-date=2012-01-18 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101195249/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-appeal-20120101,0,4281581.story?track=rss | archive-date=2012-01-01 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, Los Angeles County Superior Court Judge Kathleen Kennedy rejected their motion to drop the charges and the contention that their  salaries were protected by the city's charter.  She  issued an extremely critical  ten-page ruling that completely negated the politicians' claim that they had no intent of or knowledge they could possibly be breaking the law.  \"The city of Bell charter,\" Kennedy wrote, \"did not make Bell a sovereign nation not subject to the general penal laws of the State of California.\"<ref name=\"denial\"/>\n\nOn February 28, 2012, Judge Kennedy dismissed some felony charges against ex-Mayor Oscar Hernandez and two counts of misappropriation of public funds against former ex-councilman Luis Artiga. Hernandez and Artiga will still face the charges of misappropriating funds in a separate case.  The judge denied the motion to dismiss any charges against the ex- city manager Robert Rizzo and his assistant Angela Spaccia.<ref name=\"update2012\">{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/28/bell-salary-scandal_n_1308084.html | work=Huffington Post | title=Felony Charges Against Former Bell Officials Dropped | date=2012-02-28 | access-date=2012-04-08 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303015536/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/28/bell-salary-scandal_n_1308084.html | archive-date=2012-03-03 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn her February 9 ruling, Kennedy stated that Rizzo \"virtually ran this loan program unilaterally\" and distributed at least 40 loans totaling almost $2 million between 2001 and 2010.  In rejecting the dismissal motion by Rizzo and Spaccia, Kennedy said they \"simply set their own financial terms awarding themselves huge raises and other fringe benefits,\" and that \"This is a textbook case of conflict of interest.\"<ref name=\"update2012\"/>\n\n==Salary dispute==\n===Bell city manager===\nRizzo collected a salary of [[United States dollar|US$]] 787,637 a year, with yearly 12% increases scheduled every July, he received $1.5 million in the last year.<ref name=\"denial\"/><ref name=\"latimes7\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/la-me-bell-manager-compensation-mobile,0,52255.story?track=rss|title=Bell councilman 'ashamed', 'disgusted' that Rizzo earned $1.5 million|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-08-08|accessdate=2010-08-09|first1=Jeff|last1=Gottlieb|first2=Ruben|last2=Vives}}</ref> Rizzo remained unapologetic about his salary and said, \"If that's a number people choke on, maybe I'm in the wrong business ... I could go into private business and make that kind of money. This council has compensated me for the job I've done.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/07/15/robert-rizzo-bell-city-ma_n_647826.html|title=Robert Rizzo, Bell City Manager, Makes $800k|publisher=Huffingtonpost.com|date=2010-07-15|accessdate=2010-08-17|first=Billy|last=Silverman|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719040512/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/07/15/robert-rizzo-bell-city-ma_n_647826.html|archive-date=2010-07-19|url-status=live}}</ref> Spaccia concurred, saying: \"I would have to argue you get what you pay for.\" Rizzo and Spaccia had never achieved such a salary in the private sector.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/15/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715|work=Los Angeles Times|first1=Jeff|last1=Gottlieb|first2=Ruben|last2=Vives|date=2010-07-15|title=Is A City Manager Worth $800,000?|access-date=2011-05-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517110554/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/15/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715|archive-date=2011-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn comparison, [[Los Angeles County]] Chief Executive [[William T Fujioka]] earns $338,458.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://caljobsource.com/calsalaries.html|title=California Governor and Official Salaries|publisher=Caljobsource.com|date=2008-06-10|accessdate=2010-08-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815001551/http://caljobsource.com/calsalaries.html|archive-date=2010-08-15|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[President of the United States]] earns $400,000 per year.<ref name=\"vvdailypress1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vvdailypress.com/news/hesperia-20926-hook-pension.html|title=Hesperia is on the hook for $80,000 of Rizzo's pension|publisher=Vvdailypress.com|date=2010-08-04|accessdate=2010-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927163404/http://www.vvdailypress.com/news/hesperia-20926-hook-pension.html|archive-date=2011-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref> Rizzo also received an unusually large package of benefits, including paid vacation, sick and personal time of 28 weeks off per year.<ref name=\"latimes7\"/>  In addition, both [[Rancho Cucamonga]] and [[Hesperia, California|Hesperia]] may be obligated to pay significant percentages of Rizzo's estimated $600,000 annual pension, according to ''[[Daily Press (California)|Daily Press]]'' estimates.<ref name=\"vvdailypress1\"/> Rizzo was in line to receive a pension of $880,000 annually.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/bell-city-fires-manager-paid-president-obamas-salary/story?id=11236299|title=Bell City Fires Manager Paid Twice President Obama's Salary|publisher=Abcnews.go.com|accessdate=2010-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726071658/http://abcnews.go.com/US/bell-city-fires-manager-paid-president-obamas-salary/story?id=11236299|archive-date=2010-07-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010,  Rizzo, Mayor Oscar Hernandez, former assistant city manager Angela Spaccia and council members George Mirabal, Teresa Jacobo, Luis Artiga, George Cole and Victor Bello were arrested and charged with misappropriation of public funds.<ref name=\"latimesblogs.latimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/09/bell-charges-rizzo.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Rizzo faces 53 counts; Bell was 'corruption on steroids', D.A. Cooley says [Updated]|date=2010-09-21|access-date=2010-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923154420/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/09/bell-charges-rizzo.html|archive-date=2010-09-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"http\">{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/09/bell-charges-rizzo.html|title=8 current, former Bell, California officials arrested|publisher=CNN|date=2010-09-21|accessdate=2010-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923154420/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/09/bell-charges-rizzo.html|archive-date=2010-09-23|url-status=live}}</ref> When Hernandez refused to answer the door at his home, the sheriff's department used a [[battering ram]] to break down his door and bring out the mayor in handcuffs.<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2010/09/8-former-city-officials-in-bell-calif-reported-arrested-in-salary-scandal/1|work=USA Today|title=8 former, current officials in Bell, Calif., arrested in salary scandal|date=2010-09-21|first=Douglas|last=Stanglin|access-date=2010-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923074104/http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2010/09/8-former-city-officials-in-bell-calif-reported-arrested-in-salary-scandal/1|archive-date=2010-09-23|url-status=live}}</ref> He refused to resign from his mayoral office,<ref name=\"27th\">{{cite news|last=Palmeri|first=Christopher|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-27/california-city-in-pay-probe-has-higher-property-taxes-than-beverly-hills.html|title=California City in Pay Probe Has Higher Tax Than Beverly Hills|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|date=2010-07-27|accessdate=2010-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730071710/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-27/california-city-in-pay-probe-has-higher-property-taxes-than-beverly-hills.html|archive-date=2010-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref> and was recalled in March 2011.\n\nRizzo was released from jail after [[Los Angeles County Superior Court]] Judge Mary Lou Villar determined that the funds  posted for his $2-million bail were not linked to any  of the monies he acquired in Bell. Rizzo was required to turn in his passport and wear an electronic monitoring device.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2010-10-07/justice/california.bell.corruption_1_angela-spaccia-lorenzo-velez-mayor-oscar-hernandez?_s=PM:CRIME|work=CNN|title=Attorney general expands probe of California city officials|date=2010-08-09|access-date=2010-10-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011045714/http://articles.cnn.com/2010-10-07/justice/california.bell.corruption_1_angela-spaccia-lorenzo-velez-mayor-oscar-hernandez?_s=PM:CRIME|archive-date=2010-10-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> The bail bondsmen hired on for Rizzo's $2 million bail, James Demayo and Morris Demayo, negotiated for several weeks with the prosecutor Max Huntsman on getting his bail approved. The electronic monitor was insisted by Max Huntsman.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://wavenewspapers.com/news/local/article_bc36b290-92fb-5f43-a173-a097af8856b8.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-03-26 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130412053309/http://wavenewspapers.com/news/local/article_bc36b290-92fb-5f43-a173-a097af8856b8.html |archive-date=2013-04-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSince he resigned, Rizzo has requested that the city pay his legal bills and claims the city owes him back pay. There was no such agreement made with Rizzo when he stepped down. \"He resigned without severance pay\", former councilman Velez said, adding: \"I will not even give [him] a penny cut in half.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/10/rizzo-bell-scandal.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Rizzo says Bell owes him more money and should still be paying his salary|date=2010-10-07|access-date=2010-10-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011080136/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/10/rizzo-bell-scandal.html|archive-date=2010-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nRizzo has also been ordered to stand trial in an additional conflict-of-interest charge regarding a racehorse deal with Bell's privately contracted planning director.<ref name=\"kfiam640.com\"/> Spaccia, is charged with misappropriation of public funds.<ref name=\"March10\"/> Rizzo formerly enjoyed buying horses and visiting his nearly $1 million ranch in Washington state.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/13/local/la-me-0113-lopez-20110113|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Steve|last=Lopez|date=2011-01-13|title=Robert Rizzo ordered to stand trial on new conflict of interest charges|access-date=2011-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317025231/http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/13/local/la-me-0113-lopez-20110113|archive-date=2011-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Police Chief==\nOn September 24, 2010, the Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office finally began the investigation of former Bell Police Chief Randy Adams, as part of the expanding probe of city officials. Other police included were  Adams negotiated an agreement with Rizzo when he was hired in 2009 that stipulated that he suffered from back, knee and neck injuries and that the city would support his application for a disability pension (Liz O. Baylen, ''Los Angeles Times''). Prosecutors filed suit regarding an agreement with Rizzo, Adams had himself declared disabled the day of his being hired in Bell. The disability status stands to net Adams millions of tax-free pension dollars at taxpayers\u2019 expense. Under the agreement, the 59-year-old Adams would receive a lifetime disability benefit whenever he was ready to retire, meaning he would not have to pay taxes on half of his $400,000-plus annual pension. His Bell retirement would be the third-richest in the state's huge pension system.<ref name=\"Chief\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/2010/10/28/2365935/bell-officers-say-they-have-proof.html |accessdate=October 29, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>  The state attorney filed suit against Adams and Bell following that report on his \"disability\". \"You're only supposed to receive a disability retirement if you are disabled and unable to perform the normal duties of your job,\" said California Public Employees' Retirement System spokesman Ed Fong. \"If that is not the case, it would be fraud.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/23/local/la-me-bell-adams-20100923|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Paul|last=Pringle|title=Former Bell police chief had a lucrative tax angle for retirement|date=2010-09-23|access-date=2010-09-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928191300/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/23/local/la-me-bell-adams-20100923|archive-date=2010-09-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe injuries that  Adams cited in order to collect millions of tax-free dollars from a law-enforcement disability pension did not stop him from taking rigorous spinning classes and running in a 5K race, the Glendale Downtown Dash, in 2009.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/oct/05/local/la-me-randy-adams-20101005|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Paul|last=Pringle|title=Bell Police Chief - Injury cited by ex-Bell police chief in disability pension claim didn't prevent him from exercising|date=2010-10-05|access-date=2010-10-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101018035720/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/oct/05/local/la-me-randy-adams-20101005|archive-date=2010-10-18|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/10/05/bell-police-chief-randy-a_n_750985.html |title=\"Bell Police Chief Randy Adams Ran In 5k, Rode Bikes Despite Alleged Disability\" |access-date=2010-11-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111195759/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/10/05/bell-police-chief-randy-a_n_750985.html |archive-date=2012-11-11 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nor did it stop him from stating on a 2008 application for Orange County sheriff, that he likes to ski and had been in the 120-mile Baker to Las Vegas Relay run. When Adams applied for Orange County sheriff, the year before joining Bell, he did not mention having any physical problems, said Rick Francis, chief of staff for county Supervisor John Moorlach.<ref name=\"Chief\"/> \"He was not disabled\", said [[Glendale, California|Glendale]] City Manager Jim Starbird, who was Adams' boss until he left for Bell. \"I never heard of someone being hired to work for a city and having that [disability] determination made going in.\" Glendale has joined two other cities in trying to block what has the potential to be hundreds of thousands of dollars in pension payments for Adams, whose highly profitable term as police chief of Bell has far-reaching consequences to the state's complicated employee retirement system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/glendale-seeks-to-block-pension-benefits-for-bell-police-chief.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=L.A. Now|date=2010-07-28|access-date=2010-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928025610/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/glendale-seeks-to-block-pension-benefits-for-bell-police-chief.html|archive-date=2010-09-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Adams' salary of $457,000 was roughly double that of Los Angeles Police Chief [[Charlie Beck]] who oversees almost 10,000 officers. Bell's police department numbers 48.<ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/08/bell-official-police-chief-salary-randy-adams.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=L.A. Now|date=2010-08-11|access-date=2010-11-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100919013207/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/08/bell-official-police-chief-salary-randy-adams.html|archive-date=2010-09-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, it was revealed on [[CBS]] nighttime news that Adams had allegedly exchanged e-mails with the assistant city manager on how they were going to arrange his over $400,000 salary and how to hide that fact from the citizens. The email's contents were presented in a humorous manner regarding bilking the city.  \"I am looking forward to seeing you and taking all of Bell's money\", Adams wrote, according to the memo.<ref name=\"sfgate.com\"/>\nAdams has not yet been charged or arrested. Some people in Bell have speculated that Adams hasn't been arrested because of his law-enforcement ties to District Attorney [[Steve Cooley]].<ref>[http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_16458669 \"Officers in scandal-torn Calif. city demand probe\"]</ref>\n\nSince August 2010, the city of Bell is still looking for a new police chief. Gilbert Jara, head of the Bell Police Officers Assn., called the search \"a good first step in ensuring not only public safety but also a restoration of the public\u2019s trust in Bell officials.\"<ref name=autogenerated5 /> The city of Bell has claimed that  they were negotiating with the [[Los Angeles Sheriff's Department]] to take over the policing contract, however, Sheriff [[Lee Baca]]'s spokesman says that the L.A. County Auditor-Controller Wendy L. Watanabe, has made no contact with him regarding that possibility.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.laweekly.com/informer/2010/12/bell_compton_police_department.php |title=L.A. County: \"Bell, Compton Should Not Have Own Police Departments\" |access-date=2010-12-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226181919/http://blogs.laweekly.com/informer/2010/12/bell_compton_police_department.php |archive-date=2010-12-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2011, the city hired the first Interim Chief of Police since the scandal broke.  Steve Belcher was retained as the interim chief and brought nearly 40 years of law enforcement experience.  Belcher was tasked with giving the police department a critical look and providing the new city managemenet with his police management review.  Interim Chief Belcher submitted his recommendations and served as the Interim Chief of Police for one year.\n\nIn October 2012, Bell Police Captain Anthony (Tony) Miranda was promoted to Chief of Police after a nationwide search of over 70 candidates.  The department continues on its path to recovery under Chief Miranda's direction.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.publicceo.com/2012/10/bell-announces-new-acting-police-chief/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-12-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121124123730/http://www.publicceo.com/2012/10/bell-announces-new-acting-police-chief/ |archive-date=2012-11-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, the California Public Employees Retirement System (CalPERS) Board designated as precedential its decision to reduce former City of Bell police chief Randy Adams' requested pension by more than half. The Board's decision to designate the Adams' decision as precedential means that it can be officially cited in court, in other administrative proceedings, and may be applied broadly to other cases.<ref>http://www.calpers.ca.gov/index.jsp?bc=/about/newsroom/news/city-of-bell-case-precedential.xml{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==More police caught in scandal==\nThe office that manages retirement benefits for California public employees is looking into the validity of pension plans for at least 10 police officers, including four chiefs, who received disability pensions and workers' compensation settlements when they were compelled to leave their jobs at the city of Bell. The California Public Employees Retirement System, or CalPERS, is asking Bell officials to ascertain whether Rizzo approved retirement deals that enhanced payments to those officers, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported on its website May 11, 2011.\n\n\"If Rizzo wanted to get rid of you, he'd make some way to pay you off and make it beneficial for you financially,\" said former Chief Andreas Probst, who was granted a $250,000 workers' compensation settlement and an annual disability retirement of $158,057. Probst claimed his retirement was properly handled because he had suffered on-duty injuries in a crash with a drunk driver. But he said Rizzo bundled severance, vacation and sick pay owed to him into the workers' compensation settlement - a practice that authorities said would be in violation of the tax codes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2011/may/11/disability-pensions-of-ex-bell-cops-under-scrutiny |title=\"Disability pensions of ex-Bell cops under scrutiny\" |access-date=2011-05-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108124025/http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2011/may/11/disability-pensions-of-ex-bell-cops-under-scrutiny/ |archive-date=2011-11-08 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Other city officials===\nThe city's website shows that seven more city workers received excessively high salaries, with two making more than $400,000 per year and three making more than $200,000.<ref name=Palmeri>{{cite news|title=Outrage over high salaries in Calif. town; Three city officials resign after total compensation revealed|first=Christopher|last=Palmeri|work=The Washington Post|date=July 25, 2010|page=A.3|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/24/AR2010072402548.html|access-date=September 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922043416/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/24/AR2010072402548.html|archive-date=September 22, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>  Assistant City Manager Angela Spaccia collected $376,288 a year, with a similar 12% annual pay increase, more than the top administrator for [[Los Angeles County]].<ref name=\"latimes1\"/> Bell Police Chief Adams, who oversaw a 46-person department, had an annual salary of $457,000, which is 33% higher than the [[LAPD]] police chief, [[Charlie Beck]] who oversees 12,899 employees in [[Los Angeles]] and earns $307,000.<ref name=\"people\">{{cite news|last=Knoll|first=Corina|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0716-bell-residents-20100716,0,4326515.story|title=Bell employee salary uproar: six-figure salaries in a blue-collar city|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-07-16|accessdate=2010-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812021930/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0716-bell-residents-20100716,0,4326515.story|archive-date=2010-08-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes1\">{{cite news|last=Vives|first=Ruben|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-721-bell-20100721,0,3475382.story|title=Bell council seeks resignations of 3 city officials|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-07-21|accessdate=2010-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722004835/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-721-bell-20100721%2C0%2C3475382.story|archive-date=2010-07-22|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Vives>{{cite web|url=http://www.joinlapd.com/career_ladder.html|title=Lapd - Career Ladder|publisher=Joinlapd.com|accessdate=2010-07-31|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823140559/http://www.joinlapd.com/career_ladder.html|archivedate=2011-08-23}}</ref><ref name=\"PD\">{{Cite web |url=http://californiawatch.org/watchblog/bell-police-get-big-paychecks-too-1800 |title=In tiny Bell, police officers get big paychecks, too |access-date=2010-08-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100810003305/http://www.californiawatch.org/watchblog/bell-police-get-big-paychecks-too-1800 |archive-date=2010-08-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2009, 11 officers in Bell were paid more than $10,000 in overtime. One officer billed $26,109 in overtime.<ref name=\"PD\"/>\n\nAll of the part-time city council members collected almost $100,000 a year, excepting Councilman Lorenzo Velez.  Velez, who was paid only about $8,000 a year for his service on the council, has said he  had no idea of the exorbitant salaries other officials were collecting.<ref>[http://mymotherlode.com/news/state/ap/342607/Recall-election-scheduled-for-city-of-Bell.html \"Recall election scheduled for city of Bell\"]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He has also testified that he doesn't remember participating in any of the meetings for which other council members billed the city tens of thousands of dollars.<ref name=\"abcnews1\">{{Cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=12863838 |title=\"Calif. City Official Testifies in Corruption Case |access-date=2011-02-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628214120/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=12863838 |archive-date=2011-06-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> Council members in cities similar to Bell in size make an average of $4,800 a year.<ref name=Vives/> In contrast, members of [[San Marino, California|San Marino's]] City Council take no salary at all.<ref>[http://www.ci.san-marino.ca.us/city_council.htm City of San Marino, California's City Council Page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501214309/http://www.ci.san-marino.ca.us/city_council.htm |date=2011-05-01 }}</ref> California Attorney General [[Jerry Brown]]<ref name=\"latimes4\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-council-20100723,0,4500089.story?track=rss|title=3 Bell leaders to quit in pay scandal|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-07-22|accessdate=2010-07-26|first1=Ruben|last1=Vives|first2=Jeff|last2=Gottlieb}}</ref> and L.A. prosecutors are investigating whether the current council salaries violate a state law that regulates how much council members are paid.<ref name=\"latimes5\">{{cite news|author=|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/bell-council-found-loophole-in-law-to-allow-big-salaries.html|title=Bell council members found legal loopholes to allow big salaries|publisher=Latimesblogs.latimes.com|date=2010-07-22|accessdate=2010-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725210352/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/bell-council-found-loophole-in-law-to-allow-big-salaries.html|archive-date=2010-07-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\nBell officials voted unanimously to look into legal action against city officials, political consultants or others.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/09/03/rober-rizzo-subpoenaed-in_n_705563.html |title=\"Robert Rizzo Subpoenaed in Bell probe\" |access-date=2010-10-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100909010918/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/09/03/rober-rizzo-subpoenaed-in_n_705563.html |archive-date=2010-09-09 |url-status=live }}</ref> Other city officials receiving inflated salaries. Lourdes Garcia, the city's director of administrative services, and Eric Eggena, the director of general services, were paid more than $400,000 each. Garcia has since agreed to a 61% pay cut and Eggena was fired. An unnamed third official was also let go.<ref name=\"latimes6\">{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/01/cash-strapped-bell-to-consider-disbanding-police-department-deep-cuts-to-salaries.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=L.A. Now|date=2011-01-27|access-date=2011-01-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128224001/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/01/cash-strapped-bell-to-consider-disbanding-police-department-deep-cuts-to-salaries.html|archive-date=2011-01-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nState lawmakers and investigators traveled to the city of Bell  on November 8, 2010, to probe the Los Angeles suburb's alleged corruption and governance problems. When residents were told by the state auditor that their political leaders mismanaged tens of millions of dollars of the blue-collar city's money, using it largely to pay themselves enormous salaries, they \"gasped in shock and disbelief.\"<ref name=\"ktkz\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ktkz.com/article.aspx?id=c4de5af0-20a9-4ed9-a685-5eef91fd4d85&catid=0 |title=KTKZ AM 1380: Intelligent Conservative Talk News Article |access-date=2010-11-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713173040/http://www.ktkz.com/article.aspx?id=c4de5af0-20a9-4ed9-a685-5eef91fd4d85&catid=0 |archive-date=2011-07-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> The auditors spoke at the hearing called by state Assemblyman [[Hector De La Torre]], who said he wanted to give residents of the working-class city of 36,000 \"a full accounting of what had happened\".<ref>John Rogers, Associated Press, November 9, 2010</ref>{{Citation needed|reason=\"John Rogers, Associated Press, November 9, 2010\" is NOT a complete citation.  It's doubtless better than nothing, but it's still inadequate.|date=March 2018}}\n\nThe ''[[Los Angeles Times|L.A. Times]]'' reported that in a review of state and local records it was discovered that independent audits of public agencies in California frequently failed to recognize and note cases of questionable  mismanagement and obvious fraud. The report cites [[San Diego]], [[Compton, California|Compton]] and [[South Gate, California|South Gate]] as other cities plagued by public corruption that received dubiously clean audits. \"Bell residents know their civic house is in disarray,\" said Supervisor [[Gloria Molina]]. \"There is no way order can be restored in Bell until residents there have an accurate picture of the city's finances.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-1020-bell-finances-20101020,0,4406929.story|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Ruben|last=Vives|title=City Of Bell - L.A. County auditors to examine Bell's finances|date=2010-10-20|access-date=2010-11-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101118052804/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-1020-bell-finances-20101020,0,4406929.story|archive-date=2010-11-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==BASTA==\nThe primary group organized to fight the cities corruption is the '''Bell Association to Stop the Abuse''' (BASTA); Basta means \"enough\" in [[Spanish language|Spanish]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Thomas Lifson|url=http://www.americanthinker.com/blog/2010/07/tea_party_redux_in_bell_califo.html|title=American Thinker Blog: Tea party redux in Bell, California|publisher=Americanthinker.com|accessdate=2010-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730120410/http://www.americanthinker.com/blog/2010/07/tea_party_redux_in_bell_califo.html|archive-date=2010-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref> BASTA consists of community members who are motivating the community to become educated and to learn where and how their tax dollars are spent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myfoxla.com/dpp/news/local/bell-mayor-oscar-hernandez-to-stop-taking-high-salary-20100726|title=Bell City Council, Mayor Take Big Pay Cuts|publisher=Myfoxla.com|accessdate=2010-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321171705/http://www.myfoxla.com/dpp/news/local/bell-mayor-oscar-hernandez-to-stop-taking-high-salary-20100726|archive-date=2012-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> BASTA organized a march on July 25, 2010.  Some of the marchers wore T-shirts with the words \"My city is more corrupt than your city\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myfoxla.com/dpp/news/local/bell-residents-march-for-council-resignations-20100725|title=Bell Residents to Vote on Council Resignations &#124; FOX 11 News|publisher=Myfoxla.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100731040544/http://www.myfoxla.com/dpp/news/local/bell-residents-march-for-council-resignations-20100725|archive-date=2010-07-31|accessdate=2010-08-09}}\n<!-- The link goes to a web page on which this article, or even just \"Bell\" cannot be found as of 2017-01-22. --></ref> BASTA is supported in part by the Bell Police Officers Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://basta4bell.com|title=BASTA &#124; The Bell Association to STOP the Abuse|publisher=Basta4bell.com|accessdate=2010-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100908093739/http://basta4bell.com/|archive-date=2010-09-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Police Officers Association has opposed the contracting of services of the Police Department or consolidation of police services into a joint powers authority<ref name=\"egpnews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://egpnews.com/?p=19635|title=Critics Weigh In On Bell Salary Scandal|publisher=Egpnews.com|date=2010-07-22|accessdate=2010-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006230326/http://egpnews.com/?p=19635|archive-date=2011-10-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> and has criticized the posting of salaries on the Bell City Clerk's website, calling them \"deceptive\" due to the inclusion of overtime.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://basta4bell.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/Bell_POA_press_080610.pdf |title=BASTA website |access-date=2010-08-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707213619/http://basta4bell.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/Bell_POA_press_080610.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> BASTA collected enough signatures to force the recall election in March for the four City Council members facing corruption charges. Organizers with BASTA began the recall process in August after unsuccessfully calling for the resignation of Mayor Oscar Hernandez and council members Luis Artiga, Teresa Jacobo and George Mirabal.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/09/bell-recall-organizers-claim-enough-signatures-for-vote.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Bell recall organizers claim enough signatures for vote|date=2010-09-28|access-date=2010-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101001134746/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/09/bell-recall-organizers-claim-enough-signatures-for-vote.html|archive-date=2010-10-01|url-status=live}}</ref> Artiga has since resigned.\n\n==Further Bell scandal investigations==\n===Real estate deal under investigation===\nOfficials in Bell paid more than  double the appraised value for a parcel of land that was never redeveloped. The latest scandal involves a tract of land presently leased by a carwash. ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' reported that Rizzo and former General Services Manager Eric Eggena negotiated its purchase for $1.35 million, despite its appraisal of $612,000. \"This is a real estate deal that ran amok\", said Larry Kosmont, a Los Angeles real estate consultant. \"Essentially, they cooked the books on this\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.officialwire.com/main.php?action=posted_news&rid=290588 |title=OfficialWire: \"Bell, Real Estate Deal Scrutinized\" |access-date=2011-03-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728152210/http://www.officialwire.com/main.php?action=posted_news&rid=290588 |archive-date=2011-07-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Civil Rights Violations===\nThe FBI  has begun investigating  the accusations of violating some citizens' civil rights, particularly whether Bell officials violated the civil rights of Latino residents by assertively towing targeted cars and charging residents extortionate fees to retrieve their vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0224-bell-investigation-20110224,0,1952274.story?track=rss|work=Los Angeles Times|first1=Jeff|last1=Gottlieb|first2=Robert J.|last2=Lopez|title=New search warrants served as Bell corruption probe widens|date=2011-02-24|access-date=2011-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224151200/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0224-bell-investigation-20110224,0,1952274.story?track=rss|archive-date=2011-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref> A memo titled ''Bell Police Department Baseball Game'' lists \"points\" for officers to ticket for various targeted infractions. Police officers in Bell said in interviews in August 2010 that they frequently spent their shifts pulling over vehicles for small infractions  hoping that they would be unlicensed drivers. \"Although officers didn't look exclusively for immigrants, it was clear that the majority of the drivers pulled over turned out to be illegal immigrants\", Officer Kurt Owens said. \u201cWe'd look for younger guys in their 20s and 30s, guys with junkier cars, broken lights, loud music or tinted windows\u201d, Owens added.<ref name=target>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/02/memo-suggests-bell-police-turn-ticketing-impounding-cars-into-baseball-game.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=L.A. Now|date=2011-02-28|access-date=2011-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304223846/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/02/memo-suggests-bell-police-turn-ticketing-impounding-cars-into-baseball-game.html|archive-date=2011-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBell's budget shows that the city was generating increased income from fees and taxes over several years. Bell's records show that the city made nearly a million dollars just in impound fees in fiscal year 2008-09,<ref name=\"abc\"/> which works out to be about $10 per citizen in this small town. Bell was charging $300 for unlicensed motorists to recover their cars, three times what Los Angeles County and neighboring cities charge.<ref name=target/>\"All of this was just a means by Rizzo to nickel and dime the community to death to get more money out of them\", Christina Garcia, a community activist, said.<ref name=target/>\n\n===Bell demanded extra fees from some businesses===\n\nThe ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported on November 1, 2010, that for at least a decade, officials in Bell arbitrarily required some businesses to make payments to the city totalling tens of thousands of dollars annually, and in at least one case threatening a business owner with closure if he failed to comply.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-1102-bell-fees-20101102,0,3038770,full.story|work=Los Angeles Times|first1=Paloma|last1=Esquivel|first2=Robert J.|last2=Lopez|title=Bell demanded extra fees from some businesses|date=2010-11-02|access-date=2010-11-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101103214648/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-1102-bell-fees-20101102,0,3038770,full.story|archive-date=2010-11-03|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Oregonian'' editorialized that \"Local businesses were shook down, Sopranos-style, just to stay open.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/opinion/index.ssf/2010/11/civics_lessons_from_bell_calif.html |title=\"Civics lessons from Bell, California\" |access-date=2010-11-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104013954/http://www.oregonlive.com/opinion/index.ssf/2010/11/civics_lessons_from_bell_calif.html |archive-date=2011-11-04 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===\"Breast Cancer Awareness\" funds===\nThe City of Bell raised a reported $100,000 from multi-year [[breast cancer awareness]] fundraisers. Former vice-mayor Teresa Jacobo was one of the leaders of those campaigns and the people of Bell are trying to find out where those charitable contributions went and if any funds were ever donated to breast cancer awareness organizations.<ref>[http://www.topix.com/city/bell-ca/2010/10/indicted-city-of-bell-councilwoman-teresa-jacobo-confronted-about-breast-cancer-awareness-funds \"Jacobo breast cancer fundraising investigated\"]</ref>\n\n===Property taxes===\nAn investigation into the city's property taxes found that the homeowners of Bell were paying a rate higher than those of the affluent [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]]. Homeowners in Bell pay the second-highest tax rate of any city in Los Angeles County.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themarkettraders.com/content/city-bell-california-illegally-overcharges-29-million-property-taxes|title=The City of Bell California Illegally Overcharges 2.9 Million in Property Taxes|publisher=the market traders|accessdate=2010-08-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717012327/http://www.themarkettraders.com/content/city-bell-california-illegally-overcharges-29-million-property-taxes|archive-date=2011-07-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Wendy Watanabe, Los Angeles County's auditor-controller, stated that residents of Bell pay as much as 1.55% of their home's assessed value in taxes, 34% above the norm. State Controller John Chiang said the raised rate was illegal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/aug/16/opinion/la-oe-gelinas-bell-bonds-20100816/2|title=Bell stuck in a money rut|publisher=Articles.latimes.com|date=2010-08-16|accessdate=2010-08-30|first=Nicole|last=Gelinas|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120717063854/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/aug/16/opinion/la-oe-gelinas-bell-bonds-20100816/2|archive-date=2012-07-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Wantanabe said the average for the county is 1.16%. Auditors had discovered that taxpayers were overcharged the $2.9 million for a \"retirement tax\" to fund city employee pensions.<ref name=\"sewer\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/03/local/la-me-bell-20100903|work=The Los Angeles Times|title=Bell assessed illegal sewer fees|first=Kim|last=Christensen|date=2010-09-03|access-date=2010-09-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906125338/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/03/local/la-me-bell-20100903|archive-date=2010-09-06|url-status=live}}</ref> Under California's state tax code, the nearly $3 million overpaid by Bell homeowners, should be redirected to local schools, however, on September 1, 2010, lawmakers approved AB 900 by Assemblyman Kevin De Leon (D- Los Angeles), which returns $2.9 million in property tax refunds directly to the overcharged city residents.<ref name=cons>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-legis-bell-20100901,0,2270637.story|work=Los Angeles Times|first1=Patrick|last1=McGreevy|first2=Jack|last2=Dolan|title=California legislators OK pay reforms inspired by Bell scandal|date=2010-09-01|access-date=2010-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901210038/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-legis-bell-20100901,0,2270637.story|archive-date=2010-09-01|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 13, 2010 Lieutenant Governor [[Abel Maldonado]], approved the bill.<ref name=\"abclocal1\">{{Cite web |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flos_angeles&id=7664687 |title=\"Bell homeowners await refunds from tax scam\" |access-date=2019-10-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100916075851/http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flos_angeles&id=7664687 |archive-date=2010-09-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Illegal sewer fees===\nThe city of Bell assessed property owners for sewer fees without getting the mandated voter approval. The ''Times'' acquired a letter to the city in which Controller John Chiang stated that property owners overpaid $621,737 in fees that were illegally increased since 2007. The extra tax added about $20 per parcel for each of the last three years\u2019 tax bills. After the salary scandal surfaced in July 2010, about a hundred residents protested at City Council meetings, saying they believed that their taxes were too high.<ref name=\"sewer\"/> Many residents said they had noticed assessments on their tax bills that they were never informed of and did not understand. ABC News announced that Bell homeowners who had overpaid their property taxes over the last three years would be refunded the funds that were collected illegally. In September 2010, Lieutenant Governor Maldonado signed [[Assembly Bill 900]], which returned $3,000,000 collected from 4,000 residents.<ref name=\"abclocal1\"/>\n\n===Auditor negligence===\nIn connection with an accusation (AC2012-17) that the [[audit]] firm [[Mayer Hoffman McCann P.C.]] (MHM) of [[Irvine, California]] \"committed repeated acts of negligence on more than one occasion in the 2009 audit of the City of Bell (Bell) and the Bell Community Redevelopment Agency (Bell CRA) that departed from professional standards\" and \"insufficiently documented its audit for Bell and the Bell CRA for the year ending June 30, 2009\" the [[California Board of Accountancy]] suspended MHM's [[Certified Public Accountant|CPA]] Corporation License for six months stayed, with two years' probation, and imposed on it an administrative penalty of $300,000, among other enforcement actions, effective June 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dca.ca.gov/cba/updates/update70.pdf |title=UPDATE, Issue No 70, Fall 2012, California Board of Accountancy, p.23 |access-date=2012-12-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114122608/http://www.dca.ca.gov/cba/updates/update70.pdf |archive-date=2012-11-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Local newspaper died as Rizzo was hired ==\n\nA local newspaper, the ''Industrial Post'', was founded in Bell in 1924.  It was renamed at least twice, becoming ''Community News'' by 1998, when it was sold.  Rizzo was hired around that time.  The ''Community News'' ceased publication shortly thereafter.  Journalist Terry Francke claimed that, \"the Bell spectacle is what happens to communities without their own old-fashioned diligent news coverage by veteran newspaper reporters, or at least smart reporters led by veteran newspaper editors.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Francke|first1=Terry|title=Why the Bell Scandal Happened and What Can Be Done|url=http://voiceofoc.org/2010/07/why-the-bell-scandal-happened-and-what-can-be-done/|accessdate=2017-01-22|publisher=Voice of OC|date=July 28, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129102638/http://voiceofoc.org/2010/07/why-the-bell-scandal-happened-and-what-can-be-done/|archive-date=January 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nU.S. Rep. [[Adam Schiff]], D-[[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]], appealed to federal prosecutors to scrutinize the widespread political corruption in Los Angeles County.  At least six other cities where officials have been recently charged with corruption include [[Irwindale]], [[La Puente]], [[Monterey Park, California|Monterey Park]], [[Pico Rivera]], [[Temple City]], and [[Vernon, California|Vernon]]. \"A much more rigorous focus is obviously merited by events\", Schiff said, citing statutes that specifically aim at scams involving  taxpayer dollars. \"Some of these cases are difficult to prosecute (at the local level) and where the U.S. Attorney does very well is chasing it down.\"   Schiff said he would like to see federal prosecutors look closely at these several cities beside Bell. \"I think they have a compelling interest ...The federal government clearly has jurisdiction in public corruption investigations\", Schiff said.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sgvtribune.com/ci_16588894?IADID=Search-www.sgvtribune.com-www.sgvtribune.com |title=Schiff calls on feds to open local corruption investigations |access-date=2010-11-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716045922/http://www.sgvtribune.com/ci_16588894?IADID=Search-www.sgvtribune.com-www.sgvtribune.com |archive-date=2011-07-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe crackdown in Bell has also received extensive coverage in the Spanish-language media and has resonated among voters in blue-collar Latino communities who often feel neglected in terms of both government services and the justice system,\" said Jaime Regalado, director of the Edmund G. \"Pat\" Brown Institute of Public Affairs at [[California State University, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Willon|first=Phil|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-politics-20100923,0,5041670.story|title=Bell crackdowns hand statewide candidates a chance to shine|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-09-27|accessdate=2010-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100927224038/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-politics-20100923,0,5041670.story|archive-date=2010-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Palm Springs Desert Sun'' maintained, in an editorial:\n<blockquote>That, in a very disturbing way, we all owe the community of Bell thanks. The elected and unelected hierarchy of that [small] city went to the extremes while its voters slept... As it is today, every California citizen has a right to ask public agencies for an accounting of their taxpayer-funded salaries and other compensation. That goes for any public employee\u2014from the city manager and council members to any teacher or librarian.<ref>Associated Press, [http://www.mercurynews.com/breaking-news/ci_15818351?nclick_check=1 \"Recent California newspaper editorials\"], ''Mercury News'', quoting the ''Palm Springs Desert Sun'' of August 15, 2010.</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Awards for expose of scandal==\n''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reporters Ruben Vives and Jeff Gottlieb were awarded the [[Selden Ring Award|Selden Ring Award for Investigative Reporting]] for the expose of the Bell salary scandal, 'Breach of Faith'. The Award, presented by the Annenberg School for Communication & Journalism, the prize is worth $35,000.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.laobserved.com/archive/2011/02/selden_ring_award_to_the.php |title=\"Selden Ring award to the LAT's Bell team\" |access-date=2011-03-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110302102634/http://www.laobserved.com/archive/2011/02/selden_ring_award_to_the.php |archive-date=2011-03-02 |url-status=live }}</ref> On April 18, 2011, it was announced that the ''[[L.A. Times]]'' had won the [[Pulitzer Prize for Public Service]] reporting on breaking the Bell scandal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/04/18/national/main20055012.shtml|work=CBS News|title=LA Times wins Pulitzer for Bell, Calif., scandal|date=2011-04-18|access-date=2011-04-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110421054028/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/04/18/national/main20055012.shtml|archive-date=2011-04-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe ''L.A. Times'' announced the winners of its in-house editorial awards May 2011. The paper's [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning Bell coverage won in the \"investigations\" category as well as the ''Publisher's Prize''. ''The Times''' publisher Eddie Hartenstein said of his paper's Bell coverage: \"Robert Rizzo and his cronies, I think, savored their windfall and knew all too well what they were doing and knew they had to keep it secret. And if anyone was bold enough to uncover it, it was some of our folks here. They went to ask the city clerks at Bell, Calif., and the response they got repeatedly was 'Those records aren't available; come back in two weeks.' But they wouldn't accept that ... [W]hen [the lid] finally came off the Bell salary scandal, it was not because of a grand jury or a conscience-stricken official or anything like that. It was because of two intrepid ''L.A. Times'' reporters.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlla/la-times-announces-winners-of-its-2010-editorial-awards_b29180 |title=''L.A. Times'' Announces Winners of its '2010 Editorial Awards' |access-date=2011-05-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104005258/http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlla/la-times-announces-winners-of-its-2010-editorial-awards_b29180 |archive-date=2011-11-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[True Detective (season 2)|''True Detective'' Season 2]] is loosely based on the events in Bell, CA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-vernon-true-detective-20150619-story.html|title='True Detective' setting based on California city with a corrupt past|last=Times|first=Los Angeles|website=latimes.com|access-date=2016-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012180223/http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-vernon-true-detective-20150619-story.html|archive-date=2016-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2011/05/arrested-bell-official-gets-his-street-art-close-up-in-downtown-la.html Robert Rizzo as street art, from the ''Los Angeles Times'']\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bell, California}}\n[[Category:Bell, California]]\n[[Category:Political scandals in California]]\n[[Category:2010 in California]]\n[[Category:2011 in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Robert Rizzo|the German musician|Robert Hunecke-Rizzo}}\n\nThe '''Bell scandal''' involved the misappropriation of public funds in [[Bell, California|Bell]], [[California]], [[United States]], over a period of several years in the late 2000s. In July 2010, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' published an [[investigative journalism|investigative article]] on possible malfeasance in the neighboring city of [[Maywood, California|Maywood]], revealing that the city officials of Bell received salaries that were reported as the highest in the nation.<ref name=\"latimes11\">{{cite news|author=Jeff Gottlieb|author2=Ruben Vives|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/bell-city-manager-might-highest-paid-in-nation-787637-a-year.html|title=Bell city manager could possibly be highest paid in nation: $787,637 a year|publisher=Latimesblogs.latimes.com|date=2010-07-14|accessdate=2010-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722021336/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/bell-city-manager-might-highest-paid-in-nation-787637-a-year.html|archive-date=2010-07-22|url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequent investigations found atypically high [[property tax]] rates, allegations of [[voter fraud]] in municipal elections and other irregularities which heightened the ensuing [[scandal]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|last=Fund|first=John|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703309704575413393066886472?mod=googlenews_wsj|title=It All Starts with Vote Fraud|publisher=Online.wsj.com|date=2010-08-07|accessdate=2010-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819233801/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703309704575413393066886472?mod=googlenews_wsj|archive-date=2017-08-19|url-status=live}}</ref> These and other reports led to widespread criticism and a demand for city officials to resign.<ref name=\"latimes2\">{{cite news|first=Jeff|last=Gottlieb|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/787000-salary-for-bell-city-manager-is-outrageous-assemblyman-hector-de-la-torre-says.html|title=$787,000 salary for Bell city manager is outrageous, assemblyman says|publisher=Latimesblogs.latimes.com|date=2010-07-16|accessdate=2010-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719224103/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/787000-salary-for-bell-city-manager-is-outrageous-assemblyman-hector-de-la-torre-says.html|archive-date=2010-07-19|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes3\">{{cite news|last=Knoll|first=Corina|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0716-bell-residents-20100716,0,4326515.story|title=Residents of Bell unhappy over perceived high salaries for city employees|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-07-16|accessdate=2010-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812021930/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0716-bell-residents-20100716,0,4326515.story|archive-date=2010-08-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the end, seven Bell city officials, including former mayor Oscar Hernandez, former city administrator Robert Rizzo, assistant city administrator Angela Spaccia, and four city council members were convicted on [[graft (politics)|graft]] and [[corruption]] charges, and were given sentences ranging from [[probation]] to twelve years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Knoll|first1=Corina|last2=Gottlieb|first2=Jeff|title=Bell corruption case ends, last defendant gets a year in jail|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-final-bell-defendant-sentenced-20140801-story.html|accessdate=13 May 2015|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=1 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150513013834/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-final-bell-defendant-sentenced-20140801-story.html|archive-date=13 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==The community==\n[[Bell, California|Bell]], [[California]], is a small suburb of [[Los Angeles]] that covers {{convert|2.5|sqmi|km2|sigfig=2}}, with a population of approximately 38,000.<ref name=\"The Expose\">{{cite news|title=Is a city manager worth $800,000?|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715,0,7352605.story|first1=Jeff|last1=Gottlieb|first2=Ruben|last2=Vives|date=July 15, 2010|publisher=Los Angeles Times|access-date=July 29, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729035031/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715,0,7352605.story|archive-date=July 29, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> It is one of the poorer cities in [[Los Angeles County]],<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-20/california-official-s-800-000-salary-in-city-of-38-000-triggers-protests.html | work=Bloomberg | first=Christopher | last=Palmeri | title=California Official's $800,000 Salary in City of 38,000 Triggers Protests | date=2010-07-20 | access-date=2017-03-06 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110182042/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-20/california-official-s-800-000-salary-in-city-of-38-000-triggers-protests.html | archive-date=2015-01-10 | url-status=live }}</ref> with almost one in six residents lives below the poverty line.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-22/california-s-bell-used-as-cash-drawer-state-controller-says-after-audit.html |title=California's Bell Used as 'Cash Drawer,' State Controller Says After Audit |access-date=2017-03-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025030716/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-22/california-s-bell-used-as-cash-drawer-state-controller-says-after-audit.html |archive-date=2013-10-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2009, Bell's per capita income was about $24,800 and 90% of its residents were [[Hispanic people|Hispanic]] or [[Latino people|Latino]]. In 2010, only 43.3% held a high school degree or equivalent, while just 6.0% held a post-secondary degree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=bkmk|title=American FactFinder - Results|last=Bureau|first=U.S. Census|website=factfinder.census.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160205101044/http://www.census.gov/prod/2013pubs/acs-22.pdf|archive-date=2016-02-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> Small businesses, auto shops, markets, ''[[carniceria]]s'', and ''[[panaderia]]s'' dominate the streets of Bell.<ref name=\"people\"/> The city\u2019s unemployment level is 16%.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bowes|first=Peter|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-10798426|title=BBC News - California city pay scandal highlights media cuts|publisher=Bbc.co.uk|date=2010-07-31|accessdate=2010-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100910180207/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-10798426|archive-date=2010-09-10|url-status=live}}</ref> As with other cities in California, all of Bell's local elections are nonpartisan.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2010-09-21-bell-california-scandal_N.htm | work=USA Today | title=Corruption charges bring cheers, tears in California suburb | date=2010-09-22 | access-date=2013-10-03 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005044338/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2010-09-21-bell-california-scandal_N.htm | archive-date=2013-10-05 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Charter votes and irregularities===\nIn 2005, a measure approved by Bell voters exempted the city from a state law enacted earlier that year which limited the salary of council members of [[California#Cities.2C towns and counties|general-law cities]] &ndash; cities without a [[city charter|charter]] of their own. All five members of the Bell City Council signed a statement in favor of the \"little-noticed city ballot measure\", which converted Bell into a [[charter city]] and was \"billed as one that would give the city more control,\" yet failed to mention that Bell became exempted from the salary regulations. The measure passed, 336 votes in favor and 54 against.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/bell-council-found-loophole-in-law-to-allow-big-salaries.html |title=Jeff Gottlieb, \"Bell Council Found Loophole in Law to Allow Big Salaries,\" ''Los Angeles Times,'' July 22, 2010 |access-date=July 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725210352/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/bell-council-found-loophole-in-law-to-allow-big-salaries.html |archive-date=July 25, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe salaries and pensions scandal in Bell also brought into question the issue of [[voter fraud]]. In the 2005 election, fewer than 400 votes were cast in a special election that cleared the way for City Council members to dramatically boost their own salaries. In that election, more than half the votes cast were [[absentee ballot]]s, the most vulnerable method to manipulate fraudulent votes. One resident of Bell, on condition of anonymity, told the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' that he was assigned the chore of retrieving absentee ballots: \"Our objective was to collect absentee ballots, and if they were not filled out, instruct them how to fill it out, and if not, fill it out for them\", he said. It is estimated that less than 1% of registered voters actually showed up to cast their ballot.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> It has been reported that some residents went to the [[polling place]], only to find that their votes had already been cast.<ref>NBC news, August 9, 2010</ref>\n\n===Voter fraud led to scandal===\nAssertions about discrepancies in the 2009 election were also examined by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] and California's Secretary of State. A source at the FBI confirmed that they were aware of the accusations. In the police report were listed the names of 19 voters who allegedly were either living in [[Lebanon]], or were deceased at the time that their votes were cast.<ref>{{cite news|last=Winton|first=Richard|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-elections-20100728,0,4351844.story|title=Bell city scandal: L.A. County D.A. expands probe into Bell city government|publisher=latimes.com|date=2009-06-17|accessdate=2010-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730034358/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-elections-20100728,0,4351844.story|archive-date=2010-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref> As L.A. prosecutors investigated potential voter fraud, several citizens allegedly told the ''Times'' that city officials encouraged them to fill out absentee ballots in a manner that election experts said has significantly raised the possibility that state law has been violated.<ref>{{cite news|last=Esquivel|first=Paloma|url=http://www.latimes.com/la-me-election-fraud-bell-20100806,0,249341.story|title=Voters in Bell tell of possible fraud|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-08-05|accessdate=2010-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628202704/http://www.latimes.com/la-me-election-fraud-bell-20100806,0,249341.story|archive-date=2011-06-28|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Under state law, this is not to be done unless someone is ill or disabled. If, in fact, the election itself has been tainted by improper electioneering or other violations of state law, then that involves civil \u2014 maybe even criminal \u2014 penalties, and in some circumstances, you can overturn the election itself\", Attorney General [[Jerry Brown]] said. \"If (officials) met in a back room and said, 'How can we run an election where nobody shows up so we can then fatten our own salaries and pensions...that could constitute a violation that would bring into question the entire election.\"<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\n==The scandal==\nA series of [[investigative journalism|investigative article]]s published by the ''Times'' in July 2010 revealed that several city officials in Bell were being paid salaries significantly higher than those in other cities.<ref name=\"latimes11\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Gottlieb|first=Jeff|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715,0,7352605.story|title=Is a city manager worth $800,000?|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-07-15|accessdate=2010-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812022053/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715,0,7352605.story|archive-date=2010-08-12|url-status=live}}</ref> The two main reporters involved in the investigations were Ruben Vives and Jeff Gottlieb, and [[Kimi Yoshino]] was the guiding editor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/readers-rep/la-me-rr-kimi-yoshino-named-la-times-business-editor-20140320-story.html|title=Kimi Yoshino named L.A. Times Business editor|last=Edgar|first=Deirdre|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-01-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129140431/http://www.latimes.com/local/readers-rep/la-me-rr-kimi-yoshino-named-la-times-business-editor-20140320-story.html|archive-date=2018-01-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=130108851|title=How The L.A. Times Broke The Bell Corruption Story|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-01-28|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129080624/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=130108851|archive-date=2018-01-29|url-status=live}}</ref> In a press release issued through the Bell City Clerk's office, [[Mayor]] Oscar Hernandez claimed that \"salaries of the City Manager and other top city staff have been in line with similar positions over the period of their tenure,\" and then accused the ''Times'' of having a \"skewed view of the facts.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/scavenger/detail?entry_id=68800|work=The San Francisco Chronicle|first=Aileen|last=Yoo|title=Bell official made $700K+ while city laid off workers|date=2010-07-27|access-date=2010-08-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100829023950/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/scavenger/detail?entry_id=68800|archive-date=2010-08-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bellcityclerk.org/ftp/City%20of%20Bell%20Statement_072210.pdf |title=Bell City Clerk's office website |access-date=2010-08-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429174838/http://www.bellcityclerk.org/ftp/City%20of%20Bell%20Statement_072210.pdf |archive-date=2014-04-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Hernandez later apologized for what he called the city's \"indefensible administrative salaries\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Christopher Palmeri|url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-07-26/california-mayor-regrets-indefensible-salaries.html|title=California Mayor Regrets 'Indefensible' Salaries|publisher=BusinessWeek|date=2010-07-26|accessdate=2010-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730080245/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-07-26/california-mayor-regrets-indefensible-salaries.html|archive-date=2010-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref> He was later recalled, arrested, and indicted for [[fraud]] and other charges.\n\nBell City Council members later voted to reduce their pay to that of what one councilman, Lorenzo Velez, was being paid: $8,076 a year. Prior to that meeting, all of the other council members were making at least ten times that figure.<ref name=\"salary\">{{cite news|author=CNN Wire Staff|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/POLITICS/07/27/california.salaries/index.html?section=cnn_latest|title=California officials reduce salaries in response to outcry|publisher=CNN.com|date=2010-07-27|accessdate=2010-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109110055/http://www.cnn.com/2010/POLITICS/07/27/california.salaries/index.html?section=cnn_latest|archive-date=2012-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref>  [[State Controller]] [[John Chiang (California politician)|John Chiang]] said that the salaries in Bell had been \"outrageous and unjustifiable\" and a voter fraud hotline was set up.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wavenewspapers.com/news/Attorney-General-Jerry-Brown-subpoenas-Bell-officials-sets-up-voter-fraud-hotline-100321659.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722142250/http://www.wavenewspapers.com/news/Attorney-General-Jerry-Brown-subpoenas-Bell-officials-sets-up-voter-fraud-hotline-100321659.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-07-22|title=AG Jerry Brown subpoenas Bell officials, sets up voter fraud hotline &#124;|publisher=Wavenewspapers.com|date=2010-08-10|accessdate=2010-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Trussell|first=Donna|url=http://www.politicsdaily.com/2010/08/03/california-will-post-city-officials-salaries-after-bell-scandal|title=California Will Post City Officials' Salaries After Bell Scandal|publisher=Politicsdaily.com|accessdate=2010-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100805030126/http://www.politicsdaily.com/2010/08/03/california-will-post-city-officials-salaries-after-bell-scandal/|archive-date=2010-08-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDocuments released to the ''Times'' revealed that the [[California Public Employees' Retirement System]] (CalPERS) knew four years previously that Rizzo had received a 47% pay increase to $442,000. Then-[[Attorney General of California|California Attorney General]] [[Jerry Brown]] maintained that such a large increase should have aroused suspicion from CalPERS.<ref name=\"latimes10\">{{cite news|last=Halper|first=Evan|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-pensions-20100806,0,711701.story|title=Bell salaries raise more concerns about CalPERS|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-08-06|accessdate=2010-08-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812021718/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-pensions-20100806,0,711701.story|archive-date=2010-08-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\"These outrageous salaries in Bell are shocking and beyond belief,\" said Brown. \"With record deficits and painful budget cuts facing California cities, astronomical local government salaries raise serious questions and demand a thorough investigation.\"<ref name=\"Palmeri\"/>\n\nThe end of August 2010 ended the California legislature\u2019s law-making season, and the bill (AB1955) that would have strictly regulated elected officials\u2019 income levels died while in the [[California State Senate]].<ref name=\"SH\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.signaltribunenewspaper.com/archives/7696 |title=Signal Hill city manager explains councilmembers\u2019 complicated salaries |access-date=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100913031942/http://www.signaltribunenewspaper.com/archives/7696 |archive-date=2010-09-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> All the related bills were vetoed by [[Governor of California|Governor]] [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]].<ref name=\"blogs.sacbee.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.sacbee.com/capitolalertlatest/2010/10/schwarzenegger-on-pension-bill.html |title=Capitol Alert: Schwarzenegger on key pension bill: \"Taxpayers deserve better\" |access-date=2010-10-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825043355/http://blogs.sacbee.com/capitolalertlatest/2010/10/schwarzenegger-on-pension-bill.html |archive-date=2011-08-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A piece of legislation that had passed before the legislature\u2019s deadline, AB1987, would have put an end to the public employee practice of pension \"spiking\" &ndash; the accumulation of vacation and sick time until the end of their tenure so their retirement benefit is increased, sometimes by tens of thousands of dollars per year;<ref name=\"SH\"/> this bill was also vetoed by Governor Schwarzenegger.<ref name=\"blogs.sacbee.com\"/>\n\n\"Frankly, Bell residents need to know if their city is solvent,\" said Supervisor [[Gloria Molina]], who chairs the board and whose district includes Bell. Molina said the audit, expected to cost about $100,000, was paid for out of her office's discretionary fund, at no cost to the city.\n\nMarcia Fritz, who heads the California Foundation for Fiscal Responsibility stated that at age 62, when Rizzo could have  begun receiving Social Security payments, his annual pension and benefits would have risen to $976,771, topping $1 million two years later. \"This guy would be our first seven-figure retiree,\" said Fritz.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE66K6BX20100721|work=Reuters|title=California city manager's pension could top $30 million|date=2010-07-21|access-date=2017-06-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924023643/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE66K6BX20100721|archive-date=2010-09-24|url-status=live}}</ref> The million-dollar pension Rizzo was expecting has been reduced to about $100,000 per year. The other seven city council members arrested for misappropriating funds received similar pension cuts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flos_angeles&id=7787134 |title=\"Bell officials won't receive massive pensions\" |access-date=2019-10-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101116005902/http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flos_angeles&id=7787134 |archive-date=2010-11-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nA week after Brown sued, Rizzo and six of the other seven people named in his suit were charged in criminal court with plundering $5.5 million from Bell.<ref name=\"lau\">{{Cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/Judge-questions-suit-over-CA-apf-1750055294.html?x=0&.v=1 |title=\"Judge questions suit over CA city's big salaries\" |access-date=2017-01-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107145417/http://finance.yahoo.com/news/Judge-questions-suit-over-CA-apf-1750055294.html?x=0&.v=1 |archive-date=2011-11-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> More secreted funds containing millions of dollars were discovered in April 2011. Judge Ralph W. Dau ruled that the parts of the lawsuit accusing Rizzo and the others of \"conflict of interest, squandering public funds and putting their own interests ahead of Bell's\" could move forward. When Brown announced the lawsuit, he said he hoped to recoup hundreds of thousands of dollars for residents. He acknowledged it was a \"novel legal approach\" but said he was \"confident his office had the authority.\"<ref name=\"lau\"/>\n\nThe city of Bell had a difficult time restoring some semblance of normality in the year following the salary scandal. Residents voted in a completely new city council, and Bell's interim city manager stabilized the shaky financial position by implementing a balanced budget that eliminated several high-ranking administrative and police positions, uses federal grant money to pay some police officers\u2019 salaries, and makes other cuts.<ref name=\"CBS2\">{{Cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/07/21/scandal-plagued-city-of-bell-may-face-layoffs-cutbacks |title=Bell faces layoffs and cutbacks\" |access-date=2011-07-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510091556/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/07/21/scandal-plagued-city-of-bell-may-face-layoffs-cutbacks/ |archive-date=2012-05-10 |url-status=live }}</ref> On August 12, 2011, the city announced that Arne Croce would serve as yet another interim city manager. He started at a weekly salary of $3,230 with no medical or retirement benefits, replacing interim city manager Kenneth Hampian<ref>[http://www.cbs47.tv/news/state/story/Troubled-city-of-Bell-selects-interim-manager/vEXquLYyVk2y_wnhS9bNog.cspx?rss=154 \"Bell selects new interim city manager\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAs Governor, Jerry Brown made it more difficult for city council members to dishonestly pad their paychecks. Brown signed into law Assemblyman [[Cameron Smyth]] (R-Santa Clarita)'s legislation, AB 23, which requires city officials to publicize when they are holding concurrent or consecutive meetings, and how much the meeting attendees will receive in salaries. \"The intent is to discourage the potential abuses by making public how much officials are being paid,\" Smyth said.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/california-politics/2011/07/bell-related-reform-bill-signed-by-governor.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=PolitiCal|date=2011-07-25|access-date=2011-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813192909/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/california-politics/2011/07/bell-related-reform-bill-signed-by-governor.html|archive-date=2011-08-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==\"Special Election\" 2011==\n33% of Bell's 10,485 registered voters turned out to vote <ref name=\"election\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ktla.com/news/landing/ktla-march-8-election-results-bell,0,1796421,full.story |title=RESULTS: March 8 Election Results - City of Bell Special Election |access-date=2011-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401165659/http://www.ktla.com/news/landing/ktla-march-8-election-results-bell,0,1796421,full.story |archive-date=2012-04-01 |url-status=live }}</ref> in a recall election for the City Council members.<ref name=\"Times8\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-elections-20110308,0,3630943.story|work=Los Angeles Times|first1=Christopher|authorlink1=Christopher Goffard|last1=Goffard|first2=Paloma|last2=Esquivel|title=Bell voters cast out the old and opt for the new|date=2011-03-09}}</ref> Mayor Hernandez, Deputy Mayor Jacobo and Council member George Mirabal, were all recalled, each with a referendum of over 95%.<ref name=\"election\"/>\nDanny Harber received 54% of the vote to gain Jacobo's seat.  Filling the short term council seat vacated by Mirabal, is Ana Maria Quintana, with 44% of the vote.<ref name=\"election\"/> The next day it was announced that Ali Saleh, Nestor Valencia and Violeta Alvarez will fill the other three council seats.\n<ref name=\"election\"/> Councilman Lorenzo Velez, the only Bell official not charged with wrongdoing,<ref name=\"nbclosangeles1\">[http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local-beat/City-of-Bell-to-Investigate-High-Salaries-98758759.html \"City of Bell Postpones Investigation of High Salaries\"]</ref> was also replaced on the city council.<ref name=\"glitch\">{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.sacbee.com/capitolalertlatest/2011/03/lawmakers-target-glitch-caused.html#mi_rss=Latest%20News |title=Capitol Alert: Lawmakers target glitch caused by Bell City Council arrests |access-date=2011-03-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324230251/http://blogs.sacbee.com/capitolalertlatest/2011/03/lawmakers-target-glitch-caused.html#mi_rss=Latest%20News |archive-date=2011-03-24 |url-status=live }}</ref> Assembly Bill 93 which allows the City Clerk to swear in the new council and also allows the [[Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors]] to validate  the March 8 election results. The new city council has been unable to take office because there was no quorum (none) of the former city council to swear them in. They were sworn in the last week of March 2011.<ref name=\"glitch\"/> The council has designated Ali Saleh as the new mayor.<ref>[https://archive.today/20120909024059/http://www.scpr.org/news/2011/04/27/new-bell-mayor-talks-about-efforts-fix-citys-budge \"New Bell Mayor Talks About Efforts to Fix City's Budget, Prevent Corruption\", April 27, 2011, Southern California Public Radio]</ref>\n\nThe California Fair Political Practices Commission said July 1, 2011, that it is investigating whether Bell's police union violated state law when the union handed out a campaign flyer supporting their candidates in the recall election. The commission said it is looking into whether the Bell Police Officers Association was properly noted as the source of the flyer. Three of the five council persons elected were those endorsed by the Bell Police Officers Association.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9NTR0K81.htm |title=Bell Police Officers Association investigated by California Fair Political Practices Commission |access-date=2011-07-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102063104/http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9NTR0K81.htm |archive-date=2012-11-02 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Corruption hearings==\n===City Council===\nThe preliminary hearing for the alleged misappropriations and misdeeds of the Bell City council members charged, began on February 7, 2011. Councilman Lorenzo Velez, the only Bell official not charged with any wrongdoing, testified that he doesn't remember participating in any of the meetings for which other council members billed the city tens of thousands of dollars. Velez testified that he doesn't recall any of the council members doing any work for any of the committees or if there were ever actually any meetings held at all.<ref name=\"abcnews1\"/> \"I should have asked more questions, I'm not denying that\", said Velez, the only member of the city council who did not take a large salary. \"If ignorance is a crime, I guess I'm guilty.\" Velez was defeated in the March 2011 election. The defendants at this preliminary hearing are Hernandez, Jacobo, Mirabal, former Mayor George Cole and former Councilmen Luis Artiga and [[Victor Bello]].<ref name=KTLA>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ktla.com/news/landing/ktla-bell-city-clerk-testimony,0,1288241.story |title=Bell Salary Scandal: \"Bell City Clerk Testifies Robert Rizzo Made Her Lie\" |access-date=2011-02-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713180355/http://www.ktla.com/news/landing/ktla-bell-city-clerk-testimony,0,1288241.story |archive-date=2011-07-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFormer city clerk, Rebecca Valez, testified at the hearing that she was instructed by Rizzo to lie to resident, Roger Ramirez, who had enquired about council members salaries. The first witness at the preliminary hearing, Ramirez testified that when he confronted Rizzo at a city council meeting, regarding  the rumors  that he was paid $400,000 a year, \"He immediately said, 'No, Mr. Ramirez, if I would be making $400,000 a year I wouldn't be working here\". Ramirez had previously filed a public records request with City Hall. The bogus records he was given showed Rizzo was earning about $15,000 per month, and City Council members a couple hundred dollars per month.<ref name=\"AP_Feb23\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2011/feb/23/differing-views-of-ca-official-crook-or-victim/ |title=Differing views of CA official: Crook or victim? |author=John Rogers, Associated Press |work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]] |date=February 23, 2011 |accessdate=February 21, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303081053/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2011/feb/23/differing-views-of-ca-official-crook-or-victim/ |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Valez, who has partial immunity, stated she prepared the documents and Rizzo changed the correct figures much lower than the actual salaries; she was ordered to show the falsified lowered figures to Ramirez.<ref name=KTLA/> She also testified that Rizzo awarded himself contracts with hefty raises without any approval from the city attorney.<ref name=\"AP_Feb23\"/>\n\nBell's administrative services director, Lourdes Garcia, said shortly before she gave Ramirez the falsified documents, City Clerk Rebecca Valdez confided to her that Rizzo had directed her to have Mayor Oscar Hernandez retroactively sign Rizzo's contracts, although Hernandez was not mayor during the period that the contracts  were written. \"She was crying\", Garcia said about Valdez. \"She was very nervous.\" Valdez testified at the earlier hearing that Rizzo had instructed her to give Ramirez the fabricated figures.<ref name =\"AP_Feb23\"/> The testimony has ended and LA Superior Court Judge Henry Hall is expected to issue a ruling after the opposing attorneys present their arguments.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/02/16/bell-corruption-hearing-nears-end |title=\"Bell Corruption Hearing Ends\" |access-date=2011-03-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131130326/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/02/16/bell-corruption-hearing-nears-end/ |archive-date=2016-01-31 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA pretrial hearing was set for May  2011 for the six defendants. They all had to be arraigned again after the judge made the decision to put them on trial. They have all pleaded not guilty to all charges <ref name=\"kfiam640.com\">[http://www.kfiam640.com/cc-common/mainheadlines3.html?feed=153218&article=8315354 \"Ex Bell Officials Plead Not Guilty\"]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe trial began January 22, 2013, with deliberations beginning February 28. Deliberations were halted February 28 after a juror admitted to discussing the trial outside of the jury room. An alternate juror was seated and deliberations continued. After 18 days of deliberations five councilmembers were found guilty on some of the charges and not guilty on an equal number of charges, with other charges split 9-3 in favor of guilt. Luis Artiga, who took office after the high pay began, was exonerated of all charges.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Verdict-Reached-in-Bell-6-Corruption-Trial-199193191.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151103003104/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Verdict-Reached-in-Bell-6-Corruption-Trial-199193191.html |archive-date=2015-11-03 |url-status=live }}</ref> Subsequently, on March 21, a juror wrote notes to the judge requesting reconsideration of past verdicts, and another juror wrote a note accusing other jurors of bad behavior. \"It seems that all hell has broken loose,\" remarked the judge to attorneys in the case. After another day of deliberation, the judge declared a mistrial on all remaining counts, leaving the prosecution to determine if they wanted the case retried.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2013/03/22/36509/strange-end-of-bell-corruption-trial-may-spur-appe/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731143929/http://www.scpr.org/news/2013/03/22/36509/strange-end-of-bell-corruption-trial-may-spur-appe/ |archive-date=2013-07-31 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Former City Manager and assistant===\nAt Rizzo's hearing, documents acquired from former Assistant City Manager Angela Spaccia's computer by District Attorney Steve Cooley show that starting in 2005, she and Rizzo created fraudulent contracts that were not sanctioned by the City Council that elevated their salaries to \"outrageous\" levels and made it almost impossible to tell how much they were being paid, according to the 19-page memorandum from Cooley. \"Rizzo and Spaccia succeeded in concealing their conduct for so long, in part by trickery ... and in part by buying loyalty of city employees,\" the memo said.<ref name=\"sfgate.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2011/02/14/state/n153217S40.DTL&type=science |title=Scandal-ridden CA city's leaders ordered to trial |work=The San Francisco Chronicle }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Rizzo is allegedly considered the ringleader among the \"Bell Eight\",  former Bell city officials (now resigned, recalled or fired), accused of bilking taxpayers out of about $5.5 million through hefty salaries, benefits and illegal loans of public money.<ref name=\"March25\"/>\n\nIn his opening presentation, Rizzo's attorney, James Spertus, stated, \"Everybody has agreed that it's not a crime to be paid too much.\"<ref name=\"AP_Feb23\"/> Later that day, February 23, 2011, Rizzo complained of chest pains and feeling light-headed and was carried out on a stretcher during his preliminary hearing. He held a towel over his face as paramedics removed him to an ambulance. He was transported to [[Good Samaritan Hospital (Los Angeles)|Good Samaritan Hospital]], and the hearing was adjourned for the day.<ref>[http://www.topix.com/city/bell-ca/2011/02/rizzo-removed-on-gurney-from-courthouse \"Rizzo Removed on Gurney From Courthouse\"]</ref> Rizzo was released from the hospital the next day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/02/ex-bell-city-administrator-rizzo-released-from-hospital.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=L.A. Now|date=2011-02-25|access-date=2011-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228232908/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/02/ex-bell-city-administrator-rizzo-released-from-hospital.html|archive-date=2011-02-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Rizzo returned to court the following Monday.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Rizzo-Returns-to-Courtroom-Bell-Preliminary-hearing-117078903.html |title=\"Rizzo Returns to Court\" |access-date=2011-03-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714161126/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Rizzo-Returns-to-Courtroom-Bell-Preliminary-hearing-117078903.html |archive-date=2011-07-14 |url-status=live }}</ref> The next day, Rizzo slept through a good part of the hearing.<ref name=\"abc\">{{Cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/bell-california-scandal-reaches-court-city-manager-dozes/story?id=13028339 |title=\"Bell, California Scandal Reaches Court, Where City Manager Dozes off at Hearing\" |access-date=2011-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628204902/http://abcnews.go.com/US/bell-california-scandal-reaches-court-city-manager-dozes/story?id=13028339 |archive-date=2011-06-28 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn Friday of the same week, the focal point was Rizzo's enormous salary and  what machinations were made for him to receive it. The main issue was who had signed Rizzo's employment contracts, since although the former city attorney acknowledged the signatures appeared to be his, he claimed he did not sign them.  The D.A. claims that Rizzo signed them himself.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flos_angeles&id=7995970&rss=rss-kabc-article-7995970 |title=\"Bell testimony centers on Robert Rizzo's big salary\" |access-date=2019-10-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628230407/http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flos_angeles&id=7995970&rss=rss-kabc-article-7995970 |archive-date=2011-06-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nA second preliminary hearing for misappropriation of public funds<ref name=\"March10\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/politics/rizzo-preliminary-hearing-ruling-117732743.html |title=\"Rizzo to Stand Trial\" |access-date=2011-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714161217/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/politics/rizzo-preliminary-hearing-ruling-117732743.html |archive-date=2011-07-14 |url-status=live }}</ref> by Rizzo, and former Assistant City Manager Angela Spaccia,  began March 22, 2011.<ref name=\"CBS\"/>  The pair have already been ordered to stand trial on the previous charges.<ref name=\"March10\"/> At that arraignment on March 24, 2011, Rizzo, Spaccia, former Mayor Hernandez and ex-councilman Luis Artiga plead not guilty to the charges that they plundered tiny Bell of millions of dollars.<ref>[http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/mar/27/us-bell-salaries ''Las Vegas Sun'' coverage of Bell scandal\"]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n====More charges for the duo====\nRizzo and Spaccia were indicted on several new allegations by the  Los Angeles Grand Jury on March 30, 2011. The allegations include  new charges of misappropriating public funds, conflict of interest, falsifying public  documents and secreting of public documents.<ref name=\"March30\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Former-Bell-City-Manager-Indicted-on-New-Charges-Rizzo-118924659.html |title=\"Former Bell City Manager Indicted on New Charges\" |access-date=2011-03-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830031235/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Former-Bell-City-Manager-Indicted-on-New-Charges-Rizzo-118924659.html |archive-date=2012-08-30 |url-status=live }}</ref> Yet another allegation claims that the duo fabricated documents  appearing to be contracts for former police Chief Randy Adams and secreted the true contracts' indication that his salary was nearly $10,000 more per pay period than purported.<ref name=\"March30\"/>  These indictments add eight charges to the public corruption case against Rizzo and seven  former Bell officials<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/31/local/la-me-0331-bell-indictment-20110331|work=Los Angeles Times|first1=Jeff|last1=Gottlieb|first2=Corina|last2=Knoll|date=2011-03-31|title=Robert Rizzo, aide accused of conspiracy in Bell corruption scandal|access-date=2011-05-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110410040257/http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/31/local/la-me-0331-bell-indictment-20110331|archive-date=2011-04-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====More money secreted away====\nOn April 25, 2011, it was revealed  that at least two more illegal retirement accounts have been discovered. An additional $4.5 million was found secreted away to  avoid retirement limits for  public employees and to benefit Rizzo, Spaccia and a select few council members.<ref name=Huff1>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/04/26/robert-rizzo-pension-fund_n_853812.html |title=\"Secret Robert Rizzo Pension Fund Contained $4.5 Million\" |access-date=2011-05-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113054921/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/04/26/robert-rizzo-pension-fund_n_853812.html |archive-date=2012-11-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another account was found to be set up to benefit only Rizzo and Spaccia, letting them  evade IRS regulations which cap government pensions.<ref name=Huff1/> Lourdes Garcia, the city's director of administrative services, testified under limited immunity that Rizzo told her in 2008 that his goal was to put $14 million in the secondary pension fund, which would be  paid by  the city.<ref name=Huff1/>\n\n====Ousted officials demanded more city funds====\nFour of the city officials have requested that the city of Bell pay their legal bills. Hernandez, Jacobo and Cole are facing corruption charges for allegedly looting the city's treasury, according to the ''[[L.A. Times]]'' in January 2011. A city audit has shown that the city is close to bankruptcy.<ref name=Jan>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/01/accused-bell-officials-want-cash-strapped-city-to-pay-their-legal-bills.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=L.A. Now|date=2011-01-10|access-date=2011-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113110903/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/01/accused-bell-officials-want-cash-strapped-city-to-pay-their-legal-bills.html|archive-date=2011-01-13|url-status=live}}</ref> Cole's attorney, Robert Kaye, claims that, although he was being paid approximately $100,000 a year for his part-time position and for attending  meetings that did not occur or lasted only a few minutes that \u201cAt that time... Mr. Cole did not believe that his actions were unlawful.\u201d <ref name=Jan/> Superior Court Judge Henry J. Hall ordered in February 2011, that no compensation be paid to city officials without approval from the court.<ref name=\"losangeles.cbslocal.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/02/17/bell-city-hall-stays-open-during-trial |title=Bell City Hall Stays Open During TrialCBS Los Angeles |access-date=2011-02-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221110220/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/02/17/bell-city-hall-stays-open-during-trial/ |archive-date=2011-02-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, in March 2011, Robert Rizzo (and two other former councilmen) persisted in their claim that they are entitled to reimbursement from the city of Bell for his legal fees spent in his defense against his charges of defrauding the city of Bell out of millions of dollars.<ref name=\"March25\">{{Cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/03/25/rizzo-asks-judge-to-order-bell-to-reimburse-legal-fees |title=\"Rizzo Asks Judge To Order Bell To Reimburse Legal Fees\" |access-date=2011-03-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131130326/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/03/25/rizzo-asks-judge-to-order-bell-to-reimburse-legal-fees/ |archive-date=2016-01-31 |url-status=live }}</ref> Former Bell City Attorney Edward Lee confirmed during a testimony in 2010 that he outlined the  clause in Rizzo\u2019s contract that was intended to guarantee the former city manager defense funds \"against any type of claim\", according the court papers.<ref name=\"March25\"/> \"All of the claims triggered a defense obligation from the city of Bell under Mr. Rizzo's employment agreement and he sent the claims to the city for a defense, but the tenders were all denied by the city\", Rizzo's updated court papers attested. In June  2011, there was a hearing  regarding Rizzo's request<ref name=\"March25\"/> and the issue of ''intent'' in the employment agreement.\n\n==Hearings==\nA two-sentence order denying the petition was later signed without comment by Justices Dennis M. Perluss and Laurie D. Zelon of the 2nd District Court of Appeal in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"denial\">{{cite news | url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-appeal-20120101,0,4281581.story?track=rss | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Jeff | last=Gottlieb | title=Six former Bell council members lose appeal | date=2011-12-31 | access-date=2012-01-18 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101195249/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-appeal-20120101,0,4281581.story?track=rss | archive-date=2012-01-01 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, Los Angeles County Superior Court Judge Kathleen Kennedy rejected their motion to drop the charges and the contention that their  salaries were protected by the city's charter.  She  issued an extremely critical  ten-page ruling that completely negated the politicians' claim that they had no intent of or knowledge they could possibly be breaking the law.  \"The city of Bell charter,\" Kennedy wrote, \"did not make Bell a sovereign nation not subject to the general penal laws of the State of California.\"<ref name=\"denial\"/>\n\nOn February 28, 2012, Judge Kennedy dismissed some felony charges against ex-Mayor Oscar Hernandez and two counts of misappropriation of public funds against former ex-councilman Luis Artiga. Hernandez and Artiga will still face the charges of misappropriating funds in a separate case.  The judge denied the motion to dismiss any charges against the ex- city manager Robert Rizzo and his assistant Angela Spaccia.<ref name=\"update2012\">{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/28/bell-salary-scandal_n_1308084.html | work=Huffington Post | title=Felony Charges Against Former Bell Officials Dropped | date=2012-02-28 | access-date=2012-04-08 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303015536/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/28/bell-salary-scandal_n_1308084.html | archive-date=2012-03-03 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn her February 9 ruling, Kennedy stated that Rizzo \"virtually ran this loan program unilaterally\" and distributed at least 40 loans totaling almost $2 million between 2001 and 2010.  In rejecting the dismissal motion by Rizzo and Spaccia, Kennedy said they \"simply set their own financial terms awarding themselves huge raises and other fringe benefits,\" and that \"This is a textbook case of conflict of interest.\"<ref name=\"update2012\"/>\n\n==Salary dispute==\n===Bell city manager===\nRizzo collected a salary of [[United States dollar|US$]] 787,637 a year, with yearly 12% increases scheduled every July, he received $1.5 million in the last year.<ref name=\"denial\"/><ref name=\"latimes7\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/la-me-bell-manager-compensation-mobile,0,52255.story?track=rss|title=Bell councilman 'ashamed', 'disgusted' that Rizzo earned $1.5 million|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-08-08|accessdate=2010-08-09|first1=Jeff|last1=Gottlieb|first2=Ruben|last2=Vives}}</ref> Rizzo remained unapologetic about his salary and said, \"If that's a number people choke on, maybe I'm in the wrong business ... I could go into private business and make that kind of money. This council has compensated me for the job I've done.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/07/15/robert-rizzo-bell-city-ma_n_647826.html|title=Robert Rizzo, Bell City Manager, Makes $800k|publisher=Huffingtonpost.com|date=2010-07-15|accessdate=2010-08-17|first=Billy|last=Silverman|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719040512/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/07/15/robert-rizzo-bell-city-ma_n_647826.html|archive-date=2010-07-19|url-status=live}}</ref> Spaccia concurred, saying: \"I would have to argue you get what you pay for.\" Rizzo and Spaccia had never achieved such a salary in the private sector.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/15/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715|work=Los Angeles Times|first1=Jeff|last1=Gottlieb|first2=Ruben|last2=Vives|date=2010-07-15|title=Is A City Manager Worth $800,000?|access-date=2011-05-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517110554/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/15/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715|archive-date=2011-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn comparison, [[Los Angeles County]] Chief Executive [[William T Fujioka]] earns $338,458.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://caljobsource.com/calsalaries.html|title=California Governor and Official Salaries|publisher=Caljobsource.com|date=2008-06-10|accessdate=2010-08-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815001551/http://caljobsource.com/calsalaries.html|archive-date=2010-08-15|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[President of the United States]] earns $400,000 per year.<ref name=\"vvdailypress1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vvdailypress.com/news/hesperia-20926-hook-pension.html|title=Hesperia is on the hook for $80,000 of Rizzo's pension|publisher=Vvdailypress.com|date=2010-08-04|accessdate=2010-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927163404/http://www.vvdailypress.com/news/hesperia-20926-hook-pension.html|archive-date=2011-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref> Rizzo also received an unusually large package of benefits, including paid vacation, sick and personal time of 28 weeks off per year.<ref name=\"latimes7\"/>  In addition, both [[Rancho Cucamonga]] and [[Hesperia, California|Hesperia]] may be obligated to pay significant percentages of Rizzo's estimated $600,000 annual pension, according to ''[[Daily Press (California)|Daily Press]]'' estimates.<ref name=\"vvdailypress1\"/> Rizzo was in line to receive a pension of $880,000 annually.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/bell-city-fires-manager-paid-president-obamas-salary/story?id=11236299|title=Bell City Fires Manager Paid Twice President Obama's Salary|publisher=Abcnews.go.com|accessdate=2010-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726071658/http://abcnews.go.com/US/bell-city-fires-manager-paid-president-obamas-salary/story?id=11236299|archive-date=2010-07-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010,  Rizzo, Mayor Oscar Hernandez, former assistant city manager Angela Spaccia and council members George Mirabal, Teresa Jacobo, Luis Artiga, George Cole and Victor Bello were arrested and charged with misappropriation of public funds.<ref name=\"latimesblogs.latimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/09/bell-charges-rizzo.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Rizzo faces 53 counts; Bell was 'corruption on steroids', D.A. Cooley says [Updated]|date=2010-09-21|access-date=2010-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923154420/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/09/bell-charges-rizzo.html|archive-date=2010-09-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"http\">{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/09/bell-charges-rizzo.html|title=8 current, former Bell, California officials arrested|publisher=CNN|date=2010-09-21|accessdate=2010-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923154420/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/09/bell-charges-rizzo.html|archive-date=2010-09-23|url-status=live}}</ref> When Hernandez refused to answer the door at his home, the sheriff's department used a [[battering ram]] to break down his door and bring out the mayor in handcuffs.<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2010/09/8-former-city-officials-in-bell-calif-reported-arrested-in-salary-scandal/1|work=USA Today|title=8 former, current officials in Bell, Calif., arrested in salary scandal|date=2010-09-21|first=Douglas|last=Stanglin|access-date=2010-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923074104/http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2010/09/8-former-city-officials-in-bell-calif-reported-arrested-in-salary-scandal/1|archive-date=2010-09-23|url-status=live}}</ref> He refused to resign from his mayoral office,<ref name=\"27th\">{{cite news|last=Palmeri|first=Christopher|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-27/california-city-in-pay-probe-has-higher-property-taxes-than-beverly-hills.html|title=California City in Pay Probe Has Higher Tax Than Beverly Hills|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|date=2010-07-27|accessdate=2010-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730071710/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-27/california-city-in-pay-probe-has-higher-property-taxes-than-beverly-hills.html|archive-date=2010-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref> and was recalled in March 2011.\n\nRizzo was released from jail after [[Los Angeles County Superior Court]] Judge Mary Lou Villar determined that the funds  posted for his $2-million bail were not linked to any  of the monies he acquired in Bell. Rizzo was required to turn in his passport and wear an electronic monitoring device.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2010-10-07/justice/california.bell.corruption_1_angela-spaccia-lorenzo-velez-mayor-oscar-hernandez?_s=PM:CRIME|work=CNN|title=Attorney general expands probe of California city officials|date=2010-08-09|access-date=2010-10-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011045714/http://articles.cnn.com/2010-10-07/justice/california.bell.corruption_1_angela-spaccia-lorenzo-velez-mayor-oscar-hernandez?_s=PM:CRIME|archive-date=2010-10-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> The bail bondsmen hired on for Rizzo's $2 million bail, James Demayo and Morris Demayo, negotiated for several weeks with the prosecutor Max Huntsman on getting his bail approved. The electronic monitor was insisted by Max Huntsman.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://wavenewspapers.com/news/local/article_bc36b290-92fb-5f43-a173-a097af8856b8.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-03-26 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130412053309/http://wavenewspapers.com/news/local/article_bc36b290-92fb-5f43-a173-a097af8856b8.html |archive-date=2013-04-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSince he resigned, Rizzo has requested that the city pay his legal bills and claims the city owes him back pay. There was no such agreement made with Rizzo when he stepped down. \"He resigned without severance pay\", former councilman Velez said, adding: \"I will not even give [him] a penny cut in half.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/10/rizzo-bell-scandal.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Rizzo says Bell owes him more money and should still be paying his salary|date=2010-10-07|access-date=2010-10-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011080136/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/10/rizzo-bell-scandal.html|archive-date=2010-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nRizzo has also been ordered to stand trial in an additional conflict-of-interest charge regarding a racehorse deal with Bell's privately contracted planning director.<ref name=\"kfiam640.com\"/> Spaccia, is charged with misappropriation of public funds.<ref name=\"March10\"/> Rizzo formerly enjoyed buying horses and visiting his nearly $1 million ranch in Washington state.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/13/local/la-me-0113-lopez-20110113|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Steve|last=Lopez|date=2011-01-13|title=Robert Rizzo ordered to stand trial on new conflict of interest charges|access-date=2011-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317025231/http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/13/local/la-me-0113-lopez-20110113|archive-date=2011-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Police Chief==\nOn September 24, 2010, the Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office finally began the investigation of former Bell Police Chief Randy Adams, as part of the expanding probe of city officials. Other police included were  Adams negotiated an agreement with Rizzo when he was hired in 2009 that stipulated that he suffered from back, knee and neck injuries and that the city would support his application for a disability pension (Liz O. Baylen, ''Los Angeles Times''). Prosecutors filed suit regarding an agreement with Rizzo, Adams had himself declared disabled the day of his being hired in Bell. The disability status stands to net Adams millions of tax-free pension dollars at taxpayers\u2019 expense. Under the agreement, the 59-year-old Adams would receive a lifetime disability benefit whenever he was ready to retire, meaning he would not have to pay taxes on half of his $400,000-plus annual pension. His Bell retirement would be the third-richest in the state's huge pension system.<ref name=\"Chief\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/2010/10/28/2365935/bell-officers-say-they-have-proof.html |accessdate=October 29, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>  The state attorney filed suit against Adams and Bell following that report on his \"disability\". \"You're only supposed to receive a disability retirement if you are disabled and unable to perform the normal duties of your job,\" said California Public Employees' Retirement System spokesman Ed Fong. \"If that is not the case, it would be fraud.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/23/local/la-me-bell-adams-20100923|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Paul|last=Pringle|title=Former Bell police chief had a lucrative tax angle for retirement|date=2010-09-23|access-date=2010-09-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928191300/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/23/local/la-me-bell-adams-20100923|archive-date=2010-09-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe injuries that  Adams cited in order to collect millions of tax-free dollars from a law-enforcement disability pension did not stop him from taking rigorous spinning classes and running in a 5K race, the Glendale Downtown Dash, in 2009.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/oct/05/local/la-me-randy-adams-20101005|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Paul|last=Pringle|title=Bell Police Chief - Injury cited by ex-Bell police chief in disability pension claim didn't prevent him from exercising|date=2010-10-05|access-date=2010-10-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101018035720/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/oct/05/local/la-me-randy-adams-20101005|archive-date=2010-10-18|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/10/05/bell-police-chief-randy-a_n_750985.html |title=\"Bell Police Chief Randy Adams Ran In 5k, Rode Bikes Despite Alleged Disability\" |access-date=2010-11-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111195759/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/10/05/bell-police-chief-randy-a_n_750985.html |archive-date=2012-11-11 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nor did it stop him from stating on a 2008 application for Orange County sheriff, that he likes to ski and had been in the 120-mile Baker to Las Vegas Relay run. When Adams applied for Orange County sheriff, the year before joining Bell, he did not mention having any physical problems, said Rick Francis, chief of staff for county Supervisor John Moorlach.<ref name=\"Chief\"/> \"He was not disabled\", said [[Glendale, California|Glendale]] City Manager Jim Starbird, who was Adams' boss until he left for Bell. \"I never heard of someone being hired to work for a city and having that [disability] determination made going in.\" Glendale has joined two other cities in trying to block what has the potential to be hundreds of thousands of dollars in pension payments for Adams, whose highly profitable term as police chief of Bell has far-reaching consequences to the state's complicated employee retirement system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/glendale-seeks-to-block-pension-benefits-for-bell-police-chief.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=L.A. Now|date=2010-07-28|access-date=2010-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928025610/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/glendale-seeks-to-block-pension-benefits-for-bell-police-chief.html|archive-date=2010-09-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Adams' salary of $457,000 was roughly double that of Los Angeles Police Chief [[Charlie Beck]] who oversees almost 10,000 officers. Bell's police department numbers 48.<ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/08/bell-official-police-chief-salary-randy-adams.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=L.A. Now|date=2010-08-11|access-date=2010-11-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100919013207/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/08/bell-official-police-chief-salary-randy-adams.html|archive-date=2010-09-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, it was revealed on [[CBS]] nighttime news that Adams had allegedly exchanged e-mails with the assistant city manager on how they were going to arrange his over $400,000 salary and how to hide that fact from the citizens. The email's contents were presented in a humorous manner regarding bilking the city.  \"I am looking forward to seeing you and taking all of Bell's money\", Adams wrote, according to the memo.<ref name=\"sfgate.com\"/>\nAdams has not yet been charged or arrested. Some people in Bell have speculated that Adams hasn't been arrested because of his law-enforcement ties to District Attorney [[Steve Cooley]].<ref>[http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_16458669 \"Officers in scandal-torn Calif. city demand probe\"]</ref>\n\nSince August 2010, the city of Bell is still looking for a new police chief. Gilbert Jara, head of the Bell Police Officers Assn., called the search \"a good first step in ensuring not only public safety but also a restoration of the public\u2019s trust in Bell officials.\"<ref name=autogenerated5 /> The city of Bell has claimed that  they were negotiating with the [[Los Angeles Sheriff's Department]] to take over the policing contract, however, Sheriff [[Lee Baca]]'s spokesman says that the L.A. County Auditor-Controller Wendy L. Watanabe, has made no contact with him regarding that possibility.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.laweekly.com/informer/2010/12/bell_compton_police_department.php |title=L.A. County: \"Bell, Compton Should Not Have Own Police Departments\" |access-date=2010-12-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226181919/http://blogs.laweekly.com/informer/2010/12/bell_compton_police_department.php |archive-date=2010-12-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2011, the city hired the first Interim Chief of Police since the scandal broke.  Steve Belcher was retained as the interim chief and brought nearly 40 years of law enforcement experience.  Belcher was tasked with giving the police department a critical look and providing the new city managemenet with his police management review.  Interim Chief Belcher submitted his recommendations and served as the Interim Chief of Police for one year.\n\nIn October 2012, Bell Police Captain Anthony (Tony) Miranda was promoted to Chief of Police after a nationwide search of over 70 candidates.  The department continues on its path to recovery under Chief Miranda's direction.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.publicceo.com/2012/10/bell-announces-new-acting-police-chief/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-12-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121124123730/http://www.publicceo.com/2012/10/bell-announces-new-acting-police-chief/ |archive-date=2012-11-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, the California Public Employees Retirement System (CalPERS) Board designated as precedential its decision to reduce former City of Bell police chief Randy Adams' requested pension by more than half. The Board's decision to designate the Adams' decision as precedential means that it can be officially cited in court, in other administrative proceedings, and may be applied broadly to other cases.<ref>http://www.calpers.ca.gov/index.jsp?bc=/about/newsroom/news/city-of-bell-case-precedential.xml{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==More police caught in scandal==\nThe office that manages retirement benefits for California public employees is looking into the validity of pension plans for at least 10 police officers, including four chiefs, who received disability pensions and workers' compensation settlements when they were compelled to leave their jobs at the city of Bell. The California Public Employees Retirement System, or CalPERS, is asking Bell officials to ascertain whether Rizzo approved retirement deals that enhanced payments to those officers, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported on its website May 11, 2011.\n\n\"If Rizzo wanted to get rid of you, he'd make some way to pay you off and make it beneficial for you financially,\" said former Chief Andreas Probst, who was granted a $250,000 workers' compensation settlement and an annual disability retirement of $158,057. Probst claimed his retirement was properly handled because he had suffered on-duty injuries in a crash with a drunk driver. But he said Rizzo bundled severance, vacation and sick pay owed to him into the workers' compensation settlement - a practice that authorities said would be in violation of the tax codes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2011/may/11/disability-pensions-of-ex-bell-cops-under-scrutiny |title=\"Disability pensions of ex-Bell cops under scrutiny\" |access-date=2011-05-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108124025/http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2011/may/11/disability-pensions-of-ex-bell-cops-under-scrutiny/ |archive-date=2011-11-08 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Other city officials===\nThe city's website shows that seven more city workers received excessively high salaries, with two making more than $400,000 per year and three making more than $200,000.<ref name=Palmeri>{{cite news|title=Outrage over high salaries in Calif. town; Three city officials resign after total compensation revealed|first=Christopher|last=Palmeri|work=The Washington Post|date=July 25, 2010|page=A.3|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/24/AR2010072402548.html|access-date=September 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922043416/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/24/AR2010072402548.html|archive-date=September 22, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>  Assistant City Manager Angela Spaccia collected $376,288 a year, with a similar 12% annual pay increase, more than the top administrator for [[Los Angeles County]].<ref name=\"latimes1\"/> Bell Police Chief Adams, who oversaw a 46-person department, had an annual salary of $457,000, which is 33% higher than the [[LAPD]] police chief, [[Charlie Beck]] who oversees 12,899 employees in [[Los Angeles]] and earns $307,000.<ref name=\"people\">{{cite news|last=Knoll|first=Corina|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0716-bell-residents-20100716,0,4326515.story|title=Bell employee salary uproar: six-figure salaries in a blue-collar city|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-07-16|accessdate=2010-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812021930/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0716-bell-residents-20100716,0,4326515.story|archive-date=2010-08-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes1\">{{cite news|last=Vives|first=Ruben|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-721-bell-20100721,0,3475382.story|title=Bell council seeks resignations of 3 city officials|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-07-21|accessdate=2010-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722004835/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-721-bell-20100721%2C0%2C3475382.story|archive-date=2010-07-22|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Vives>{{cite web|url=http://www.joinlapd.com/career_ladder.html|title=Lapd - Career Ladder|publisher=Joinlapd.com|accessdate=2010-07-31|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823140559/http://www.joinlapd.com/career_ladder.html|archivedate=2011-08-23}}</ref><ref name=\"PD\">{{Cite web |url=http://californiawatch.org/watchblog/bell-police-get-big-paychecks-too-1800 |title=In tiny Bell, police officers get big paychecks, too |access-date=2010-08-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100810003305/http://www.californiawatch.org/watchblog/bell-police-get-big-paychecks-too-1800 |archive-date=2010-08-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2009, 11 officers in Bell were paid more than $10,000 in overtime. One officer billed $26,109 in overtime.<ref name=\"PD\"/>\n\nAll of the part-time city council members collected almost $100,000 a year, excepting Councilman Lorenzo Velez.  Velez, who was paid only about $8,000 a year for his service on the council, has said he  had no idea of the exorbitant salaries other officials were collecting.<ref>[http://mymotherlode.com/news/state/ap/342607/Recall-election-scheduled-for-city-of-Bell.html \"Recall election scheduled for city of Bell\"]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He has also testified that he doesn't remember participating in any of the meetings for which other council members billed the city tens of thousands of dollars.<ref name=\"abcnews1\">{{Cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=12863838 |title=\"Calif. City Official Testifies in Corruption Case |access-date=2011-02-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628214120/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=12863838 |archive-date=2011-06-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> Council members in cities similar to Bell in size make an average of $4,800 a year.<ref name=Vives/> In contrast, members of [[San Marino, California|San Marino's]] City Council take no salary at all.<ref>[http://www.ci.san-marino.ca.us/city_council.htm City of San Marino, California's City Council Page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501214309/http://www.ci.san-marino.ca.us/city_council.htm |date=2011-05-01 }}</ref> California Attorney General [[Jerry Brown]]<ref name=\"latimes4\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-council-20100723,0,4500089.story?track=rss|title=3 Bell leaders to quit in pay scandal|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-07-22|accessdate=2010-07-26|first1=Ruben|last1=Vives|first2=Jeff|last2=Gottlieb}}</ref> and L.A. prosecutors are investigating whether the current council salaries violate a state law that regulates how much council members are paid.<ref name=\"latimes5\">{{cite news|author=|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/bell-council-found-loophole-in-law-to-allow-big-salaries.html|title=Bell council members found legal loopholes to allow big salaries|publisher=Latimesblogs.latimes.com|date=2010-07-22|accessdate=2010-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725210352/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/bell-council-found-loophole-in-law-to-allow-big-salaries.html|archive-date=2010-07-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\nBell officials voted unanimously to look into legal action against city officials, political consultants or others.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/09/03/rober-rizzo-subpoenaed-in_n_705563.html |title=\"Robert Rizzo Subpoenaed in Bell probe\" |access-date=2010-10-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100909010918/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/09/03/rober-rizzo-subpoenaed-in_n_705563.html |archive-date=2010-09-09 |url-status=live }}</ref> Other city officials receiving inflated salaries. Lourdes Garcia, the city's director of administrative services, and Eric Eggena, the director of general services, were paid more than $400,000 each. Garcia has since agreed to a 61% pay cut and Eggena was fired. An unnamed third official was also let go.<ref name=\"latimes6\">{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/01/cash-strapped-bell-to-consider-disbanding-police-department-deep-cuts-to-salaries.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=L.A. Now|date=2011-01-27|access-date=2011-01-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128224001/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/01/cash-strapped-bell-to-consider-disbanding-police-department-deep-cuts-to-salaries.html|archive-date=2011-01-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nState lawmakers and investigators traveled to the city of Bell  on November 8, 2010, to probe the Los Angeles suburb's alleged corruption and governance problems. When residents were told by the state auditor that their political leaders mismanaged tens of millions of dollars of the blue-collar city's money, using it largely to pay themselves enormous salaries, they \"gasped in shock and disbelief.\"<ref name=\"ktkz\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ktkz.com/article.aspx?id=c4de5af0-20a9-4ed9-a685-5eef91fd4d85&catid=0 |title=KTKZ AM 1380: Intelligent Conservative Talk News Article |access-date=2010-11-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713173040/http://www.ktkz.com/article.aspx?id=c4de5af0-20a9-4ed9-a685-5eef91fd4d85&catid=0 |archive-date=2011-07-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> The auditors spoke at the hearing called by state Assemblyman [[Hector De La Torre]], who said he wanted to give residents of the working-class city of 36,000 \"a full accounting of what had happened\".<ref>John Rogers, Associated Press, November 9, 2010</ref>{{Citation needed|reason=\"John Rogers, Associated Press, November 9, 2010\" is NOT a complete citation.  It's doubtless better than nothing, but it's still inadequate.|date=March 2018}}\n\nThe ''[[Los Angeles Times|L.A. Times]]'' reported that in a review of state and local records it was discovered that independent audits of public agencies in California frequently failed to recognize and note cases of questionable  mismanagement and obvious fraud. The report cites [[San Diego]], [[Compton, California|Compton]] and [[South Gate, California|South Gate]] as other cities plagued by public corruption that received dubiously clean audits. \"Bell residents know their civic house is in disarray,\" said Supervisor [[Gloria Molina]]. \"There is no way order can be restored in Bell until residents there have an accurate picture of the city's finances.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-1020-bell-finances-20101020,0,4406929.story|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Ruben|last=Vives|title=City Of Bell - L.A. County auditors to examine Bell's finances|date=2010-10-20|access-date=2010-11-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101118052804/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-1020-bell-finances-20101020,0,4406929.story|archive-date=2010-11-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==BASTA==\nThe primary group organized to fight the cities corruption is the '''Bell Association to Stop the Abuse''' (BASTA); Basta means \"enough\" in [[Spanish language|Spanish]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Thomas Lifson|url=http://www.americanthinker.com/blog/2010/07/tea_party_redux_in_bell_califo.html|title=American Thinker Blog: Tea party redux in Bell, California|publisher=Americanthinker.com|accessdate=2010-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730120410/http://www.americanthinker.com/blog/2010/07/tea_party_redux_in_bell_califo.html|archive-date=2010-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref> BASTA consists of community members who are motivating the community to become educated and to learn where and how their tax dollars are spent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myfoxla.com/dpp/news/local/bell-mayor-oscar-hernandez-to-stop-taking-high-salary-20100726|title=Bell City Council, Mayor Take Big Pay Cuts|publisher=Myfoxla.com|accessdate=2010-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321171705/http://www.myfoxla.com/dpp/news/local/bell-mayor-oscar-hernandez-to-stop-taking-high-salary-20100726|archive-date=2012-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> BASTA organized a march on July 25, 2010.  Some of the marchers wore T-shirts with the words \"My city is more corrupt than your city\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myfoxla.com/dpp/news/local/bell-residents-march-for-council-resignations-20100725|title=Bell Residents to Vote on Council Resignations &#124; FOX 11 News|publisher=Myfoxla.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100731040544/http://www.myfoxla.com/dpp/news/local/bell-residents-march-for-council-resignations-20100725|archive-date=2010-07-31|accessdate=2010-08-09}}\n<!-- The link goes to a web page on which this article, or even just \"Bell\" cannot be found as of 2017-01-22. --></ref> BASTA is supported in part by the Bell Police Officers Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://basta4bell.com|title=BASTA &#124; The Bell Association to STOP the Abuse|publisher=Basta4bell.com|accessdate=2010-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100908093739/http://basta4bell.com/|archive-date=2010-09-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Police Officers Association has opposed the contracting of services of the Police Department or consolidation of police services into a joint powers authority<ref name=\"egpnews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://egpnews.com/?p=19635|title=Critics Weigh In On Bell Salary Scandal|publisher=Egpnews.com|date=2010-07-22|accessdate=2010-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006230326/http://egpnews.com/?p=19635|archive-date=2011-10-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> and has criticized the posting of salaries on the Bell City Clerk's website, calling them \"deceptive\" due to the inclusion of overtime.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://basta4bell.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/Bell_POA_press_080610.pdf |title=BASTA website |access-date=2010-08-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707213619/http://basta4bell.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/Bell_POA_press_080610.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> BASTA collected enough signatures to force the recall election in March for the four City Council members facing corruption charges. Organizers with BASTA began the recall process in August after unsuccessfully calling for the resignation of Mayor Oscar Hernandez and council members Luis Artiga, Teresa Jacobo and George Mirabal.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/09/bell-recall-organizers-claim-enough-signatures-for-vote.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Bell recall organizers claim enough signatures for vote|date=2010-09-28|access-date=2010-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101001134746/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/09/bell-recall-organizers-claim-enough-signatures-for-vote.html|archive-date=2010-10-01|url-status=live}}</ref> Artiga has since resigned.\n\n==Further Bell scandal investigations==\n===Real estate deal under investigation===\nOfficials in Bell paid more than  double the appraised value for a parcel of land that was never redeveloped. The latest scandal involves a tract of land presently leased by a carwash. ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' reported that Rizzo and former General Services Manager Eric Eggena negotiated its purchase for $1.35 million, despite its appraisal of $612,000. \"This is a real estate deal that ran amok\", said Larry Kosmont, a Los Angeles real estate consultant. \"Essentially, they cooked the books on this\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.officialwire.com/main.php?action=posted_news&rid=290588 |title=OfficialWire: \"Bell, Real Estate Deal Scrutinized\" |access-date=2011-03-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728152210/http://www.officialwire.com/main.php?action=posted_news&rid=290588 |archive-date=2011-07-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Civil Rights Violations===\nThe FBI  has begun investigating  the accusations of violating some citizens' civil rights, particularly whether Bell officials violated the civil rights of Latino residents by assertively towing targeted cars and charging residents extortionate fees to retrieve their vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0224-bell-investigation-20110224,0,1952274.story?track=rss|work=Los Angeles Times|first1=Jeff|last1=Gottlieb|first2=Robert J.|last2=Lopez|title=New search warrants served as Bell corruption probe widens|date=2011-02-24|access-date=2011-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224151200/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0224-bell-investigation-20110224,0,1952274.story?track=rss|archive-date=2011-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref> A memo titled ''Bell Police Department Baseball Game'' lists \"points\" for officers to ticket for various targeted infractions. Police officers in Bell said in interviews in August 2010 that they frequently spent their shifts pulling over vehicles for small infractions  hoping that they would be unlicensed drivers. \"Although officers didn't look exclusively for immigrants, it was clear that the majority of the drivers pulled over turned out to be illegal immigrants\", Officer Kurt Owens said. \u201cWe'd look for younger guys in their 20s and 30s, guys with junkier cars, broken lights, loud music or tinted windows\u201d, Owens added.<ref name=target>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/02/memo-suggests-bell-police-turn-ticketing-impounding-cars-into-baseball-game.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=L.A. Now|date=2011-02-28|access-date=2011-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304223846/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/02/memo-suggests-bell-police-turn-ticketing-impounding-cars-into-baseball-game.html|archive-date=2011-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBell's budget shows that the city was generating increased income from fees and taxes over several years. Bell's records show that the city made nearly a million dollars just in impound fees in fiscal year 2008-09,<ref name=\"abc\"/> which works out to be about $10 per citizen in this small town. Bell was charging $300 for unlicensed motorists to recover their cars, three times what Los Angeles County and neighboring cities charge.<ref name=target/>\"All of this was just a means by Rizzo to nickel and dime the community to death to get more money out of them\", Christina Garcia, a community activist, said.<ref name=target/>\n\n===Bell demanded extra fees from some businesses===\n\nThe ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported on November 1, 2010, that for at least a decade, officials in Bell arbitrarily required some businesses to make payments to the city totalling tens of thousands of dollars annually, and in at least one case threatening a business owner with closure if he failed to comply.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-1102-bell-fees-20101102,0,3038770,full.story|work=Los Angeles Times|first1=Paloma|last1=Esquivel|first2=Robert J.|last2=Lopez|title=Bell demanded extra fees from some businesses|date=2010-11-02|access-date=2010-11-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101103214648/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-1102-bell-fees-20101102,0,3038770,full.story|archive-date=2010-11-03|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Oregonian'' editorialized that \"Local businesses were shook down, Sopranos-style, just to stay open.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/opinion/index.ssf/2010/11/civics_lessons_from_bell_calif.html |title=\"Civics lessons from Bell, California\" |access-date=2010-11-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104013954/http://www.oregonlive.com/opinion/index.ssf/2010/11/civics_lessons_from_bell_calif.html |archive-date=2011-11-04 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===\"Breast Cancer Awareness\" funds===\nThe City of Bell raised a reported $100,000 from multi-year [[breast cancer awareness]] fundraisers. Former vice-mayor Teresa Jacobo was one of the leaders of those campaigns and the people of Bell are trying to find out where those charitable contributions went and if any funds were ever donated to breast cancer awareness organizations.<ref>[http://www.topix.com/city/bell-ca/2010/10/indicted-city-of-bell-councilwoman-teresa-jacobo-confronted-about-breast-cancer-awareness-funds \"Jacobo breast cancer fundraising investigated\"]</ref>\n\n===Property taxes===\nAn investigation into the city's property taxes found that the homeowners of Bell were paying a rate higher than those of the affluent [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]]. Homeowners in Bell pay the second-highest tax rate of any city in Los Angeles County.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themarkettraders.com/content/city-bell-california-illegally-overcharges-29-million-property-taxes|title=The City of Bell California Illegally Overcharges 2.9 Million in Property Taxes|publisher=the market traders|accessdate=2010-08-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717012327/http://www.themarkettraders.com/content/city-bell-california-illegally-overcharges-29-million-property-taxes|archive-date=2011-07-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Wendy Watanabe, Los Angeles County's auditor-controller, stated that residents of Bell pay as much as 1.55% of their home's assessed value in taxes, 34% above the norm. State Controller John Chiang said the raised rate was illegal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/aug/16/opinion/la-oe-gelinas-bell-bonds-20100816/2|title=Bell stuck in a money rut|publisher=Articles.latimes.com|date=2010-08-16|accessdate=2010-08-30|first=Nicole|last=Gelinas|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120717063854/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/aug/16/opinion/la-oe-gelinas-bell-bonds-20100816/2|archive-date=2012-07-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Wantanabe said the average for the county is 1.16%. Auditors had discovered that taxpayers were overcharged the $2.9 million for a \"retirement tax\" to fund city employee pensions.<ref name=\"sewer\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/03/local/la-me-bell-20100903|work=The Los Angeles Times|title=Bell assessed illegal sewer fees|first=Kim|last=Christensen|date=2010-09-03|access-date=2010-09-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906125338/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/03/local/la-me-bell-20100903|archive-date=2010-09-06|url-status=live}}</ref> Under California's state tax code, the nearly $3 million overpaid by Bell homeowners, should be redirected to local schools, however, on September 1, 2010, lawmakers approved AB 900 by Assemblyman Kevin De Leon (D- Los Angeles), which returns $2.9 million in property tax refunds directly to the overcharged city residents.<ref name=cons>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-legis-bell-20100901,0,2270637.story|work=Los Angeles Times|first1=Patrick|last1=McGreevy|first2=Jack|last2=Dolan|title=California legislators OK pay reforms inspired by Bell scandal|date=2010-09-01|access-date=2010-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901210038/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-legis-bell-20100901,0,2270637.story|archive-date=2010-09-01|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 13, 2010 Lieutenant Governor [[Abel Maldonado]], approved the bill.<ref name=\"abclocal1\">{{Cite web |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flos_angeles&id=7664687 |title=\"Bell homeowners await refunds from tax scam\" |access-date=2019-10-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100916075851/http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news%2Flocal%2Flos_angeles&id=7664687 |archive-date=2010-09-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Illegal sewer fees===\nThe city of Bell assessed property owners for sewer fees without getting the mandated voter approval. The ''Times'' acquired a letter to the city in which Controller John Chiang stated that property owners overpaid $621,737 in fees that were illegally increased since 2007. The extra tax added about $20 per parcel for each of the last three years\u2019 tax bills. After the salary scandal surfaced in July 2010, about a hundred residents protested at City Council meetings, saying they believed that their taxes were too high.<ref name=\"sewer\"/> Many residents said they had noticed assessments on their tax bills that they were never informed of and did not understand. ABC News announced that Bell homeowners who had overpaid their property taxes over the last three years would be refunded the funds that were collected illegally. In September 2010, Lieutenant Governor Maldonado signed [[Assembly Bill 900]], which returned $3,000,000 collected from 4,000 residents.<ref name=\"abclocal1\"/>\n\n===Auditor negligence===\nIn connection with an accusation (AC2012-17) that the [[audit]] firm [[Mayer Hoffman McCann P.C.]] (MHM) of [[Irvine, California]] \"committed repeated acts of negligence on more than one occasion in the 2009 audit of the City of Bell (Bell) and the Bell Community Redevelopment Agency (Bell CRA) that departed from professional standards\" and \"insufficiently documented its audit for Bell and the Bell CRA for the year ending June 30, 2009\" the [[California Board of Accountancy]] suspended MHM's [[Certified Public Accountant|CPA]] Corporation License for six months stayed, with two years' probation, and imposed on it an administrative penalty of $300,000, among other enforcement actions, effective June 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dca.ca.gov/cba/updates/update70.pdf |title=UPDATE, Issue No 70, Fall 2012, California Board of Accountancy, p.23 |access-date=2012-12-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114122608/http://www.dca.ca.gov/cba/updates/update70.pdf |archive-date=2012-11-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Local newspaper died as Rizzo was hired ==\n\nA local newspaper, the ''Industrial Post'', was founded in Bell in 1924.  It was renamed at least twice, becoming ''Community News'' by 1998, when it was sold.  Rizzo was hired around that time.  The ''Community News'' ceased publication shortly thereafter.  Journalist Terry Francke claimed that, \"the Bell spectacle is what happens to communities without their own old-fashioned diligent news coverage by veteran newspaper reporters, or at least smart reporters led by veteran newspaper editors.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Francke|first1=Terry|title=Why the Bell Scandal Happened and What Can Be Done|url=http://voiceofoc.org/2010/07/why-the-bell-scandal-happened-and-what-can-be-done/|accessdate=2017-01-22|publisher=Voice of OC|date=July 28, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129102638/http://voiceofoc.org/2010/07/why-the-bell-scandal-happened-and-what-can-be-done/|archive-date=January 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nU.S. Rep. [[Adam Schiff]], D-[[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]], appealed to federal prosecutors to scrutinize the widespread political corruption in Los Angeles County.  At least six other cities where officials have been recently charged with corruption include [[Irwindale]], [[La Puente]], [[Monterey Park, California|Monterey Park]], [[Pico Rivera]], [[Temple City]], and [[Vernon, California|Vernon]]. \"A much more rigorous focus is obviously merited by events\", Schiff said, citing statutes that specifically aim at scams involving  taxpayer dollars. \"Some of these cases are difficult to prosecute (at the local level) and where the U.S. Attorney does very well is chasing it down.\"   Schiff said he would like to see federal prosecutors look closely at these several cities beside Bell. \"I think they have a compelling interest ...The federal government clearly has jurisdiction in public corruption investigations\", Schiff said.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sgvtribune.com/ci_16588894?IADID=Search-www.sgvtribune.com-www.sgvtribune.com |title=Schiff calls on feds to open local corruption investigations |access-date=2010-11-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716045922/http://www.sgvtribune.com/ci_16588894?IADID=Search-www.sgvtribune.com-www.sgvtribune.com |archive-date=2011-07-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe crackdown in Bell has also received extensive coverage in the Spanish-language media and has resonated among voters in blue-collar Latino communities who often feel neglected in terms of both government services and the justice system,\" said Jaime Regalado, director of the Edmund G. \"Pat\" Brown Institute of Public Affairs at [[California State University, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Willon|first=Phil|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-politics-20100923,0,5041670.story|title=Bell crackdowns hand statewide candidates a chance to shine|publisher=latimes.com|date=2010-09-27|accessdate=2010-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100927224038/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-bell-politics-20100923,0,5041670.story|archive-date=2010-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Palm Springs Desert Sun'' maintained, in an editorial:\n<blockquote>That, in a very disturbing way, we all owe the community of Bell thanks. The elected and unelected hierarchy of that [small] city went to the extremes while its voters slept... As it is today, every California citizen has a right to ask public agencies for an accounting of their taxpayer-funded salaries and other compensation. That goes for any public employee\u2014from the city manager and council members to any teacher or librarian.<ref>Associated Press, [http://www.mercurynews.com/breaking-news/ci_15818351?nclick_check=1 \"Recent California newspaper editorials\"], ''Mercury News'', quoting the ''Palm Springs Desert Sun'' of August 15, 2010.</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Awards for expose of scandal==\n''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reporters Ruben Vives and Jeff Gottlieb were awarded the [[Selden Ring Award|Selden Ring Award for Investigative Reporting]] for the expose of the Bell salary scandal, 'Breach of Faith'. The Award, presented by the Annenberg School for Communication & Journalism, the prize is worth $35,000.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.laobserved.com/archive/2011/02/selden_ring_award_to_the.php |title=\"Selden Ring award to the LAT's Bell team\" |access-date=2011-03-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110302102634/http://www.laobserved.com/archive/2011/02/selden_ring_award_to_the.php |archive-date=2011-03-02 |url-status=live }}</ref> On April 18, 2011, it was announced that the ''[[L.A. Times]]'' had won the [[Pulitzer Prize for Public Service]] reporting on breaking the Bell scandal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/04/18/national/main20055012.shtml|work=CBS News|title=LA Times wins Pulitzer for Bell, Calif., scandal|date=2011-04-18|access-date=2011-04-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110421054028/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/04/18/national/main20055012.shtml|archive-date=2011-04-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe ''L.A. Times'' announced the winners of its in-house editorial awards May 2011. The paper's [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning Bell coverage won in the \"investigations\" category as well as the ''Publisher's Prize''. ''The Times''' publisher Eddie Hartenstein said of his paper's Bell coverage: \"Robert Rizzo and his cronies, I think, savored their windfall and knew all too well what they were doing and knew they had to keep it secret. And if anyone was bold enough to uncover it, it was some of our folks here. They went to ask the city clerks at Bell, Calif., and the response they got repeatedly was 'Those records aren't available; come back in two weeks.' But they wouldn't accept that ... [W]hen [the lid] finally came off the Bell salary scandal, it was not because of a grand jury or a conscience-stricken official or anything like that. It was because of two intrepid ''L.A. Times'' reporters.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlla/la-times-announces-winners-of-its-2010-editorial-awards_b29180 |title=''L.A. Times'' Announces Winners of its '2010 Editorial Awards' |access-date=2011-05-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104005258/http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlla/la-times-announces-winners-of-its-2010-editorial-awards_b29180 |archive-date=2011-11-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[True Detective (season 2)|''True Detective'' Season 2]] is loosely based on the events in Bell, CA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-vernon-true-detective-20150619-story.html|title='True Detective' setting based on California city with a corrupt past|last=Times|first=Los Angeles|website=latimes.com|access-date=2016-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012180223/http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-vernon-true-detective-20150619-story.html|archive-date=2016-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2011/05/arrested-bell-official-gets-his-street-art-close-up-in-downtown-la.html Robert Rizzo as street art, from the ''Los Angeles Times'']\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bell, California}}\n[[Category:Bell, California]]\n[[Category:Political scandals in California]]\n[[Category:2010 in California]]\n[[Category:2011 in California]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLatino(link changed toHispanic and Latino Americans) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/City_of_Bell_scandal"}
{"title_page": "Bita Moghaddam", "text_new": "{{short description|Iranian-American neuroscientist}}\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n{{cleanup|reason=duplicate citations, [[WP:NAMEDREFS]] is needed.|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Bita Moghaddam\n| image             = File:Bita Moghaddam 2012.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = Iran\n| nationality       = Iranian-American\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Oregon Health Sciences University\n| alma_mater        = PhD at University of Kansas, Postdoctoral work at Yale University\n| known_for         = Discovery of first non-monoamine targeting compound for treatment of schizophrenia\n| awards            = Ruth Matarazzo Professor at OHSU, Paul Jansen Award for Excellence in Schizophrenia Research, Efron Award for Excellence in Research Related to Neuropsychopharmacology, 2014 CINP Neuroscience Basic Research Award, MERIT Award from the National Institute of Mental Health\n| Institutions      = Oregon Health Sciences University\n}}\n'''Bita Moghaddam''' is an Iranian-American neuroscientist as well as a Professor of Behavioral Neuroscience and the Chair of the Department of Behavioral Neuroscience at [[Oregon Health & Science University|Oregon Health and Science University]]. Moghaddam investigates the neuronal processes underlying emotion and cognition as a first step to designing strategies to treat and prevent brain illnesses.\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\nMoghaddam grew up in [[Iran]] with her mother, father, and sister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Growing up in an environment where her parents emphasized the importance of education, Moghaddam came to learn that she could do anything as long as she put in the time and effort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\u00a0 In the late 1970\u2019s, Moghaddam moved to the [[United States]] to pursue her PhD at the [[University of Kansas]] with the intentions of returning to [[Iran]] after her education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> When Moghaddam started her graduate education, she had intentions to pursue her dissertation work in chemistry, but was inspired by one of her professors, Dr. Ralph Adams, and his innovative applications of [[analytical chemistry]] to understand brain chemistry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> After becoming fascinated by the neural processes underlying [[schizophrenia]], Moghaddam decided to pursue a PhD, and a career, in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/bita-moghaddam/|title=Bita Moghaddam \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Under the mentorship of Dr. Ralph Adams, Moghaddam could learn from a pioneer in the field how to build and apply electroanalytical tools to study schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://electroanalytical.org/Adams.html|title=Recollections - Ralph N. Adams|website=electroanalytical.org|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nDuring her PhD, Moghaddam worked on improving graphite electrodes for [[in vivo]] electrochemical experiments studying [[cationic]] primary neurotransmitters.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gerhardt|first=Greg A.|last2=Oke|first2=Arvin F.|last3=Nagy|first3=Geza|last4=Moghaddam|first4=Bita|last5=Adams|first5=Ralph N.|date=1984-01-09|title=Nafion-coated electrodes with high selectivity for CNS electrochemistry|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899384909636|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=290|issue=2|pages=390\u2013395|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(84)90963-6|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1986, Moghaddam published a first author paper in the [[Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences]] describing her improvements of the in vivo [[voltammetry]] method for applications in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=B.|last2=Adams|first2=R. N.|date=1986|title=Recent Developments of in Vivo Voltammetry: Applications to Studies of Chemical Dynamics in the Neuronal Microenvironmenta|url=https://nyaspubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1749-6632.1986.tb27142.x|journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=481|issue=1|pages=106\u2013115|doi=10.1111/j.1749-6632.1986.tb27142.x|issn=1749-6632}}</ref> Moghaddam then published another first author paper highlighting her findings, using potassium-selective microelectrodes, that extracellular potassium concentrations vary across brain regions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Adams|first2=Ralph N.|date=1987-03-17|title=Regional differences in resting extracellular potassium levels of rat brain|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899387908031|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=406|issue=1|pages=337\u2013340|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(87)90803-1|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1987, Moghaddam completed her dissertation in which she simultaneously recorded the extracellular levels of both ions and neurotransmitters in the mammalian brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elibrary.ru/item.asp?id=7530811|title=SIMULTANEOUS MONITORING OF EXTRACELLULAR ION AND NEUROTRANSMITTER LEVELS IN MAMMALIAN BRAIN.|website=www.elibrary.ru|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> After her PhD, Moghaddam pursued her postdoctoral training at [[Yale University]] in New Haven, Connecticut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbrfoundation.org/about/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita Moghaddam, Ph.D.|date=2017-04-24|website=Brain & Behavior Research Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Yale, Moghaddam worked under the mentorship of Dr. Benjamin Bunney in the Department of Psychiatry exploring the modulatory effects of dopaminergic signalling in the striatum.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benhamin S.|date=1989|title=Differential effect of cocaine on extracellular dopamine levels in rat medial prefrontal cortex and nucleus accumbens: Comparison to amphetamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/syn.890040209|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=156\u2013161|doi=10.1002/syn.890040209|issn=1098-2396}}</ref>\u00a0Moghaddam published 6 first author papers during her 3 year postdoctoral studies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=EX5b5sUAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&sortby=pubdate|title=Bita Moghaddam - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Moghaddem used the technique of in vivo [[microdialysis]] to look at the composition of extracellular [[dopamine]] in the rodent brain in various experimental preparations. She first discovered that the [[cocaine]] administration in rodents induced a higher magnitude increase in extracellular dopamine in the Nucleus Accumbens compared to the Medial Prefrontal Cortex.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benhamin S.|date=1989|title=Differential effect of cocaine on extracellular dopamine levels in rat medial prefrontal cortex and nucleus accumbens: Comparison to amphetamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/syn.890040209|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=156\u2013161|doi=10.1002/syn.890040209|issn=1098-2396}}</ref> In the [[Journal of Neurochemistry]], she then reported the effects of perfusing solution on extracellular [[dopamine]] levels and the downstream effects this has on dopaminergic brain systems.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benjamin S.|date=1989|title=Ionic Composition of Microdialysis Perfusing Solution Alters the Pharmacological Responsiveness and Basal Outflow of Striatal Dopamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.1989.tb07383.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=53|issue=2|pages=652\u2013654|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.1989.tb07383.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref> Just before she began her faculty position at Yale, Moghaddam published another first author paper in the [[Journal of Neurochemistry]] reporting that administration of different antipsychotic drugs to rats has distinct effects on the release of dopamine in the Prefrontal Cortex, Nucleus Accumbens and the Striatum.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benjamin S.|date=1990|title=Acute Effects of Typical and Atypical Antipsychotic Drugs on the Release of Dopamine from Prefrontal Cortex, Nucleus Accumbens, and Striatum of the Rat: An In Vivo Microdialysis Study|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.1990.tb01230.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=54|issue=5|pages=1755\u20131760|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.1990.tb01230.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref>\n\n== Career and Research ==\nIn 1990, Moghaddam started her first faculty position at [[Yale University]] in the Department of Psychiatry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbrfoundation.org/about/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita Moghaddam, Ph.D.|date=2017-04-24|website=Brain & Behavior Research Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> She quickly rose to a full faculty position at Yale as she set up her lab to explore the neurobiology of midbrain dopamine neurons and prefrontal cortical subregions, key brain systems implicated in schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moghaddamlab.org/about-the-lab/|title=About the Lab \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In a study published in Psychiatry in 1991, the Moghaddam Lab reported that Ventral Tegmental Area dopamine neurons are activated both before stimulus onset, signifying an internal state of anticipation, in addition to firing in response to rewarding post-stimulus outcomes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Totah|first=Nelson K. B.|last2=Kim|first2=Yunbok|last3=Moghaddam|first3=Bita|date=2013-07-01|title=Distinct prestimulus and poststimulus activation of VTA neurons correlates with stimulus detection|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3727034/|journal=Journal of Neurophysiology|volume=110|issue=1|pages=75\u201385|doi=10.1152/jn.00784.2012|issn=0022-3077|pmc=3727034|pmid=23554430}}</ref> Moghaddam continued to collaborate with her postdoctoral mentor and others at Yale to explore the effects of typical schizophrenia medications on brain chemistry in vivo.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Daly|first=Darron A.|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Bita|date=1993-04-02|title=Actions of clozapine and haloperidol on the extracellular levels of excitatory amino acids in the prefrontal cortex and striatum of conscious rats|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304394093904832|journal=Neuroscience Letters|language=en|volume=152|issue=1|pages=61\u201364|doi=10.1016/0304-3940(93)90483-2|issn=0304-3940}}</ref>\n\nAs a young professor at Yale, Moghaddam started to hone in on the potential that aberrant glutamate signalling might be a large contributing factor to the pathology of Schizophrenia, so she began to explore glutamate regulation and modulatory effects of glutamate in the brain regions associated with schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In 1994, Moghaddam found that stress-induced dopamine release is controlled by local activation of [[ionotropic glutamate receptor]]s ([[AMPA receptor|AMPA]] receptors and [[Kainate receptor|kainate]] receptors).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jedema|first=H. P.|last2=Moghaddam|first2=B.|date=August 1994|title=Glutamatergic control of dopamine release during stress in the rat prefrontal cortex|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7518503|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|volume=63|issue=2|pages=785\u2013788|doi=10.1046/j.1471-4159.1994.63020785.x|issn=0022-3042|pmid=7518503}}</ref> A few years later, she found that [[Metabotropic glutamate receptor 5|metabotropic glutamate receptors]] regulate dopamine release in the striatum, adding to the understanding of the diverse interactions between glutamate and dopaminergic system in the brain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Verma|first=Anita|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Bita|date=1998|title=Regulation of striatal dopamine release by metabotropic glutamate receptors|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/%28SICI%291098-2396%28199803%2928%3A3%3C220%3A%3AAID-SYN5%3E3.0.CO%3B2-C|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=28|issue=3|pages=220\u2013226|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1098-2396(199803)28:33.0.CO;2-C|issn=1098-2396}}</ref> She also made a novel finding regarding the regulation of glutamate release during times of stress, such that glucocorticoids, released as a result of HPA axis activation, inhibit the stress-induced output of glutamate in the prefrontal cortex.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bolinao|first2=Maria L.|last3=Stein-Behrens|first3=Becky|last4=Sapolsky|first4=Robert|date=1994-08-29|title=Glucocortcoids mediate the stress-induced extracellular accumulation of glutamate|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899394916225|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=655|issue=1|pages=251\u2013254|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(94)91622-5|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1999, Moghaddam and her colleagues tested the compound LY354740, a metabotropic glutamate receptor agonist, which they found to suppress aberrant glutamate release, reduced behavioral disruptions in animals given PCP, and overall have less side effects than typical benzodiazepines used to treat certain symptoms of schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> These findings suggested that LY354740 could potentially be used to treat psychiatric and neurological disorders characterized by aberrant glutamate transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1999-11564-001|title=APA PsycNet|website=psycnet.apa.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Moghaddam was recruited to the University of Pittsburgh, and was the first faculty member to be recruited straight to full professorship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Pitt, Moghaddam took on more teaching roles than she had previously at Yale, and she became a critical mentor to many young undergraduate students hoping to pursue opportunities in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Pitt, Moghaddam made many contributions to the field of neuroscience by continuing to probe how modulation of glutamate signalling affects behavior and neural circuit function in models for anxiety and schizophrenia. She then expanded her laboratory focus to understanding [[glutamatergic]] interactions and dopaminergic systems in adolescence since many of the symptoms of psychiatric conditions emerge during adolescence and targeting aberrant functions during this developmental period will be essential to preventing onset of disease in adulthood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Moghaddam joined the faculty at the Oregon Health Sciences University where she is the Chair of the Department of Behavioral Neuroscience as well as the Ruth Matarazzo Professor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.osu.edu/events/bn-area-presents-bita-moghaddam-ph.d.|title=The BN Area Presents: Bita Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.osu.edu|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Moghaddam continues to probe the brain mechanisms involved in cognition and emotion in brain areas implicated in schizophrenia, anxiety, ADHD, and addiction, while also performing leaderships roles to oversee long-term planning and enhance collaboration within the OHSU behavioral neuroscience department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In addition to her laboratory and departmental efforts, Moghaddam brings extensive teaching experience from her time at Pitt and participates in a large array of outreach efforts and initiatives to promote women in science and young students to pursue careers in science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nwnoggin.org/2018/05/26/diet-vs-brain/|title=Diet vs. Brain \u2013 NW NOGGIN: Neuroscience outreach group (growing in networks)|last=Griesar|first=Bill|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* Ruth Matarazzo Professor at OHSU<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.osu.edu/events/bn-area-presents-bita-moghaddam-ph.d.|title=The BN Area Presents: Bita Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.osu.edu|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Paul Jansen Award for Excellence in Schizophrenia Research<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Efron Award for Excellence in Research Related to Neuropsychopharmacology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acnp.org/annual-meeting/honorific-grants/daniel-h-efron-research-previous-award-winners/|title=Daniel H. Efron Research Previous Award Winners|website=ACNP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* 2014 CINP Neuroscience Basic Research Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* MERIT award from the National Institute of Mental Health<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Select Publications ==\n\n* Del Arco, A., Park, J., Wood, J., Kim, Y., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Adaptive encoding of outcome prediction by prefrontal cortex ensembles supports behavioral flexibility. Journal of Neuroscience, 0450-17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Bueno-Junior, L.S., Simon, N.W., Wegener, M.A., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Repeated Nicotine Strengthens Gamma Oscillations in the Prefrontal Cortex and Improves Visual Attention\u00a0 Neuropsychopharmacology 42 (8), 1590-1598.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Park, J., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Impact of anxiety on prefrontal cortex encoding of cognitive flexibility. Neuroscience 345, 193-202.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Park, J., Wood, J., Bondi, C., Del Arco, A., and Moghaddam, B. (2016) Anxiety evokes hypofrontality and disrupts rule-relevant encoding by dorsomedial prefrontal cortex neurons. Journal of Neuroscience, 36(11): 3322-3335.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Lohani, S., Poplawsky, A.J., Kim, S.G., and Moghaddam, B. (2017) Unexpected global impact of VTA dopamine neuron activati on as measured by opto-fMRI. Molecular Psychiatry, doi:10.1038/mp.2016.102.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Kim, Y., Simon, N.W., Wood, J., and Moghaddam, B. (2015). Reward anticipation is encoded differently by adolescent VTA neurons. Biological Psychiatry, 79(11):878-86.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. and Gur, R.E. (2015). Women at the Podium: ACNP Strives to Reach Speaker Gender Equality at the Annual Meeting. Neuropsychopharmacology, 41(4):929-31.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Sturman, D.A., Moghaddam, B. (2012) The striatum processes reward differently in adolescents versus adults. Proceedings of the National Academy of Science, 109(5): 1719-24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Darrah, J., Stefani, M.R., Moghaddam, B. (2008) Interaction of n-methyl-d-aspartate (NMDA) and group 5 metabotropic glutamate (mGlu5) receptors on behavioral flexibility using a novel operant set-shift paradigm. Behavioral Pharmacology, 19:225-234.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. (2004) Targetting metabotropic glutamate receptors for treatment of cognitive symptoms of schizophrenia. Psychopharmacology, 174:39-44.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. (2002) Stress activation of glutamate neurotransmission in the prefrontal cortex: Implications for dopamine-associated psychiatric disorders. Biological Psychiatry, 51:775-787.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. (1993) Stress preferentially activates extraneuronal levels of excitatory amino acids in the prefrontal cortex: A comparison to hippocampus and basal ganglia. Journal of Neurochemistry, 60:1650-1657.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B., Roth, R.H., Bunney, B.S. (1990) Characterization of dopamine release in the rat prefrontal cortex as assessed by in vivo microdialysis: Comparison to the striatum. Neuroscience, 36:669-676.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B., Adams, R.N. (1987) Regional differences in resting extracellular potassium levels of rat brain. Brain Research, 406:337-340.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B., Schenk, J.O., Stewart, W.B., Hansen, A.J. (1987) Temporal relationship between neurotransmitter release and ion flux during spreading depression and anoxia. Canadian Journal of Physiology and Pharmacology, 65:1105-1110.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Media Coverage ==\n\n* Huffington Post, 22 March 2016, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/anxiety-bad-decisions_us_56eb2012e4b09bf44a9cd3ba \u201cAnxiety Could Be The Reason You Made A Bad Decision.\u201d] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/anxiety-bad-decisions_n_56eb2012e4b09bf44a9cd3ba|title=Anxiety Could Be The Reason You Made A Bad Decision|last=Gregoire|first=Carolyn|date=2016-03-22|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Psychology Today, 17 March 2016, \u201c[https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-athletes-way/201603/how-does-anxiety-short-circuit-the-decision-making-process How Does Anxiety Short Circuit the Decision-Making Process]?\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-athletes-way/201603/how-does-anxiety-short-circuit-the-decision-making-process|title=How Does Anxiety Short Circuit the Decision-Making Process?|website=Psychology Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Forbes, 29 October 2012, \u201c[http://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/10/29/new-study-shows-that-omega-3-supplements-can-boost-memory-in-young-adults/ New Study Shows that Omega-3 Supplements Can Boost Memory in Young Adults].\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/10/29/new-study-shows-that-omega-3-supplements-can-boost-memory-in-young-adults/|title=New Study Shows that Omega-3 Supplements Can Boost Memory in Young Adults|last=DiSalvo|first=David|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* March 2016, \u201c[http://www.nature.com/multimedia/podcast/npp/npp_03212016.mp3 Women at the Podium: ACNP Strives to Reach Speaker Gender Equality at the Annual Meeting].\u201d \n* SfN's first-ever podcast on \"[http://neuronline.sfn.org/podcast The Perils of Publishing]\"\n\n== Personal life ==\nMoghaddam\u2019s father was a judge in western Iran and her mother attended college and was from Tehran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== References  ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Iranian-American neuroscientist}}\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n{{cleanup|reason=duplicate citations, WP:NAMEDREFS is needed.|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Bita Moghaddam\n| image             = File:Bita Moghaddam 2012.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = Iran\n| nationality       = Iranian-American\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Oregon Health Sciences University\n| alma_mater        = PhD at University of Kansas, Postdoctoral work at Yale University\n| known_for         = Discovery of first non-monoamine targeting compound for treatment of schizophrenia\n| awards            = Ruth Matarazzo Professor at OHSU, Paul Jansen Award for Excellence in Schizophrenia Research, Efron Award for Excellence in Research Related to Neuropsychopharmacology, 2014 CINP Neuroscience Basic Research Award, MERIT Award from the National Institute of Mental Health\n| Institutions      = Oregon Health Sciences University\n}}\n'''Bita Moghaddam''' is an Iranian-American neuroscientist as well as a Professor of Behavioral Neuroscience and the Chair of the Department of Behavioral Neuroscience at [[Oregon Health & Science University|Oregon Health and Science University]]. Moghaddam investigates the neuronal processes underlying emotion and cognition as a first step to designing strategies to treat and prevent brain illnesses.\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\nMoghaddam grew up in [[Iran]] with her mother, father, and sister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Growing up in an environment where her parents emphasized the importance of education, Moghaddam came to learn that she could do anything as long as she put in the time and effort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\u00a0 In the late 1970\u2019s, Moghaddam moved to the [[United States]] to pursue her PhD at the [[University of Kansas]] with the intentions of returning to [[Iran]] after her education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> When Moghaddam started her graduate education, she had intentions to pursue her dissertation work in chemistry, but was inspired by one of her professors, Dr. Ralph Adams, and his innovative applications of [[analytical chemistry]] to understand brain chemistry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> After becoming fascinated by the neural processes underlying [[schizophrenia]], Moghaddam decided to pursue a PhD, and a career, in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/bita-moghaddam/|title=Bita Moghaddam \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Under the mentorship of Dr. Ralph Adams, Moghaddam could learn from a pioneer in the field how to build and apply electroanalytical tools to study schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://electroanalytical.org/Adams.html|title=Recollections - Ralph N. Adams|website=electroanalytical.org|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nDuring her PhD, Moghaddam worked on improving graphite electrodes for [[in vivo]] electrochemical experiments studying [[cationic]] primary neurotransmitters.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gerhardt|first=Greg A.|last2=Oke|first2=Arvin F.|last3=Nagy|first3=Geza|last4=Moghaddam|first4=Bita|last5=Adams|first5=Ralph N.|date=1984-01-09|title=Nafion-coated electrodes with high selectivity for CNS electrochemistry|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899384909636|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=290|issue=2|pages=390\u2013395|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(84)90963-6|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1986, Moghaddam published a first author paper in the [[Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences]] describing her improvements of the in vivo [[voltammetry]] method for applications in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=B.|last2=Adams|first2=R. N.|date=1986|title=Recent Developments of in Vivo Voltammetry: Applications to Studies of Chemical Dynamics in the Neuronal Microenvironmenta|url=https://nyaspubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1749-6632.1986.tb27142.x|journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=481|issue=1|pages=106\u2013115|doi=10.1111/j.1749-6632.1986.tb27142.x|issn=1749-6632}}</ref> Moghaddam then published another first author paper highlighting her findings, using potassium-selective microelectrodes, that extracellular potassium concentrations vary across brain regions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Adams|first2=Ralph N.|date=1987-03-17|title=Regional differences in resting extracellular potassium levels of rat brain|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899387908031|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=406|issue=1|pages=337\u2013340|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(87)90803-1|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1987, Moghaddam completed her dissertation in which she simultaneously recorded the extracellular levels of both ions and neurotransmitters in the mammalian brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elibrary.ru/item.asp?id=7530811|title=SIMULTANEOUS MONITORING OF EXTRACELLULAR ION AND NEUROTRANSMITTER LEVELS IN MAMMALIAN BRAIN.|website=www.elibrary.ru|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> After her PhD, Moghaddam pursued her postdoctoral training at [[Yale University]] in New Haven, Connecticut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbrfoundation.org/about/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita Moghaddam, Ph.D.|date=2017-04-24|website=Brain & Behavior Research Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Yale, Moghaddam worked under the mentorship of Dr. Benjamin Bunney in the Department of Psychiatry exploring the modulatory effects of dopaminergic signalling in the striatum.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benhamin S.|date=1989|title=Differential effect of cocaine on extracellular dopamine levels in rat medial prefrontal cortex and nucleus accumbens: Comparison to amphetamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/syn.890040209|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=156\u2013161|doi=10.1002/syn.890040209|issn=1098-2396}}</ref>\u00a0Moghaddam published 6 first author papers during her 3 year postdoctoral studies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=EX5b5sUAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&sortby=pubdate|title=Bita Moghaddam - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Moghaddem used the technique of in vivo [[microdialysis]] to look at the composition of extracellular [[dopamine]] in the rodent brain in various experimental preparations. She first discovered that the [[cocaine]] administration in rodents induced a higher magnitude increase in extracellular dopamine in the Nucleus Accumbens compared to the Medial Prefrontal Cortex.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benhamin S.|date=1989|title=Differential effect of cocaine on extracellular dopamine levels in rat medial prefrontal cortex and nucleus accumbens: Comparison to amphetamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/syn.890040209|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=156\u2013161|doi=10.1002/syn.890040209|issn=1098-2396}}</ref> In the [[Journal of Neurochemistry]], she then reported the effects of perfusing solution on extracellular [[dopamine]] levels and the downstream effects this has on dopaminergic brain systems.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benjamin S.|date=1989|title=Ionic Composition of Microdialysis Perfusing Solution Alters the Pharmacological Responsiveness and Basal Outflow of Striatal Dopamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.1989.tb07383.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=53|issue=2|pages=652\u2013654|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.1989.tb07383.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref> Just before she began her faculty position at Yale, Moghaddam published another first author paper in the [[Journal of Neurochemistry]] reporting that administration of different antipsychotic drugs to rats has distinct effects on the release of dopamine in the Prefrontal Cortex, Nucleus Accumbens and the Striatum.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benjamin S.|date=1990|title=Acute Effects of Typical and Atypical Antipsychotic Drugs on the Release of Dopamine from Prefrontal Cortex, Nucleus Accumbens, and Striatum of the Rat: An In Vivo Microdialysis Study|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.1990.tb01230.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=54|issue=5|pages=1755\u20131760|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.1990.tb01230.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref>\n\n== Career and Research ==\nIn 1990, Moghaddam started her first faculty position at [[Yale University]] in the Department of Psychiatry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbrfoundation.org/about/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita Moghaddam, Ph.D.|date=2017-04-24|website=Brain & Behavior Research Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> She quickly rose to a full faculty position at Yale as she set up her lab to explore the neurobiology of midbrain dopamine neurons and prefrontal cortical subregions, key brain systems implicated in schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moghaddamlab.org/about-the-lab/|title=About the Lab \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In a study published in Psychiatry in 1991, the Moghaddam Lab reported that Ventral Tegmental Area dopamine neurons are activated both before stimulus onset, signifying an internal state of anticipation, in addition to firing in response to rewarding post-stimulus outcomes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Totah|first=Nelson K. B.|last2=Kim|first2=Yunbok|last3=Moghaddam|first3=Bita|date=2013-07-01|title=Distinct prestimulus and poststimulus activation of VTA neurons correlates with stimulus detection|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3727034/|journal=Journal of Neurophysiology|volume=110|issue=1|pages=75\u201385|doi=10.1152/jn.00784.2012|issn=0022-3077|pmc=3727034|pmid=23554430}}</ref> Moghaddam continued to collaborate with her postdoctoral mentor and others at Yale to explore the effects of typical schizophrenia medications on brain chemistry in vivo.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Daly|first=Darron A.|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Bita|date=1993-04-02|title=Actions of clozapine and haloperidol on the extracellular levels of excitatory amino acids in the prefrontal cortex and striatum of conscious rats|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304394093904832|journal=Neuroscience Letters|language=en|volume=152|issue=1|pages=61\u201364|doi=10.1016/0304-3940(93)90483-2|issn=0304-3940}}</ref>\n\nAs a young professor at Yale, Moghaddam started to hone in on the potential that aberrant glutamate signalling might be a large contributing factor to the pathology of Schizophrenia, so she began to explore glutamate regulation and modulatory effects of glutamate in the brain regions associated with schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In 1994, Moghaddam found that stress-induced dopamine release is controlled by local activation of [[ionotropic glutamate receptor]]s ([[AMPA receptor|AMPA]] receptors and [[Kainate receptor|kainate]] receptors).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jedema|first=H. P.|last2=Moghaddam|first2=B.|date=August 1994|title=Glutamatergic control of dopamine release during stress in the rat prefrontal cortex|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7518503|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|volume=63|issue=2|pages=785\u2013788|doi=10.1046/j.1471-4159.1994.63020785.x|issn=0022-3042|pmid=7518503}}</ref> A few years later, she found that [[Metabotropic glutamate receptor 5|metabotropic glutamate receptors]] regulate dopamine release in the striatum, adding to the understanding of the diverse interactions between glutamate and dopaminergic system in the brain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Verma|first=Anita|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Bita|date=1998|title=Regulation of striatal dopamine release by metabotropic glutamate receptors|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/%28SICI%291098-2396%28199803%2928%3A3%3C220%3A%3AAID-SYN5%3E3.0.CO%3B2-C|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=28|issue=3|pages=220\u2013226|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1098-2396(199803)28:33.0.CO;2-C|issn=1098-2396}}</ref> She also made a novel finding regarding the regulation of glutamate release during times of stress, such that glucocorticoids, released as a result of HPA axis activation, inhibit the stress-induced output of glutamate in the prefrontal cortex.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bolinao|first2=Maria L.|last3=Stein-Behrens|first3=Becky|last4=Sapolsky|first4=Robert|date=1994-08-29|title=Glucocortcoids mediate the stress-induced extracellular accumulation of glutamate|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899394916225|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=655|issue=1|pages=251\u2013254|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(94)91622-5|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1999, Moghaddam and her colleagues tested the compound LY354740, a metabotropic glutamate receptor agonist, which they found to suppress aberrant glutamate release, reduced behavioral disruptions in animals given PCP, and overall have less side effects than typical benzodiazepines used to treat certain symptoms of schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> These findings suggested that LY354740 could potentially be used to treat psychiatric and neurological disorders characterized by aberrant glutamate transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1999-11564-001|title=APA PsycNet|website=psycnet.apa.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Moghaddam was recruited to the University of Pittsburgh, and was the first faculty member to be recruited straight to full professorship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Pitt, Moghaddam took on more teaching roles than she had previously at Yale, and she became a critical mentor to many young undergraduate students hoping to pursue opportunities in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Pitt, Moghaddam made many contributions to the field of neuroscience by continuing to probe how modulation of glutamate signalling affects behavior and neural circuit function in models for anxiety and schizophrenia. She then expanded her laboratory focus to understanding [[glutamatergic]] interactions and dopaminergic systems in adolescence since many of the symptoms of psychiatric conditions emerge during adolescence and targeting aberrant functions during this developmental period will be essential to preventing onset of disease in adulthood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Moghaddam joined the faculty at the Oregon Health Sciences University where she is the Chair of the Department of Behavioral Neuroscience as well as the Ruth Matarazzo Professor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.osu.edu/events/bn-area-presents-bita-moghaddam-ph.d.|title=The BN Area Presents: Bita Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.osu.edu|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Moghaddam continues to probe the brain mechanisms involved in cognition and emotion in brain areas implicated in schizophrenia, anxiety, ADHD, and addiction, while also performing leaderships roles to oversee long-term planning and enhance collaboration within the OHSU behavioral neuroscience department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In addition to her laboratory and departmental efforts, Moghaddam brings extensive teaching experience from her time at Pitt and participates in a large array of outreach efforts and initiatives to promote women in science and young students to pursue careers in science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nwnoggin.org/2018/05/26/diet-vs-brain/|title=Diet vs. Brain \u2013 NW NOGGIN: Neuroscience outreach group (growing in networks)|last=Griesar|first=Bill|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* Ruth Matarazzo Professor at OHSU<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.osu.edu/events/bn-area-presents-bita-moghaddam-ph.d.|title=The BN Area Presents: Bita Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.osu.edu|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Paul Jansen Award for Excellence in Schizophrenia Research<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Efron Award for Excellence in Research Related to Neuropsychopharmacology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acnp.org/annual-meeting/honorific-grants/daniel-h-efron-research-previous-award-winners/|title=Daniel H. Efron Research Previous Award Winners|website=ACNP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* 2014 CINP Neuroscience Basic Research Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* MERIT award from the National Institute of Mental Health<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Select Publications ==\n\n* Del Arco, A., Park, J., Wood, J., Kim, Y., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Adaptive encoding of outcome prediction by prefrontal cortex ensembles supports behavioral flexibility. Journal of Neuroscience, 0450-17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Bueno-Junior, L.S., Simon, N.W., Wegener, M.A., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Repeated Nicotine Strengthens Gamma Oscillations in the Prefrontal Cortex and Improves Visual Attention\u00a0 Neuropsychopharmacology 42 (8), 1590-1598.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Park, J., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Impact of anxiety on prefrontal cortex encoding of cognitive flexibility. Neuroscience 345, 193-202.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Park, J., Wood, J., Bondi, C., Del Arco, A., and Moghaddam, B. (2016) Anxiety evokes hypofrontality and disrupts rule-relevant encoding by dorsomedial prefrontal cortex neurons. Journal of Neuroscience, 36(11): 3322-3335.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Lohani, S., Poplawsky, A.J., Kim, S.G., and Moghaddam, B. (2017) Unexpected global impact of VTA dopamine neuron activati on as measured by opto-fMRI. Molecular Psychiatry, doi:10.1038/mp.2016.102.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Kim, Y., Simon, N.W., Wood, J., and Moghaddam, B. (2015). Reward anticipation is encoded differently by adolescent VTA neurons. Biological Psychiatry, 79(11):878-86.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. and Gur, R.E. (2015). Women at the Podium: ACNP Strives to Reach Speaker Gender Equality at the Annual Meeting. Neuropsychopharmacology, 41(4):929-31.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Sturman, D.A., Moghaddam, B. (2012) The striatum processes reward differently in adolescents versus adults. Proceedings of the National Academy of Science, 109(5): 1719-24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Darrah, J., Stefani, M.R., Moghaddam, B. (2008) Interaction of n-methyl-d-aspartate (NMDA) and group 5 metabotropic glutamate (mGlu5) receptors on behavioral flexibility using a novel operant set-shift paradigm. Behavioral Pharmacology, 19:225-234.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. (2004) Targetting metabotropic glutamate receptors for treatment of cognitive symptoms of schizophrenia. Psychopharmacology, 174:39-44.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. (2002) Stress activation of glutamate neurotransmission in the prefrontal cortex: Implications for dopamine-associated psychiatric disorders. Biological Psychiatry, 51:775-787.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. (1993) Stress preferentially activates extraneuronal levels of excitatory amino acids in the prefrontal cortex: A comparison to hippocampus and basal ganglia. Journal of Neurochemistry, 60:1650-1657.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B., Roth, R.H., Bunney, B.S. (1990) Characterization of dopamine release in the rat prefrontal cortex as assessed by in vivo microdialysis: Comparison to the striatum. Neuroscience, 36:669-676.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B., Adams, R.N. (1987) Regional differences in resting extracellular potassium levels of rat brain. Brain Research, 406:337-340.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B., Schenk, J.O., Stewart, W.B., Hansen, A.J. (1987) Temporal relationship between neurotransmitter release and ion flux during spreading depression and anoxia. Canadian Journal of Physiology and Pharmacology, 65:1105-1110.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Media Coverage ==\n\n* Huffington Post, 22 March 2016, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/anxiety-bad-decisions_us_56eb2012e4b09bf44a9cd3ba \u201cAnxiety Could Be The Reason You Made A Bad Decision.\u201d] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/anxiety-bad-decisions_n_56eb2012e4b09bf44a9cd3ba|title=Anxiety Could Be The Reason You Made A Bad Decision|last=Gregoire|first=Carolyn|date=2016-03-22|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Psychology Today, 17 March 2016, \u201c[https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-athletes-way/201603/how-does-anxiety-short-circuit-the-decision-making-process How Does Anxiety Short Circuit the Decision-Making Process]?\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-athletes-way/201603/how-does-anxiety-short-circuit-the-decision-making-process|title=How Does Anxiety Short Circuit the Decision-Making Process?|website=Psychology Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Forbes, 29 October 2012, \u201c[http://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/10/29/new-study-shows-that-omega-3-supplements-can-boost-memory-in-young-adults/ New Study Shows that Omega-3 Supplements Can Boost Memory in Young Adults].\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/10/29/new-study-shows-that-omega-3-supplements-can-boost-memory-in-young-adults/|title=New Study Shows that Omega-3 Supplements Can Boost Memory in Young Adults|last=DiSalvo|first=David|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* March 2016, \u201c[http://www.nature.com/multimedia/podcast/npp/npp_03212016.mp3 Women at the Podium: ACNP Strives to Reach Speaker Gender Equality at the Annual Meeting].\u201d \n* SfN's first-ever podcast on \"[http://neuronline.sfn.org/podcast The Perils of Publishing]\"\n\n== Personal life ==\nMoghaddam\u2019s father was a judge in western Iran and her mother attended college and was from Tehran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== References  ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Kj cheetham", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bita_Moghaddam"}
{"title_page": "Latino punk", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=October 2013}}\n[[File:LEBatLolla2.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Le Butcherettes]], a Mexican punk band, performing at Lollapalooza 2011 in Chicago, Illinois]]\n'''Latino punk''' is [[punk music]] created by [[Latin Americans|Latino people]] in [[Latin America]] and the [[United States]].\n\nThe angst and protest qualities of punk music and style have had a strong appeal to Latino youth in the U.S., and to the people in [[Latin America]]. It is impossible to pinpoint the exact location or moment when Latinos began engaging in the punk subculture. However, Latin American rock began showing aspects of punk music during the mid-1960s with the Peruvian band [[Los Saicos]]; this band reflected many aspects of other [[proto-punk]] bands such as [[the Yardbirds]]. The Saicos were predecessors to some of the most influential [[proto-punk]] bands in the U.S., such as [[New York Dolls]], [[MC5]], and [[The Stooges]]<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://noisey.vice.com/noisey-specials/was-punk-rock-born-in-peru|title=Was punk rock born in Peru? |author=vice.com|accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref> [[Johnny Thunders]] (John Anthony Genzale, Jr) of the seminal [[New York Dolls]], who also played with [[The Heartbreakers]] and the [[Waldos]], was of Latino descent and very clearly played Latin-influenced scales on some of his tracks (e.g. ''King of the Gypsies'').\n\nPunk music began engaging a wider variety of artists and audience in the late 1970s and 1980s, either in Latin America or in the U.S. By the mid-1970s, the aesthetics promoted by [[glam rock]] in the United Kingdom had created a social gap between the audience and the artist. The punk scene that began to sprout during that era shared more commonalities with the youth audience, while still retaining some attributes from glam rock.\n\nPunk music presented itself as the voice for white teenage angst, without the arrogance and verbosity of glam rock. The punk genre rooted itself in a music and style that created by the working class without the intellectual posturing of its previous genres. It was a genre created by and for the white working class in the United Kingdom. During the late 1970s, punk's social basis for creating commonalities with its fans, and its integration of style and instruments from reggae allowed for punk bands of different ethnicities to integrate themselves into the social scene in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hebdige |first=Dick |chapter=Bleached Roots: Punks and White Ethnicity |title=Subculture, the Meaning of Style |location=London |publisher=Methuen |year=1979 |pages=62\u201372}}</ref>\n\n== Chicano/Latino Punk ==\n\nIn the late 1970s, many punk bands began appearing in Los Angeles, among them many Latino and Chicano punks like [[The Plugz]], [[Bags (Los Angeles band)|The Bags]], [[The Zeros (American band)|The Zeros]], [[Los Illegals]], Los Angelinos, Odd Squad, Felix and the Katz, the [[The Stains (LA band)|Stains]], and [[The Brat (punk band)|The Brat]]. Most of these bands did not consider themselves Latino punk bands, but artists challenging the mainstream just like their non-Latino peers.\n\nHowever, in the late 1970s Latino/Chicano punks in East L.A began organizing gigs in their own communities. These bands were part of a punk movement called The East Side Renaissance, who dedicated themselves to bringing to light the local Chicano/Latino bands in their own neighborhoods.<ref name=\"MasAlla\">{{cite video |title=Mas Alla De Los Gritos (Beyond the Screams) |author=Martin Sorrondeguy |year=1991}}</ref>\n\n=== Latin American/Chicano hardcore punk ===\nThe Latino hardcore punk scene in the U.S. exploded during the 1990s due to all the political issues facing Latinos, such as [[California Proposition 187|Prop 187]], [[NAFTA]] and the [[Zapatista uprising in Chiapas, Mexico|Zapatista Uprising]]. Policies that specifically targeted the Latino community all across the U.S. during the 90s pushed Latinos and Latinas to begin singing and writing hardcore punk as a form of angst and protest. Bands from cites like New York, Chicago, El Paso, Texas, Los Angeles, and Santa Fe, New Mexico had prominent hardcore Latino punk bands in the 1990s. Among the most notable Latino hardcore punk bands were:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* Huasipungo \n* [[Los Crudos]]\n* Arma Contra Arma\n* Tras de Nada\n* Youth Against\n* No Less\n* Sbitch\n* Kontra Attaque\n* Subsistencia\n* Life\u2019s Halt\n* Logical Nonsense\n* Emperismo\n}}\nIn contrast to their white punk peers, these bands were discriminated against for singing about the struggles of minorities that whites did not want to hear about. Latino hardcore punk bands began to sing about the direct problems that they, their families, and their Latino communities were facing. The themes of these problems were the violation of immigrant rights; particularly the abuse of Latino immigrant workers.<ref name=\"MasAlla\" />\n\n== 1970s Latin American punk ==\n\nLittle known outside Latin America, Latin punk was a huge sensation among teens in countries like Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, and Mexico during the 1970s. These countries shared a history of dictatorship, poverty and political oppression, about which these Latin American teens began to sing and play, about adversity and oppression that they had lived and suffered under. In the late 1970s, Mexico, Argentina and Brazil all had popular punk bands well-established within their circuits. In both Mexico and Argentina specifically the punk scene was large due to affluent youth who had the means to obtain the music of bands from the United Kingdom and the U.S.\n\n*In Brazil on the other hand, Douglas Viscaino was interested in the ideology of the youth revolting against the military regime of the nation. Bands such as his {{Interlanguage link multi|Restos de Nada|pt}}, [[:pt:Coquetel_Molotov_(banda)|Coquetel Molotov]] (from Rio de Janeiro), {{Interlanguage link multi|AI-5 (Brazilian punk band)|pt|3=AI-5 (banda)|lt=AI-5}}, and N.A.I were among the founders of Brazilian punk. \n*In Argentina, the punk scene depended in the ability to travel and gain knowledge of the punk scene, due to the military regime's media censorship. Bands such as Los Testiculos, [[Los Violadores]], and others who cemented punk in Argentina were followed by bands like Los Baraja, Alerta Roja,<ref>\n{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.killfromtheheart.com/bands.php?id=3068|\ntitle=Alerta Roja|\naccessdate=October 10, 2015}}\n</ref> [[Comando Suicida]], Los Inadaptables, and Trixy y Los Maniaticos. \n*The original punk bands of Mexico, such as {{Interlanguage link multi|Size (Mexican punk band)|es|3=Size|lt=Size}}, Salida, [[Ritmo Peligroso]]<ref>\n{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.shit-fi.com/content/dangerous-rhythm|title=Ritmo Peligroso|\nauthor=shit-fi.com|\naccessdate=October 10, 2015}}\n</ref> and others, began playing music completely in English, alienating them from the mass marginalized youth of their nation. Yet in the north of Mexico punk was largely racialized with heavy influence from the United States. The 1980s would become the true fulfillment of punk in Latin America.<ref name=\"MasAlla\" />\n\n== 1980s Latin American punk ==\nBy the 1980s punk was well established in multiple nations of Latin America. Punk became a form of resistance among the youth of Latin America, in which they spoke against the establishment of their countries, which was completely dangerous. For in Chile during the 1970s the separation of rock music, and musician was one of the key points the dictatorship focused on overpowering. The youth followed the ideology of DIY, in order to create space in which created and alternative to their livelihoods.<ref>{{cite video |title=El Grito Subterr\u00e1neo |author=Julio Montero |year=1987 |publisher=Maximumrocknroll}}</ref>\n\n=== Punk in Mexico ===\n\nMexican punk had more similar roots to that of 1970s based on the fact that marginalized minorities were beginning to participate and perform. It was during this time that bands such as Massacre 68 and {{Interlanguage link multi|Rebel\u2019d|es|3=Rebel'd Punk}} began to emerge. Rebel'd was one of the most important bands, often considered the [[Ramones]] of Mexico, and has played with multiple bands such as the Ramones, the [[Dead Kennedys]] and the [[Misfits (band)|Misfits]]. In the late 1980s bands such as {{Interlanguage link multi|Esp\u00e9cimen|es|3=Esp\u00e9cimen_(banda)}}<ref>Musicbrainz info on Especimen https://musicbrainz.org/artist/3fc51e2b-bb90-47fa-b2ed-75bbdec23e67</ref> and {{Interlanguage link multi|Masacre 68|es}} were key factors in the hardcore scene.\n\n=== Punk in Colombia ===\n\nIn Colombia punk emerged amid national unrest, during an era in which there was a major war between narco-traffickers and the government of Colombia. [[Complot]] was one of the earliest bands there, and got its start playing covers of bands such as [[the Clash]], the [[Buzzcocks]] and others. Within the realms of hardcore-punk [[La Pestilencia]] and Mougue emerged as the main contenders in the style in Colombia to date.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tiusaba |first=Marcelo S |title=La improbable historia del punk rock (Colombia) |publisher=[[Blogspot]] |work=Anti and Roll: Espacio Dedicado Al Rock Latinoamericano |date=23 August 2012 |url=http://antiandroll.blogspot.com/2012/08/la-improbable-historia-del-punk-rock.html}}</ref> The epicenter of punk in Colombia was [[Bogot\u00e1]] with bands such as [[Chite]] and [[Area 12 (band)|Area 12]];<ref>{{Cite web|title = Area 12 {{!}}  {{!}} Bandas de Colombia|url = http://metalymetal.com/area12|website = metalymetal.com|access-date = 2016-02-10}}</ref> but Colombia\u2019s peripheries also had popular bands.\n\n=== Punk in Peru ===\n\nPeru is especially important to the Latino punk genre, with significant contributions in the mid-1960s with [[Los Saicos]]. Los Saicos played a key role in the genre of punk, being considered at times the first real punk band. The 1987 documentary ''El Grito Subterraneo'' (The Underground Scream), presented interviews of youth in the movement, and  outside officials trying to understand the movement, as well as performances in Peru at the time, such as {{Interlanguage link multi|Voz propia|es}}, [[Leusemia]], Eutanasia, Kaos, Flema, Narcosis, Maria Teta, Empujon Brutal, Sinkura, Guerrilla Urbana, and others.<ref>\n{{cite web|\nurl = http://maximumrocknroll.com/peruvian-punk-documentaries-el-grito-subterraneo-y-lima-explota/|\ntitle = Peruvian punk documentaries: El Grito Subterr\u00e1neo y Lima Explota|\nauthor=Maximum RockNRoll|\ndate=September 25, 2012|\naccessdate=October 10, 2015\n}}\n</ref>\n\n=== Punk in Brazil ===\n{{main|Punk in Brazil}}\nBrazil was producing mixtapes in the early 1980s with a hardcore sound, as well as an early punk festivals. Yet in the mid-1980s, between punks, skinheads, and metal head, punk began to take an early post-punk turn, with bands such as [[Inocentes]], [[Mercen\u00e1rias]] and 365.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Cojoba (band)|Cojoba]]\n*[[Mas alla de los Gritos]]\n*[[La Movida Madrile\u00f1a]]\n*[[Rock en espa\u00f1ol]]\n*[[Mexican rock]]\n*[[Avanzada Regia]]\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/15/los-saicos_n_3757986.html Los Saicos Documentary]\n*[http://huasipungo.noblogs.org/ Huasipungo]\n*[http://www.shit-fi.com/articles/LosVioladores History of Los Violadores]\n*[http://www.firstpost.com/topic/organization/queensland-roar-empirismo-demo-video-U2h6PUZNdOY-18845-1.html Emperismo demo]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZqqLRO-R3GM GRITO SUBTERR\u00c1NEO, el video. Versi\u00f3n completa]\n*[http://especimen.com.mx/ Official Especimen webpage]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Punk}}\n{{Amerisalsa}}\n\n[[Category:Latin American music]]\n[[Category:Punk rock genres]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=October 2013}}\n[[File:LEBatLolla2.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Le Butcherettes]], a Mexican punk band, performing at Lollapa