 During the late 1970s, punk's social basis for creating commonalities with its fans, and its integration of style and instruments from reggae allowed for punk bands of different ethnicities to integrate themselves into the social scene in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hebdige |first=Dick |chapter=Bleached Roots: Punks and White Ethnicity |title=Subculture, the Meaning of Style |location=London |publisher=Methuen |year=1979 |pages=62\u201372}}</ref>\n\n== Chicano/Latino Punk ==\n\nIn the late 1970s, many punk bands began appearing in Los Angeles, among them many Latino and Chicano punks like [[The Plugz]], [[Bags (Los Angeles band)|The Bags]], [[The Zeros (American band)|The Zeros]], [[Los Illegals]], Los Angelinos, Odd Squad, Felix and the Katz, the [[The Stains (LA band)|Stains]], and [[The Brat (punk band)|The Brat]]. Most of these bands did not consider themselves Latino punk bands, but artists challenging the mainstream just like their non-Latino peers.\n\nHowever, in the late 1970s Latino/Chicano punks in East L.A began organizing gigs in their own communities. These bands were part of a punk movement called The East Side Renaissance, who dedicated themselves to bringing to light the local Chicano/Latino bands in their own neighborhoods.<ref name=\"MasAlla\">{{cite video |title=Mas Alla De Los Gritos (Beyond the Screams) |author=Martin Sorrondeguy |year=1991}}</ref>\n\n=== Latin American/Chicano hardcore punk ===\nThe Latino hardcore punk scene in the U.S. exploded during the 1990s due to all the political issues facing Latinos, such as [[California Proposition 187|Prop 187]], [[NAFTA]] and the [[Zapatista uprising in Chiapas, Mexico|Zapatista Uprising]]. Policies that specifically targeted the Latino community all across the U.S. during the 90s pushed Latinos and Latinas to begin singing and writing hardcore punk as a form of angst and protest. Bands from cites like New York, Chicago, El Paso, Texas, Los Angeles, and Santa Fe, New Mexico had prominent hardcore Latino punk bands in the 1990s. Among the most notable Latino hardcore punk bands were:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* Huasipungo \n* [[Los Crudos]]\n* Arma Contra Arma\n* Tras de Nada\n* Youth Against\n* No Less\n* Sbitch\n* Kontra Attaque\n* Subsistencia\n* Life\u2019s Halt\n* Logical Nonsense\n* Emperismo\n}}\nIn contrast to their white punk peers, these bands were discriminated against for singing about the struggles of minorities that whites did not want to hear about. Latino hardcore punk bands began to sing about the direct problems that they, their families, and their Latino communities were facing. The themes of these problems were the violation of immigrant rights; particularly the abuse of Latino immigrant workers.<ref name=\"MasAlla\" />\n\n== 1970s Latin American punk ==\n\nLittle known outside Latin America, Latin punk was a huge sensation among teens in countries like Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, and Mexico during the 1970s. These countries shared a history of dictatorship, poverty and political oppression, about which these Latin American teens began to sing and play, about adversity and oppression that they had lived and suffered under. In the late 1970s, Mexico, Argentina and Brazil all had popular punk bands well-established within their circuits. In both Mexico and Argentina specifically the punk scene was large due to affluent youth who had the means to obtain the music of bands from the United Kingdom and the U.S.\n\n*In Brazil on the other hand, Douglas Viscaino was interested in the ideology of the youth revolting against the military regime of the nation. Bands such as his {{Interlanguage link multi|Restos de Nada|pt}}, [[:pt:Coquetel_Molotov_(banda)|Coquetel Molotov]] (from Rio de Janeiro), {{Interlanguage link multi|AI-5 (Brazilian punk band)|pt|3=AI-5 (banda)|lt=AI-5}}, and N.A.I were among the founders of Brazilian punk. \n*In Argentina, the punk scene depended in the ability to travel and gain knowledge of the punk scene, due to the military regime's media censorship. Bands such as Los Testiculos, [[Los Violadores]], and others who cemented punk in Argentina were followed by bands like Los Baraja, Alerta Roja,<ref>\n{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.killfromtheheart.com/bands.php?id=3068|\ntitle=Alerta Roja|\naccessdate=October 10, 2015}}\n</ref> [[Comando Suicida]], Los Inadaptables, and Trixy y Los Maniaticos. \n*The original punk bands of Mexico, such as {{Interlanguage link multi|Size (Mexican punk band)|es|3=Size|lt=Size}}, Salida, [[Ritmo Peligroso]]<ref>\n{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.shit-fi.com/content/dangerous-rhythm|title=Ritmo Peligroso|\nauthor=shit-fi.com|\naccessdate=October 10, 2015}}\n</ref> and others, began playing music completely in English, alienating them from the mass marginalized youth of their nation. Yet in the north of Mexico punk was largely racialized with heavy influence from the United States. The 1980s would become the true fulfillment of punk in Latin America.<ref name=\"MasAlla\" />\n\n== 1980s Latin American punk ==\nBy the 1980s punk was well established in multiple nations of Latin America. Punk became a form of resistance among the youth of Latin America, in which they spoke against the establishment of their countries, which was completely dangerous. For in Chile during the 1970s the separation of rock music, and musician was one of the key points the dictatorship focused on overpowering. The youth followed the ideology of DIY, in order to create space in which created and alternative to their livelihoods.<ref>{{cite video |title=El Grito Subterr\u00e1neo |author=Julio Montero |year=1987 |publisher=Maximumrocknroll}}</ref>\n\n=== Punk in Mexico ===\n\nMexican punk had more similar roots to that of 1970s based on the fact that marginalized minorities were beginning to participate and perform. It was during this time that bands such as Massacre 68 and {{Interlanguage link multi|Rebel\u2019d|es|3=Rebel'd Punk}} began to emerge. Rebel'd was one of the most important bands, often considered the [[Ramones]] of Mexico, and has played with multiple bands such as the Ramones, the [[Dead Kennedys]] and the [[Misfits (band)|Misfits]]. In the late 1980s bands such as {{Interlanguage link multi|Esp\u00e9cimen|es|3=Esp\u00e9cimen_(banda)}}<ref>Musicbrainz info on Especimen https://musicbrainz.org/artist/3fc51e2b-bb90-47fa-b2ed-75bbdec23e67</ref> and {{Interlanguage link multi|Masacre 68|es}} were key factors in the hardcore scene.\n\n=== Punk in Colombia ===\n\nIn Colombia punk emerged amid national unrest, during an era in which there was a major war between narco-traffickers and the government of Colombia. [[Complot]] was one of the earliest bands there, and got its start playing covers of bands such as [[the Clash]], the [[Buzzcocks]] and others. Within the realms of hardcore-punk [[La Pestilencia]] and Mougue emerged as the main contenders in the style in Colombia to date.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tiusaba |first=Marcelo S |title=La improbable historia del punk rock (Colombia) |publisher=[[Blogspot]] |work=Anti and Roll: Espacio Dedicado Al Rock Latinoamericano |date=23 August 2012 |url=http://antiandroll.blogspot.com/2012/08/la-improbable-historia-del-punk-rock.html}}</ref> The epicenter of punk in Colombia was [[Bogot\u00e1]] with bands such as [[Chite]] and [[Area 12 (band)|Area 12]];<ref>{{Cite web|title = Area 12 {{!}}  {{!}} Bandas de Colombia|url = http://metalymetal.com/area12|website = metalymetal.com|access-date = 2016-02-10}}</ref> but Colombia\u2019s peripheries also had popular bands.\n\n=== Punk in Peru ===\n\nPeru is especially important to the Latino punk genre, with significant contributions in the mid-1960s with [[Los Saicos]]. Los Saicos played a key role in the genre of punk, being considered at times the first real punk band. The 1987 documentary ''El Grito Subterraneo'' (The Underground Scream), presented interviews of youth in the movement, and  outside officials trying to understand the movement, as well as performances in Peru at the time, such as {{Interlanguage link multi|Voz propia|es}}, [[Leusemia]], Eutanasia, Kaos, Flema, Narcosis, Maria Teta, Empujon Brutal, Sinkura, Guerrilla Urbana, and others.<ref>\n{{cite web|\nurl = http://maximumrocknroll.com/peruvian-punk-documentaries-el-grito-subterraneo-y-lima-explota/|\ntitle = Peruvian punk documentaries: El Grito Subterr\u00e1neo y Lima Explota|\nauthor=Maximum RockNRoll|\ndate=September 25, 2012|\naccessdate=October 10, 2015\n}}\n</ref>\n\n=== Punk in Brazil ===\n{{main|Punk in Brazil}}\nBrazil was producing mixtapes in the early 1980s with a hardcore sound, as well as an early punk festivals. Yet in the mid-1980s, between punks, skinheads, and metal head, punk began to take an early post-punk turn, with bands such as [[Inocentes]], [[Mercen\u00e1rias]] and 365.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Cojoba (band)|Cojoba]]\n*[[Mas alla de los Gritos]]\n*[[La Movida Madrile\u00f1a]]\n*[[Rock en espa\u00f1ol]]\n*[[Mexican rock]]\n*[[Avanzada Regia]]\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/15/los-saicos_n_3757986.html Los Saicos Documentary]\n*[http://huasipungo.noblogs.org/ Huasipungo]\n*[http://www.shit-fi.com/articles/LosVioladores History of Los Violadores]\n*[http://www.firstpost.com/topic/organization/queensland-roar-empirismo-demo-video-U2h6PUZNdOY-18845-1.html Emperismo demo]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZqqLRO-R3GM GRITO SUBTERR\u00c1NEO, el video. Versi\u00f3n completa]\n*[http://especimen.com.mx/ Official Especimen webpage]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Punk}}\n{{Amerisalsa}}\n\n[[Category:Latin American music]]\n[[Category:Punk rock genres]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLatino(link changed toLatin Americans) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latino_punk"}
